var ZHONGKAO_DATA = {"textbook":"初中考纲","units":[{"name":"人体昼夜节律","entries":[{"cn":"早晨，上午","en":"morning","type":"word"},{"cn":"早餐","en":"breakfast","type":"word"},{"cn":"家庭；家族；家人","en":"family","type":"word"},{"cn":"学校；上学","en":"school","type":"word"},{"cn":"〔基督教〕教友会[公谊会]教友","en":"friend","type":"word"},{"cn":"幸福的;快乐的,高兴的","en":"happy","type":"word"},{"cn":"教师；老师","en":"teacher","type":"word"},{"cn":"回答；答复；答案；回(信)；回答；答复；回(信)","en":"answer","type":"word"},{"cn":"困难的；费力的","en":"difficult","type":"word"},{"cn":"帮助,帮忙","en":"help","type":"word"},{"cn":"午餐；午饭","en":"lunch","type":"word"},{"cn":"公园 停放(车辆等)","en":"park","type":"word"},{"cn":"下午","en":"afternoon","type":"word"},{"cn":"游戏；运动；比赛","en":"game","type":"word"},{"cn":"赢；获胜","en":"win","type":"word"},{"cn":"疲劳的；累的","en":"tired","type":"word"},{"cn":"家；在家;到家;回家","en":"home","type":"word"},{"cn":"正餐","en":"dinner","type":"word"},{"cn":"故事；小说","en":"story","type":"word"},{"cn":"记得；想起","en":"remember","type":"word"},{"cn":"明天","en":"tomorrow","type":"word"},{"cn":"梦;梦想","en":"dream","type":"word"},{"cn":"脑","en":"brain","type":"word"},{"cn":"睡觉","en":"sleep","type":"word"},{"cn":"精力;能量","en":"energy","type":"word"}],"passage":{"title":"How Your Body Runs the Day","html":"<p>Every <b>morning</b>, sunlight signals a gland deep inside your <b>brain</b> to stop producing melatonin — the hormone that <b class=\"gs\">keeps you asleep</b>. This is why you wake naturally at roughly the same hour each day. Scientists have found that <b class=\"gs\">eating a good</b> <b>breakfast</b> provides the <b>energy</b> your body needs for <b class=\"gs\">concentration and memory</b>. <b>Family</b> members who eat together <b class=\"gs\">tend to share</b> similar biological rhythms. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>At <b>school</b>, your brain <b class=\"gs\">works like</b> an electrical network. When a <b>teacher</b> <b class=\"gs\">asks a question</b>, billions of neurons coordinate to retrieve the <b>answer</b>. If the material feels <b>difficult</b>, do not be discouraged — neuroscientists have shown that mental struggle <b class=\"gs\">strengthens neural pathways</b>. When a <b>friend</b> <b class=\"gs\">offers to help</b>, your brain releases oxytocin, a chemical that <b class=\"gs\">builds trust and reduces anxiety</b>. This is why students often feel <b>happy</b> after studying together. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>At <b>lunch</b>, your digestive system <b class=\"gs\">converts food into</b> glucose. Without adequate fuel, concentration <b class=\"gs\">drops sharply</b> in the <b>afternoon</b>. Physical activity helps: if you spend time in a <b>park</b> or play a <b>game</b>, your heart <b class=\"gs\">pumps oxygen-rich blood</b> to the brain. The desire to <b>win</b> <b class=\"gs\">triggers the release of</b> dopamine, a chemical that <b class=\"gs\">motivates continued effort</b>. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>By evening, a substance called adenosine <b class=\"gs\">builds up in your bloodstream</b>, making you feel <b>tired</b>. This is your brain <b class=\"gs\">sending a clear signal</b> to prepare for <b>sleep</b>. Eating <b>dinner</b> with people you care about <b class=\"gs\">lowers stress hormones</b>. During deep sleep, your brain <b class=\"gs\">replays experiences like a</b> <b>story</b>, <b class=\"gs\">moving important information</b> into long-term storage. This process is why you <b>remember</b> things better after rest. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>Your most vivid <b>dream</b>s occur during REM sleep, when brain activity <b class=\"gs\">becomes nearly as intense as</b> when awake. By <b>tomorrow</b> morning, the cycle resets — your body, without conscious effort, is ready for another day of learning and growing. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p>"}},{"name":"水循环之旅","entries":[{"cn":"水 浇水","en":"water","type":"word"},{"cn":"海洋","en":"ocean","type":"word"},{"cn":"太阳；阳光","en":"sun","type":"word"},{"cn":"云","en":"cloud","type":"word"},{"cn":"雨，雨水","en":"rain","type":"word"},{"cn":"江，河","en":"river","type":"word"},{"cn":"雪","en":"snow","type":"word"},{"cn":"冰","en":"ice","type":"word"},{"cn":"地球;土,泥;大地","en":"earth","type":"word"},{"cn":"上升；升起；起床","en":"rise","type":"word"},{"cn":"落下；降落；倒下；跌倒","en":"fall","type":"word"},{"cn":"形式；方式","en":"form","type":"word"},{"cn":"新鲜的","en":"fresh","type":"word"},{"cn":"盐","en":"salt","type":"word"},{"cn":"喝;饮 饮料;喝酒","en":"drink","type":"word"},{"cn":"空气；大气","en":"air","type":"word"},{"cn":"温度","en":"temperature","type":"word"},{"cn":"天气﹔气象","en":"weather","type":"word"},{"cn":"山；山脉","en":"mountain","type":"word"},{"cn":"地面","en":"ground","type":"word"},{"cn":"天空；天","en":"sky","type":"word"},{"cn":"旅行；游历","en":"travel","type":"word"},{"cn":"变得；成为","en":"become","type":"word"},{"cn":"滴 掉下,落下;扔掉;放弃","en":"drop","type":"word"},{"cn":"循环（周期）；自行车﹔摩托车","en":"cycle","type":"word"}],"passage":{"title":"The Water Cycle","html":"<p>The <b>water</b> on <b>earth</b> has been <b>travel</b>ing through an endless <b>cycle</b> for billions of years. When the <b>sun</b> <b class=\"gs\">heats the surface</b> of the <b>ocean</b>, liquid water <b class=\"gs\">turns into</b> invisible vapor and begins to <b>rise</b> into the <b>air</b>. This process, called evaporation, <b class=\"gs\">separates pure water from</b> dissolved <b>salt</b> — the salt <b class=\"gs\">stays behind</b> while <b>fresh</b> vapor lifts upward. When this vapor reaches cooler <b>temperature</b>s high in the <b>sky</b>, it <b class=\"gs\">condenses around</b> tiny dust particles to <b>form</b> a <b>cloud</b>. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>As a <b>cloud</b> <b class=\"gs\">grows heavier</b>, water droplets <b class=\"gs\">combine until they</b> <b>fall</b> back to the surface as <b>rain</b> — or as <b>snow</b> if the <b>air</b> below is cold enough. Most <b>rain</b> <b>drop</b>s <b class=\"gs\">land directly in</b> the <b>ocean</b>, completing a short <b>cycle</b>. But some <b>fall</b> onto <b>mountain</b> slopes, where they <b class=\"gs\">feed streams and</b> <b>river</b>s that <b class=\"gs\">carve paths through</b> the <b>ground</b> over thousands of years. As water flows downhill, it <b class=\"gs\">picks up tiny particles</b> of rock and soil — which is why <b>fresh</b> <b>river</b> water tastes different from pure <b>rain</b>. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>Not all <b>water</b> <b>travel</b>s quickly. Some <b class=\"gs\">seeps deep into</b> the <b>ground</b>, filling underground reservoirs called aquifers. This groundwater can <b class=\"gs\">remain stored for</b> centuries before <b class=\"gs\">emerging at springs</b> or being pumped up for people to <b>drink</b>. In cold regions, <b>water</b> may <b>become</b> trapped as <b>ice</b> in glaciers for thousands of years. Scientists studying ancient <b>ice</b> layers <b class=\"gs\">have reconstructed climate records</b> going back hundreds of thousands of years, revealing how <b>temperature</b> and <b>weather</b> patterns have shifted. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>Living things <b class=\"gs\">play a crucial role</b> in the <b>cycle</b> too. Plants <b class=\"gs\">draw water from</b> the <b>ground</b> through their roots and release it back into the <b>air</b> through tiny pores in their leaves — a single large tree can <b class=\"gs\">release hundreds of liters</b> of vapor on a warm day. Animals, including humans, <b>drink</b> <b>water</b> and <b class=\"gs\">return it to the environment</b> through breathing and waste. Even the <b>weather</b> you experience — humidity, fog, morning dew — is a direct expression of <b>water</b> <b class=\"gs\">moving through its endless</b> <b>cycle</b>. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>The same molecules that <b>fall</b> as <b>rain</b> today may have once <b class=\"gs\">flowed through an ancient</b> <b>river</b>, <b>become</b> part of a dinosaur's body, or rested as <b>snow</b> on a prehistoric <b>mountain</b>. The <b>earth</b>'s <b>water</b> is essentially a closed system — almost no new <b>water</b> <b class=\"gs\">arrives from space</b>, and almost none escapes. Every glass you <b>drink</b> <b class=\"gs\">has traveled through</b> <b>ocean</b>s, <b>cloud</b>s, <b>ice</b> caps, and living organisms for billions of years. The journey never ends. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p>"}},{"name":"叶子为什么变色","entries":[{"cn":"叶子；（书籍等的）一张；扇页 vi. 生叶；翻书页 vt. 翻…的页，匆匆翻阅 n. (Leaf)人名；(英","en":"leaf","type":"word"},{"cn":"绿色；绿色的;青的","en":"green","type":"word"},{"cn":"颜色  涂色","en":"colour","type":"word"},{"cn":"秋天，秋季","en":"autumn","type":"word"},{"cn":"树","en":"tree","type":"word"},{"cn":"光；灯光","en":"light","type":"word"},{"cn":"太阳；阳光","en":"sun","type":"word"},{"cn":"种植；播种 植物","en":"plant","type":"word"},{"cn":"食物，食品","en":"food","type":"word"},{"cn":"精力;能量","en":"energy","type":"word"},{"cn":"冬天；冬季","en":"winter","type":"word"},{"cn":"春天﹐春季","en":"spring","type":"word"},{"cn":"夏天；夏季","en":"summer","type":"word"},{"cn":"落下；降落；倒下；跌倒","en":"fall","type":"word"},{"cn":"温暖的；暖和的","en":"warm","type":"word"},{"cn":"冷的，寒冷的  寒冷；感冒","en":"cold","type":"word"},{"cn":"改变；更换；兑换；n. 零钱；变化","en":"change","type":"word"},{"cn":"打破(断、碎)；损坏；休息；间隙","en":"break","type":"word"},{"cn":"化学品；化学的","en":"chemical","type":"word"},{"cn":"生产；产生；制造","en":"produce","type":"word"},{"cn":"明亮的；聪明的；灿烂的","en":"bright","type":"word"},{"cn":"黄色的 黄色","en":"yellow","type":"word"},{"cn":"红色的 红色","en":"red","type":"word"},{"cn":"橘子，橙；橙色","en":"orange","type":"word"},{"cn":"死","en":"die","type":"word"}],"passage":{"title":"Why Leaves Change Color","html":"<p>Every <b>autumn</b>, millions of <b>tree</b>s across the northern hemisphere put on a spectacular show, transforming from deep <b>green</b> into brilliant shades of <b>yellow</b>, <b>orange</b>, and <b>red</b>. This <b>colour</b> <b>change</b> is not random — it is the visible result of a precise <b>chemical</b> process that <b class=\"gs\">has been finely tuned</b> by evolution. During <b>spring</b> and <b>summer</b>, <b>leaf</b> cells are packed with chlorophyll, the pigment that <b class=\"gs\">captures energy from</b> <b>sun</b><b>light</b> to <b>produce</b> <b>food</b> for the <b>plant</b>. Chlorophyll is so abundant that it <b class=\"gs\">masks all other</b> pigments present in the <b>leaf</b>. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>As days grow shorter and <b>cold</b>er in <b>autumn</b>, <b>tree</b>s receive a <b>chemical</b> signal to <b class=\"gs\">prepare for</b> <b>winter</b>. A layer of corky cells <b class=\"gs\">forms at the base</b> of each <b>leaf</b> stem, gradually <b class=\"gs\">cutting off the flow of</b> water and nutrients. With the supply line blocked, chlorophyll begins to <b>break</b> down and <b class=\"gs\">is not replaced</b>. As the dominant <b>green</b> fades, other pigments that were there all along — carotenoids — <b class=\"gs\">become visible for</b> the first time, revealing their warm <b>yellow</b> and <b>orange</b> hues. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>The vivid <b>red</b>s and purples that appear in some species, like maples, <b class=\"gs\">come from an entirely different</b> <b>chemical</b> process. As chlorophyll <b class=\"gs\">breaks down</b>, sugars <b class=\"gs\">become trapped in</b> the <b>leaf</b>. In the presence of <b>bright</b> <b>sun</b><b>light</b> and <b>cold</b> nights, these sugars <b class=\"gs\">are converted into</b> anthocyanins — the same pigments that give <b>red</b> apples and purple grapes their <b>colour</b>. Scientists believe this extra <b>chemical</b> step <b class=\"gs\">may protect the</b> <b>leaf</b> from <b>sun</b> damage while the <b>tree</b> <b class=\"gs\">reabsorbs valuable</b> nutrients. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p><b>Weather</b> <b class=\"gs\">plays a decisive role</b> in how spectacular the display <b class=\"gs\">turns out to be</b>. A <b>warm</b>, wet <b>spring</b> followed by a <b>summer</b> with adequate moisture, then <b>autumn</b> days full of <b>bright</b> <b>sun</b><b>light</b> and crisp <b>cold</b> nights — these conditions <b>produce</b> the most intense <b>colour</b>s. If <b>autumn</b> is too <b>warm</b> or too cloudy, the <b>red</b>s <b class=\"gs\">fail to develop fully</b>, and the display is dominated by <b>yellow</b>s and browns. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>Eventually, the <b class=\"gs\">sealed-off</b> <b>leaf</b> <b class=\"gs\">can no longer hold on</b>. A gentle breeze or a <b>cold</b> night is enough to send it drifting to the <b>ground</b>, where it will decompose and <b class=\"gs\">return its nutrients to</b> the soil. The bare branches wait through <b>winter</b> until <b>spring</b> returns, when new buds <b class=\"gs\">burst open with</b> fresh <b>green</b> <b>leaf</b>s — and the entire <b>cycle</b> begins again. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p>"}},{"name":"地震如何发生","entries":[{"cn":"地震","en":"earthquake","type":"word"},{"cn":"地球;土,泥;大地","en":"earth","type":"word"},{"cn":"地面","en":"ground","type":"word"},{"cn":"移动，搬动；搬家；感动","en":"move","type":"word"},{"cn":"岩石；摇滚乐","en":"rock","type":"word"},{"cn":"盘子；碟子；板；牌","en":"plate","type":"word"},{"cn":"表面；表层","en":"surface","type":"word"},{"cn":"精力;能量","en":"energy","type":"word"},{"cn":"波动；波浪；高潮；挥手示意；卷曲 vt. 卷（烫）发；向…挥手示意；使成波浪形 vi.","en":"wave","type":"word"},{"cn":"摇动；哆嗦 vt. 动摇；","en":"shake","type":"word"},{"cn":"打破(断、碎)；损坏；休息；间隙","en":"break","type":"word"},{"cn":"深的","en":"deep","type":"word"},{"cn":"建筑；建造","en":"build","type":"word"},{"cn":"压力；","en":"pressure","type":"word"},{"cn":"海洋","en":"ocean","type":"word"},{"cn":"山；山脉","en":"mountain","type":"word"},{"cn":"，办法","en":"measure","type":"word"},{"cn":"破坏；损害","en":"damage","type":"word"},{"cn":"安全的；平安的；无危险的","en":"safe","type":"word"},{"cn":"危险","en":"danger","type":"word"},{"cn":"(偶然)发生;碰巧","en":"happen","type":"word"},{"cn":"突然发生的事 adj. 突然的，意外的；快速的","en":"sudden","type":"word"},{"cn":"原因，起因；促使；引起","en":"cause","type":"word"},{"cn":"落下；降落；倒下；跌倒","en":"fall","type":"word"},{"cn":"强壮的；坚强的","en":"strong","type":"word"}],"passage":{"title":"How Earthquakes Happen","html":"<p>An <b>earthquake</b> is one of the most powerful demonstrations of the <b>earth</b>'s dynamic nature. It <b>happen</b>s because the <b>earth</b>'s outer shell is not a single solid piece — it is <b class=\"gs\">divided into enormous</b> slabs called tectonic <b>plate</b>s that float on a layer of semi-molten <b>rock</b> <b>deep</b> beneath the <b>surface</b>. These <b>plate</b>s are constantly in <b>move</b>ment, though at about the same speed your fingernails grow — a few centimeters per year. The <b>energy</b> that drives them <b class=\"gs\">comes from heat</b> rising from the <b>earth</b>'s core. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>As <b>plate</b>s <b>move</b>, their edges <b class=\"gs\">do not slide past each other</b> smoothly. Friction <b class=\"gs\">locks them together</b> along fault lines, and <b>pressure</b> <b class=\"gs\">builds up over</b> decades or even centuries. The <b>rock</b> <b class=\"gs\">bends and stores</b> elastic <b>energy</b> — much like a stretched rubber band. When the accumulated <b>pressure</b> finally <b class=\"gs\">overcomes the friction</b>, the <b>rock</b> <b>break</b>s with a <b>sudden</b>, violent snap. This <b class=\"gs\">releases the stored</b> <b>energy</b> in the form of seismic <b>wave</b>s that <b>shake</b> the <b>ground</b> in all directions. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>The point <b>deep</b> underground where the <b>rock</b> first <b>break</b>s is called the focus, and the spot directly above it on the <b>surface</b> is the epicenter. The <b>strong</b>est <b>shake</b>ing <b class=\"gs\">is usually felt</b> at the epicenter. Scientists <b class=\"gs\">use sensitive instruments</b> called seismographs to <b>measure</b> the <b>wave</b>s and <b class=\"gs\">calculate the magnitude</b> — the amount of <b>energy</b> released. A <b>strong</b> <b>earthquake</b> can <b class=\"gs\">release as much energy as</b> thousands of nuclear bombs, enough to <b>cause</b> widespread <b>damage</b>. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>The most <b>danger</b>ous <b>earthquake</b>s often <b>happen</b> at subduction zones, where one <b>plate</b> <b class=\"gs\">dives beneath another</b>. These zones, found mainly around the Pacific <b>ocean</b> in the so-called Ring of Fire, also <b class=\"gs\">give rise to</b> <b>mountain</b> ranges and volcanic activity. When an <b>earthquake</b> <b class=\"gs\">strikes beneath the</b> <b>ocean</b> floor, it can <b>cause</b> a tsunami — a series of enormous <b>wave</b>s that <b class=\"gs\">travel at the speed of</b> a jet plane across the open sea, then <b class=\"gs\">rise to destructive heights</b> as they approach the shore. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>While we cannot prevent <b>earthquake</b>s, we can <b class=\"gs\">reduce the</b> <b>damage</b> they <b>cause</b>. Engineers now <b>build</b> structures that <b class=\"gs\">sway with the</b> <b>shake</b>ing rather than resisting it, and early warning systems can <b class=\"gs\">detect the first</b> <b>wave</b>s and send alerts seconds before the most <b>strong</b> <b>shake</b>ing arrives — enough time to stop trains, shut off gas lines, and move people to <b>safe</b>r locations. In <b>earthquake</b>-prone regions, knowing what to do — <b class=\"gs\">drop, cover, and hold on</b> — can <b class=\"gs\">make the difference between</b> life and death. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p>"}},{"name":"蜜蜂的社会","entries":[{"cn":"蜜蜂","en":"bee","type":"word"},{"cn":"皇后；女王","en":"queen","type":"word"},{"cn":"工作者﹔工作人员","en":"worker","type":"word"},{"cn":"虫","en":"insect","type":"word"},{"cn":"花","en":"flower","type":"word"},{"cn":"蜂蜜","en":"honey","type":"word"},{"cn":"食物，食品","en":"food","type":"word"},{"cn":"收集，采集","en":"collect","type":"word"},{"cn":"建筑；建造","en":"build","type":"word"},{"cn":"蜡；蜡状物 adj. 蜡制的；似蜡的 vt. 给…上蜡 vi. 月亮渐满；增大 n. (Wax)人名；(德","en":"wax","type":"word"},{"cn":"细胞；电池；蜂房的巢室；单人小室 vi. 住在牢房或小室中 n. (Cell)人名；(英)塞尔","en":"cell","type":"word"},{"cn":"蛋;卵","en":"egg","type":"word"},{"cn":"拉尔瓦","en":"larva","type":"word"},{"cn":"喂养；饲养","en":"feed","type":"word"},{"cn":"生;发育;种植;变成","en":"grow","type":"word"},{"cn":"翼；翅膀；飞翔；派别；侧厅，耳房，厢房 vt. 使飞；飞过；空运；增加…速度；装以翼 vi. 飞行","en":"wing","type":"word"},{"cn":"飞，飞行；乘飞机旅行；(旗帜等)飘动；放(风筝、飞机模型等) 飞行；苍蝇","en":"fly","type":"word"},{"cn":"跳舞","en":"dance","type":"word"},{"cn":"交流；交际","en":"communicate","type":"word"},{"cn":"闻；嗅；发出气味","en":"smell","type":"word"},{"cn":"找到；发现；发觉","en":"find","type":"word"},{"cn":"千","en":"thousand","type":"word"},{"cn":"生活；居住；活着","en":"live","type":"word"},{"cn":"保护","en":"protect","type":"word"},{"cn":"生产；产生；制造","en":"produce","type":"word"}],"passage":{"title":"The Society of Honeybees","html":"<p>A <b>bee</b>hive is one of the most remarkable societies in the <b>insect</b> world, where tens of <b>thousand</b>s of individuals <b>live</b> and work together in perfect coordination. At the center of this society is a single <b>queen</b>, whose sole job is to <b class=\"gs\">lay up to</b> two <b>thousand</b> <b>egg</b>s per day during peak season. Every other <b>bee</b> in the colony is a <b>worker</b> — a female who <b class=\"gs\">takes on different roles</b> as she ages, from cleaning <b>cell</b>s, to <b>feed</b>ing <b>larva</b>e, to <b>build</b>ing <b class=\"gs\">the intricate</b> <b>wax</b> comb, to <b>fly</b>ing out to <b>collect</b> <b>food</b>. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>The <b>bee</b>s' ability to <b>find</b> the best <b>flower</b>s and <b>communicate</b> their location is one of nature's great wonders. When a scout <b>bee</b> discovers a rich source of nectar, she returns to the hive and performs a <b class=\"gs\">remarkable figure-eight movement</b> called the waggle <b>dance</b>. The angle of the <b>dance</b> relative to the sun <b class=\"gs\">tells other bees the direction</b> to <b>fly</b>, while the duration of the waggle <b class=\"gs\">indicates the distance</b>. Researchers have confirmed that <b>bee</b>s can <b class=\"gs\">encode locations up to</b> several kilometers away using this <b class=\"gs\">sophisticated symbolic language</b>. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>Once <b>worker</b> <b>bee</b>s arrive at the <b>flower</b>s, they use their long tongues to <b class=\"gs\">suck up nectar</b> and store it in a special stomach. Pollen <b class=\"gs\">sticks to their fuzzy bodies</b> and is packed into baskets on their legs. Back at the hive, the nectar is <b class=\"gs\">passed from bee to bee</b>, each <b class=\"gs\">adding enzymes that transform</b> it from a thin sugary liquid into thick, golden <b>honey</b>. The <b>bee</b>s then <b class=\"gs\">fan their</b> <b>wing</b>s to evaporate excess water until the <b>honey</b> is perfectly preserved — it can last for years without spoiling. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>The hive itself is an engineering masterpiece. <b>Worker</b> <b>bee</b>s <b>produce</b> tiny flakes of <b>wax</b> from glands on their abdomens and <b class=\"gs\">shape them into</b> hexagonal <b>cell</b>s. This hexagonal pattern is mathematically optimal — it <b class=\"gs\">uses the least amount of</b> <b>wax</b> to store the most <b>honey</b>. Some <b>cell</b>s are reserved for <b class=\"gs\">raising young</b>: the <b>queen</b> deposits a single <b>egg</b> in each, and when the <b>egg</b> hatches three days later, <b>worker</b>s begin <b>feed</b>ing the <b>larva</b> <b class=\"gs\">a protein-rich secretion</b> that helps it <b>grow</b> rapidly. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>A healthy hive <b class=\"gs\">holds together through</b> <b>smell</b> — each colony has a unique <b>chemical</b> signature that allows guard <b>bee</b>s to <b class=\"gs\">identify intruders instantly</b> and <b>protect</b> the entrance. The colony <b>live</b>s as a single superorganism: no individual <b>bee</b> can <b>live</b> alone for <b>long</b>, but together they <b class=\"gs\">accomplish feats that</b> continue to amaze scientists — from <b class=\"gs\">regulating the hive's temperature</b> to within half a degree, to collectively deciding <b class=\"gs\">when and where to relocate</b>, to <b>produce</b>ing enough <b>honey</b> to sustain tens of <b>thousand</b>s of lives through the <b>winter</b>. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p>"}},{"name":"四季的形成","entries":[{"cn":"季节；季","en":"season","type":"word"},{"cn":"地球;土,泥;大地","en":"earth","type":"word"},{"cn":"太阳；阳光","en":"sun","type":"word"},{"cn":"夏天；夏季","en":"summer","type":"word"},{"cn":"冬天；冬季","en":"winter","type":"word"},{"cn":"春天﹐春季","en":"spring","type":"word"},{"cn":"秋天，秋季","en":"autumn","type":"word"},{"cn":"倾斜 vt. 使倾斜；使翘起 vi. 倾斜；翘起；以言词或文字抨击 n. (Tilt)人","en":"tilt","type":"word"},{"cn":"轴；轴线；轴心国","en":"axis","type":"word"},{"cn":"北的；朝北的；北方的","en":"north","type":"word"},{"cn":"南；南方","en":"south","type":"word"},{"cn":"半球","en":"hemisphere","type":"word"},{"cn":"，指挥","en":"direct","type":"word"},{"cn":"角度，角，方面 vi. 钓鱼；谋取","en":"angle","type":"word"},{"cn":"冷的，寒冷的  寒冷；感冒","en":"cold","type":"word"},{"cn":"温暖的；暖和的","en":"warm","type":"word"},{"cn":"(一)天，(一)日；白天","en":"day","type":"word"},{"cn":"夜；夜间","en":"night","type":"word"},{"cn":"(时间)长的；(距离)远的","en":"long","type":"word"},{"cn":"短的；矮的","en":"short","type":"word"},{"cn":"改变；更换；兑换；n. 零钱；变化","en":"change","type":"word"},{"cn":"天气﹔气象","en":"weather","type":"word"},{"cn":"温度","en":"temperature","type":"word"},{"cn":"杆；极点；电极 n. (Pole)人名；(英)波尔；(俄)波列；(塞)波莱 vt. 用竿支撑","en":"pole","type":"word"},{"cn":"光；灯光","en":"light","type":"word"}],"passage":{"title":"Why We Have Seasons","html":"<p>The four <b>season</b>s — <b>spring</b>, <b>summer</b>, <b>autumn</b>, and <b>winter</b> — are not <b class=\"gs\">caused by changes in</b> the <b>earth</b>'s distance from the <b>sun</b>, as many people believe. In fact, the <b>earth</b> is actually closest to the <b>sun</b> during the northern hemisphere's <b>winter</b>. The true <b class=\"gs\">cause of the</b> <b>season</b>s is the <b>earth</b>'s <b>axis</b> <b>tilt</b> — our planet <b class=\"gs\">spins at an</b> <b>angle</b> of approximately 23.5 degrees relative to its orbit. This <b>tilt</b> <b class=\"gs\">remains fixed in</b> <b>direction</b> as the <b>earth</b> <b class=\"gs\">travels around the</b> <b>sun</b>. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>During the <b>north</b>ern <b>hemisphere</b>'s <b>summer</b>, the <b>north</b> <b>pole</b> <b class=\"gs\">tilts toward the</b> <b>sun</b>. Sun<b>light</b> <b class=\"gs\">strikes this part of</b> the <b>earth</b> at a more <b>direct</b> <b>angle</b>, <b class=\"gs\">concentrating more energy on</b> each square meter of <b>ground</b>. The <b>day</b>s <b class=\"gs\">become noticeably</b> <b>long</b>er, sometimes lasting more than fifteen hours, and <b>temperature</b>s <b class=\"gs\">climb steadily</b>. Meanwhile, the <b>south</b>ern <b>hemisphere</b> experiences <b>winter</b> — the <b>sun</b>'s rays <b class=\"gs\">arrive at a shallow</b> <b>angle</b>, spreading the same <b>energy</b> over a larger area, and the <b>day</b>s <b class=\"gs\">shrink to their</b> <b>short</b>est. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>As the <b>earth</b> <b class=\"gs\">continues its orbit</b>, the <b>tilt</b> <b class=\"gs\">gradually shifts the</b> <b>direct</b> rays from the <b>north</b>ern <b>hemisphere</b> toward the equator and then into the <b>south</b>ern <b>hemisphere</b>. This <b class=\"gs\">produces the transitional</b> <b>season</b>s: <b>spring</b> and <b>autumn</b>. During these periods, <b>day</b> and <b>night</b> <b class=\"gs\">are roughly equal</b> in <b>long</b>th — a phenomenon called the equinox. The <b>weather</b> <b class=\"gs\">becomes more moderate</b>, <b>temperature</b>s <b>change</b> rapidly, and life <b class=\"gs\">responds with remarkable precision</b>: <b>plant</b>s bloom in <b>spring</b> and <b class=\"gs\">shed their leaves in</b> <b>autumn</b>. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>At the <b>pole</b>s, the <b class=\"gs\">effects are extreme</b>. The <b>north</b> <b>pole</b> experiences continuous <b>day</b><b>light</b> for six months during <b>summer</b>, followed by six months of <b>dark</b>ness in <b>winter</b>. These dramatic <b>change</b>s <b class=\"gs\">shape entire ecosystems</b>, from the <b class=\"gs\">mass migration of</b> animals to the <b class=\"gs\">growth cycles of</b> <b>plant</b>s. The <b>season</b>s are not merely a <b>weather</b> pattern — they are a fundamental rhythm that <b class=\"gs\">has driven the evolution of</b> <b class=\"gs\">life on</b> <b>earth</b> for hundreds of millions of years. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p>"}},{"name":"疫苗的工作原理","entries":[{"cn":"疫苗；牛痘苗 adj. 疫苗的；牛痘的","en":"vaccine","type":"word"},{"cn":"身体","en":"body","type":"word"},{"cn":"免疫者；免除者 adj. 免疫的；免于……的，免除的","en":"immune","type":"word"},{"cn":"病，[医] 疾病；弊病 vt. 传染；使…有病","en":"disease","type":"word"},{"cn":"比鲁斯","en":"virus","type":"word"},{"cn":"细胞；电池；蜂房的巢室；单人小室 vi. 住在牢房或小室中 n. (Cell)人名；(英)塞尔","en":"cell","type":"word"},{"cn":"保护","en":"protect","type":"word"},{"cn":"回忆；记忆","en":"memory","type":"word"},{"cn":"弱的；虚弱的","en":"weak","type":"word"},{"cn":"强壮的；坚强的","en":"strong","type":"word"},{"cn":"打仗；打架；争论","en":"fight","type":"word"},{"cn":"安全的；平安的；无危险的","en":"safe","type":"word"},{"cn":"药","en":"medicine","type":"word"},{"cn":"医生","en":"doctor","type":"word"},{"cn":"健康","en":"health","type":"word"},{"cn":"注入；注射","en":"inject","type":"word"},{"cn":"认出；承认，认可；识别","en":"recognise","type":"word"},{"cn":"进攻，袭击","en":"attack","type":"word"},{"cn":"生产；产生；制造","en":"produce","type":"word"},{"cn":"抗体","en":"antibody","type":"word"},{"cn":"防止，预防；阻止，阻挡","en":"prevent","type":"word"},{"cn":"，差额","en":"spread","type":"word"},{"cn":"杀死，弄死","en":"kill","type":"word"},{"cn":"有病的;不健康的","en":"ill","type":"word"},{"cn":"制度，体制；系统；方法","en":"system","type":"word"}],"passage":{"title":"How Vaccines Work","html":"<p>A <b>vaccine</b> is one of the greatest achievements in the history of <b>medicine</b>. Its <b class=\"gs\">fundamental principle is</b> brilliantly simple: <b class=\"gs\">teach the</b> <b>body</b>'s <b>immune</b> <b>system</b> to <b>recognise</b> and <b>fight</b> a dangerous <b>disease</b> without ever <b class=\"gs\">exposing it to</b> the real threat. To understand how <b>vaccine</b>s work, we must first understand that our <b>body</b> <b class=\"gs\">is constantly patrolled by</b> specialized white blood <b>cell</b>s that <b class=\"gs\">hunt down anything</b> they do not <b>recognise</b> — including <b>virus</b>es and bacteria. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>When a <b>vaccine</b> is <b class=\"gs\">introduced into the</b> <b>body</b> — usually through an <b class=\"gs\">injection in the</b> arm — it <b class=\"gs\">contains either weakened</b> or inactivated pieces of a <b>virus</b>, or even just <b class=\"gs\">fragments of its</b> genetic material. These pieces cannot <b>cause</b> the actual <b>disease</b> because they are too <b>weak</b> or <b class=\"gs\">have been killed</b>. However, they are <b class=\"gs\">still recognizable enough</b> for the <b>immune</b> <b>system</b> to <b class=\"gs\">treat them as</b> an invader and mount a <b class=\"gs\">full defensive response</b>. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>During this <b>safe</b> practice <b>attack</b>, specialized <b>cell</b>s <b>produce</b> proteins called <b>antibody</b> molecules — each one <b class=\"gs\">perfectly shaped to latch onto</b> that specific <b>virus</b>. After the harmless invader <b class=\"gs\">has been cleared</b>, most of the <b>immune</b> <b>cell</b>s <b class=\"gs\">die off naturally</b>. But a small number <b class=\"gs\">remain in the</b> <b>body</b> as <b>memory</b> <b>cell</b>s — some <b class=\"gs\">patrolling for decades</b>, ready to <b>recognise</b> the same <b>virus</b> instantly if it ever appears again. This is why a <b class=\"gs\">vaccinated person can</b> <b>fight</b> off the real <b>disease</b> so effectively. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>The <b class=\"gs\">power of vaccination goes beyond</b> individual <b>protect</b>ion. When <b class=\"gs\">enough people in</b> a population <b class=\"gs\">develop immunity through</b> <b>vaccine</b>s, the <b>disease</b> <b class=\"gs\">can no longer</b> <b>spread</b> easily from person to person — a phenomenon called herd immunity. This <b>protect</b>s those who cannot receive <b>vaccine</b>s, including very <b>ill</b> patients and newborns. The <b>memory</b> <b>cell</b>s created by <b>vaccine</b>s have <b class=\"gs\">saved more lives than</b> any other <b>medical</b> invention in human history, <b class=\"gs\">turning once-feared diseases into</b> <b class=\"gs\">preventable conditions</b>. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p>"}},{"name":"天空为什么是蓝的","entries":[{"cn":"天空；天","en":"sky","type":"word"},{"cn":"蓝色选手〔指牛津或剑桥大学校队运动员〕﹔蓝色（选手的）荣誉","en":"blue","type":"word"},{"cn":"光；灯光","en":"light","type":"word"},{"cn":"太阳；阳光","en":"sun","type":"word"},{"cn":"颜色  涂色","en":"colour","type":"word"},{"cn":"，消散","en":"scatter","type":"word"},{"cn":"波动；波浪；高潮；挥手示意；卷曲 vt. 卷（烫）发；向…挥手示意；使成波浪形 vi.","en":"wave","type":"word"},{"cn":"红色的 红色","en":"red","type":"word"},{"cn":"橘子，橙；橙色","en":"orange","type":"word"},{"cn":"黄色的 黄色","en":"yellow","type":"word"},{"cn":"绿色；绿色的;青的","en":"green","type":"word"},{"cn":"紫罗兰；堇菜；羞怯的人 adj. 紫色的；紫罗兰色的 n. (Violet)人名；(西)比奥莱特；(法)维奥莱；(印、匈、英)维奥莱特","en":"violet","type":"word"},{"cn":"小的；少的","en":"small","type":"word"},{"cn":"颗粒；[物] 质点；极小量；小品词","en":"particle","type":"word"},{"cn":"空气；大气","en":"air","type":"word"},{"cn":"分子；微小颗粒，微粒","en":"molecule","type":"word"},{"cn":"穿过；通过","en":"through","type":"word"},{"cn":"旅行；游历","en":"travel","type":"word"},{"cn":"到达，抵达；伸手够到","en":"reach","type":"word"},{"cn":"眼睛","en":"eye","type":"word"},{"cn":"为什么","en":"why","type":"word"},{"cn":"出现","en":"appear","type":"word"},{"cn":"日出；黎明 n. (Sunrise)人名；(德)松里泽","en":"sunrise","type":"word"},{"cn":"日落，傍晚","en":"sunset","type":"word"},{"cn":"气氛；大气；空气","en":"atmosphere","type":"word"}],"passage":{"title":"Why the Sky Is Blue","html":"<p>Why is the <b>sky</b> <b>blue</b>? This question, which <b class=\"gs\">seems simple enough</b> for a <b class=\"gs\">child to ask</b>, actually leads to one of the most elegant demonstrations of how <b>light</b> interacts with matter. The <b>sun</b> <b class=\"gs\">emits white light</b>, which <b class=\"gs\">contains all the</b> <b>colour</b>s of the <b class=\"gs\">visible spectrum combined</b>. But when this <b>light</b> <b>travel</b>s <b>through</b> the <b>earth</b>'s <b>atmosphere</b>, it <b class=\"gs\">does not simply pass</b> <b>through</b> unchanged — it <b class=\"gs\">collides with countless</b> tiny gas <b>molecule</b>s and <b>small</b> <b>particle</b>s suspended in the <b>air</b>. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>The <b class=\"gs\">key to understanding the</b> <b>sky</b>'s <b>colour</b> lies in a process called Rayleigh <b>scatter</b>ing. When <b>light</b> <b>wave</b>s <b class=\"gs\">strike particles that are</b> much <b>small</b>er than their own <b>wave</b>length, the <b>particle</b>s <b class=\"gs\">absorb and then re-emit</b> the <b>light</b> in all directions. Crucially, <b class=\"gs\">shorter wavelengths scatter much more</b> strongly than longer ones. <b>Blue</b> <b>light</b>, with its <b class=\"gs\">relatively short wavelength</b>, <b class=\"gs\">scatters about ten times</b> more than <b>red</b> <b>light</b>. So when you <b class=\"gs\">look up at the</b> <b>sky</b>, you see <b class=\"gs\">sunlight that has been scattered</b> by <b>air</b> <b>molecule</b>s — and since <b>blue</b> <b class=\"gs\">scatters the most</b>, the <b>sky</b> <b>appear</b>s <b>blue</b>. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>This also explains why <b>sunrise</b>s and <b>sunset</b>s <b>appear</b> <b>red</b> and <b>orange</b>. When the <b>sun</b> is <b class=\"gs\">low on the horizon</b>, its <b>light</b> must <b>travel</b> <b>through</b> a much thicker section of the <b>atmosphere</b> to <b>reach</b> your <b>eye</b>s. During this <b class=\"gs\">longer journey</b>, nearly all the <b>blue</b> and <b>green</b> <b>light</b> <b class=\"gs\">gets scattered away</b>, leaving only the longer <b>wave</b>lengths — the warm <b>red</b>s, <b>orange</b>s, and <b>yellow</b>s — to <b>reach</b> your <b>eye</b>s. The more <b>particle</b>s in the <b>air</b>, the more vivid the <b>colour</b>s <b class=\"gs\">tend to be</b>. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>If the <b>earth</b> had no <b>atmosphere</b>, the <b>sky</b> would <b>appear</b> <b class=\"gs\">completely black</b> even during the <b>day</b> — just as <b class=\"gs\">astronauts see it from</b> the <b>moon</b>. The <b>blue</b> <b>sky</b> is, in a <b class=\"gs\">very real sense</b>, a <b class=\"gs\">gift of our atmosphere</b> — a <b class=\"gs\">gentle reminder that</b> the <b>air</b> we breathe is <b class=\"gs\">constantly shaping how we</b> see the universe, filtering and <b class=\"gs\">coloring every beam of</b> <b>sun</b><b>light</b> that <b>reach</b>es our <b>eye</b>s. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p>"}},{"name":"鸟类的迁徙","entries":[{"cn":"鸟","en":"bird","type":"word"},{"cn":"飞，飞行；乘飞机旅行；(旗帜等)飘动；放(风筝、飞机模型等) 飞行；苍蝇","en":"fly","type":"word"},{"cn":"使移居；使移植","en":"migrate","type":"word"},{"cn":"冬天；冬季","en":"winter","type":"word"},{"cn":"夏天；夏季","en":"summer","type":"word"},{"cn":"南；南方","en":"south","type":"word"},{"cn":"北的；朝北的；北方的","en":"north","type":"word"},{"cn":"旅行；游历","en":"travel","type":"word"},{"cn":"旅行；旅程","en":"journey","type":"word"},{"cn":"翼；翅膀；飞翔；派别；侧厅，耳房，厢房 vt. 使飞；飞过；空运；增加…速度；装以翼 vi. 飞行","en":"wing","type":"word"},{"cn":"距离","en":"distance","type":"word"},{"cn":"千","en":"thousand","type":"word"},{"cn":"路线；航线；通道 vt. 按某路线发送","en":"route","type":"word"},{"cn":"地磁的；有磁性的；有吸引力的","en":"magnetic","type":"word"},{"cn":"田地；牧场；场地","en":"field","type":"word"},{"cn":"星星；明星","en":"star","type":"word"},{"cn":"陆地；土地","en":"land","type":"word"},{"cn":"海洋","en":"ocean","type":"word"},{"cn":"食物，食品","en":"food","type":"word"},{"cn":"繁殖；","en":"breed","type":"word"},{"cn":"巢，窝；安乐窝；温床 vt. 筑巢；嵌套 vi. 筑巢；找鸟巢 n. (Nest)人名；(德)内丝","en":"nest","type":"word"},{"cn":"蛋;卵","en":"egg","type":"word"},{"cn":"年轻的","en":"young","type":"word"},{"cn":"季节；季","en":"season","type":"word"},{"cn":"休息；剩余部分 休息","en":"rest","type":"word"}],"passage":{"title":"How Birds Migrate","html":"<p>Twice every <b>year</b>, billions of <b>bird</b>s <b class=\"gs\">take to the skies</b> in one of the most extraordinary spectacles in nature: <b class=\"gs\">the great migration</b>. Some species <b>travel</b> astonishing <b>distance</b>s — the Arctic tern <b>fly</b>s from its <b>breed</b>ing <b>ground</b>s in the <b>north</b> to the <b>south</b>ern <b>ocean</b> and back each <b>year</b>, covering over seventy <b>thousand</b> kilometers annually. The primary <b class=\"gs\">driver of migration is</b> <b>food</b>: as <b>winter</b> <b class=\"gs\">arrives in the</b> <b>north</b>ern hemisphere, insects <b class=\"gs\">disappear and plants</b> <b class=\"gs\">stop producing fruit</b>, forcing <b>bird</b>s to <b class=\"gs\">seek warmer regions where</b> resources remain available. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>How do <b>bird</b>s <b class=\"gs\">find their way across</b> such vast <b>distance</b>s, often <b>fly</b>ing at <b>night</b> and <b class=\"gs\">crossing entire</b> <b>ocean</b>s without <b>rest</b>? Scientists have discovered that <b>bird</b>s <b class=\"gs\">use multiple navigation systems</b> working together. They can <b class=\"gs\">sense the earth's</b> <b>magnetic</b> <b>field</b> through tiny crystals of magnetite in their beaks, <b class=\"gs\">giving them a built-in</b> compass. They also <b class=\"gs\">read the position of</b> the <b>star</b>s — experiments in planetariums have shown that <b>bird</b>s raised under an artificial <b>star</b> map will <b class=\"gs\">orient themselves accordingly</b> when released. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>The physical demands of migration are <b class=\"gs\">almost beyond belief</b>. Before departure, <b>bird</b>s <b class=\"gs\">undergo a dramatic transformation</b> called hyperphagia — they <b class=\"gs\">eat voraciously and can</b> double their <b>body</b> weight in <b>fat</b>, which <b class=\"gs\">serves as fuel for</b> the <b>journey</b>. Their <b>wing</b> muscles <b class=\"gs\">enlarge and their internal</b> organs <b class=\"gs\">shrink to reduce weight</b>. Some species, like the bar-tailed godwit, <b>fly</b> nonstop for over eleven <b>thousand</b> kilometers across the Pacific <b>ocean</b> — the <b class=\"gs\">longest nonstop flight of</b> any <b>bird</b> — without eating, drinking, or sleeping. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>When <b>bird</b>s <b>reach</b> their destination, the <b class=\"gs\">real work begins</b>: <b class=\"gs\">finding a mate, building a</b> <b>nest</b>, laying <b>egg</b>s, and raising <b>young</b>. They <b class=\"gs\">must accomplish all of this</b> within a narrow <b>season</b>al window before the <b class=\"gs\">return journey begins</b>. As <b>summer</b> fades, the <b class=\"gs\">urge to migrate stirs again</b>, triggered by <b class=\"gs\">changes in daylight length</b> and hormonal shifts. The <b>young</b> <b>bird</b>s, who have never <b class=\"gs\">made the journey before</b>, will <b>fly</b> the same <b>route</b> their ancestors have followed for <b>thousand</b>s of generations — a <b class=\"gs\">testament to how deeply</b> migration <b class=\"gs\">is etched into their</b> <b class=\"gs\">genetic code</b>. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p>"}},{"name":"睡眠的科学","entries":[{"cn":"睡觉","en":"sleep","type":"word"},{"cn":"脑","en":"brain","type":"word"},{"cn":"身体","en":"body","type":"word"},{"cn":"梦;梦想","en":"dream","type":"word"},{"cn":"回忆；记忆","en":"memory","type":"word"},{"cn":"深的","en":"deep","type":"word"},{"cn":"夜；夜间","en":"night","type":"word"},{"cn":"(一)天，(一)日；白天","en":"day","type":"word"},{"cn":"小时","en":"hour","type":"word"},{"cn":"醒来；唤醒","en":"wake","type":"word"},{"cn":"循环（周期）；自行车﹔摩托车","en":"cycle","type":"word"},{"cn":"休息；剩余部分 休息","en":"rest","type":"word"},{"cn":"健康","en":"health","type":"word"},{"cn":"生;发育;种植;变成","en":"grow","type":"word"},{"cn":"修理","en":"repair","type":"word"},{"cn":"细胞；电池；蜂房的巢室；单人小室 vi. 住在牢房或小室中 n. (Cell)人名；(英)塞尔","en":"cell","type":"word"},{"cn":"激素，荷尔蒙","en":"hormone","type":"word"},{"cn":"免疫者；免除者 adj. 免疫的；免于……的，免除的","en":"immune","type":"word"},{"cn":"必须","en":"need","type":"word"},{"cn":"年轻的","en":"young","type":"word"},{"cn":"成年人；成年的","en":"adult","type":"word"},{"cn":"在....的期间;在.....过程中","en":"during","type":"word"},{"cn":"当……时候；然而","en":"while","type":"word"},{"cn":"，行程","en":"stage","type":"word"},{"cn":"质量","en":"quality","type":"word"}],"passage":{"title":"The Science of Sleep","html":"<p>We spend roughly one-third of our lives asleep, yet scientists are still <b class=\"gs\">uncovering the full picture</b> of <b class=\"gs\">what happens during those</b> <b>hour</b>s of unconsciousness. What we do know is that <b>sleep</b> is not simply a period of <b>rest</b> — it is an active, highly organized process that <b class=\"gs\">is essential for nearly</b> every <b class=\"gs\">system in the</b> <b>body</b>. Most <b>adult</b>s <b>need</b> between seven and nine <b>hour</b>s per <b>night</b>, <b>while</b> <b>young</b> children may <b>need</b> up to fourteen <b>hour</b>s because their <b>body</b> and <b>brain</b> are <b class=\"gs\">undergoing rapid development</b>. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p><b>Sleep</b> <b class=\"gs\">unfolds in repeating</b> <b>cycle</b>s of approximately ninety minutes, each <b class=\"gs\">moving through distinct</b> <b>stage</b>s. The most fascinating is REM <b>sleep</b> — named for the rapid <b>eye</b> movements that <b class=\"gs\">occur beneath closed lids</b> — <b>during</b> which most vivid <b>dream</b>ing <b class=\"gs\">takes place</b>. In this <b>stage</b>, your <b>brain</b> is nearly as active as when you are <b>wake</b>, but your <b>body</b> <b class=\"gs\">enters a state of temporary</b> paralysis that <b class=\"gs\">prevents you from acting out</b> your <b>dream</b>s. <b>Deep</b> <b>sleep</b>, by contrast, is when the <b>brain</b> <b class=\"gs\">produces slow delta waves</b> and the <b>body</b> <b class=\"gs\">focuses on physical</b> <b>repair</b>. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>The <b class=\"gs\">functions of sleep are remarkably</b> diverse. <b>During</b> <b>deep</b> <b>sleep</b>, the <b>body</b> <b class=\"gs\">releases growth</b> <b>hormone</b>, which <b class=\"gs\">stimulates tissue</b> <b>repair</b>, muscle <b>grow</b>th, and bone development — this is <b class=\"gs\">one reason children need</b> so much <b>sleep</b>. The <b>immune</b> <b>system</b> <b class=\"gs\">also becomes more active</b> <b>during</b> <b>sleep</b>, <b class=\"gs\">producing proteins that help</b> <b>fight</b> infection. Meanwhile, the <b>brain</b> <b class=\"gs\">performs critical housekeeping</b>: it <b class=\"gs\">clears out toxic waste</b> products that <b class=\"gs\">accumulate during the</b> <b>day</b>, <b class=\"gs\">strengthens important neural connections</b>, and <b class=\"gs\">transfers newly formed</b> <b>memory</b> from temporary storage to <b class=\"gs\">more permanent regions</b>. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>The <b class=\"gs\">consequences of insufficient</b> <b>sleep</b> <b class=\"gs\">are severe and wide-ranging</b>. After just one <b>night</b> of poor <b>sleep</b>, <b>memory</b> <b class=\"gs\">consolidation suffers and emotional</b> control <b class=\"gs\">becomes noticeably impaired</b>. Chronic <b>sleep</b> deprivation <b class=\"gs\">has been linked to</b> weakened <b>immune</b> function, increased risk of heart <b>disease</b>, and <b class=\"gs\">long-term cognitive decline</b>. Modern <b>life</b>, with its artificial lighting and <b class=\"gs\">constant digital stimulation</b>, <b class=\"gs\">has disrupted our natural</b> <b>sleep</b>-<b>wake</b> <b>cycle</b> — but the science is clear: <b>quality</b> <b>sleep</b> is not a luxury; it is a biological necessity. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p>"}},{"name":"光合作用","entries":[{"cn":"种植；播种 植物","en":"plant","type":"word"},{"cn":"叶子；（书籍等的）一张；扇页 vi. 生叶；翻书页 vt. 翻…的页，匆匆翻阅 n. (Leaf)人名；(英","en":"leaf","type":"word"},{"cn":"太阳；阳光","en":"sun","type":"word"},{"cn":"光；灯光","en":"light","type":"word"},{"cn":"精力;能量","en":"energy","type":"word"},{"cn":"水 浇水","en":"water","type":"word"},{"cn":"卡尔邦；","en":"carbon","type":"word"},{"cn":"二氧化物","en":"dioxide","type":"word"},{"cn":"氧气，","en":"oxygen","type":"word"},{"cn":"食物，食品","en":"food","type":"word"},{"cn":"糖","en":"sugar","type":"word"},{"cn":"根；根源；词根；祖先 vt. 生根，固定；根源在于","en":"root","type":"word"},{"cn":"土地；土壤；国家；粪便；务农；温床 vt. 弄脏；污辱 vi. 变脏","en":"soil","type":"word"},{"cn":"空气；大气","en":"air","type":"word"},{"cn":"绿色；绿色的;青的","en":"green","type":"word"},{"cn":"叶绿素","en":"chlorophyll","type":"word"},{"cn":"生;发育;种植;变成","en":"grow","type":"word"},{"cn":"化学品；化学的","en":"chemical","type":"word"},{"cn":"处理；加工","en":"process","type":"word"},{"cn":"生产；产生；制造","en":"produce","type":"word"},{"cn":"释放，排放；发表","en":"release","type":"word"},{"cn":"全神贯注","en":"absorb","type":"word"},{"cn":"穿过；通过","en":"through","type":"word"},{"cn":"必须","en":"need","type":"word"},{"cn":"生活；居住；活着","en":"live","type":"word"}],"passage":{"title":"How Plants Make Food","html":"<p>Every <b>green</b> <b>leaf</b> on every <b>plant</b> is a miniature factory, <b class=\"gs\">quietly performing one of</b> the most important <b>chemical</b> <b>process</b>es on <b>earth</b>: photosynthesis. The word itself <b class=\"gs\">comes from Greek roots</b> meaning \"putting together with <b>light</b>,\" and that is exactly what happens. <b>Plant</b>s <b class=\"gs\">capture energy from</b> <b>sun</b><b>light</b> and use it to <b class=\"gs\">transform simple molecules into</b> the <b>food</b> that <b class=\"gs\">powers nearly all life</b> on our planet. Without this <b>process</b>, the <b>earth</b> as we know it would be <b class=\"gs\">completely unrecognizable</b>. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>The <b class=\"gs\">key player in photosynthesis</b> is <b>chlorophyll</b>, the pigment that <b class=\"gs\">gives leaves their</b> <b>green</b> <b>colour</b>. <b>Chlorophyll</b> molecules are <b class=\"gs\">packed into tiny structures</b> inside <b>leaf</b> cells called chloroplasts, where they <b>absorb</b> <b>sun</b><b>light</b> — primarily the <b class=\"gs\">blue and red portions of</b> the spectrum, which is <b class=\"gs\">why leaves appear</b> <b>green</b> to our eyes. The <b>absorb</b>ed <b>light</b> <b>energy</b> <b class=\"gs\">splits water molecules</b> that the <b>plant</b> has <b class=\"gs\">drawn up from</b> the <b>soil</b> <b>through</b> its <b>root</b>s, releasing <b>oxygen</b> as a byproduct — the very <b>oxygen</b> that <b class=\"gs\">fills our atmosphere and</b> that animals <b>need</b> to <b>live</b>. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>Meanwhile, the <b>plant</b> <b class=\"gs\">takes in</b> <b>carbon</b> <b>dioxide</b> from the <b>air</b> <b>through</b> microscopic pores in its <b>leaf</b>s. Using the <b>energy</b> captured from <b>sun</b><b>light</b>, it <b class=\"gs\">combines this carbon</b> with hydrogen from <b>water</b> to <b>produce</b> <b>sugar</b>, a simple carbohydrate. The <b>plant</b> can then <b class=\"gs\">convert this sugar into</b> more complex molecules — starches for storage, cellulose <b class=\"gs\">to build cell walls</b>, and proteins for <b>grow</b>th. Every bite of <b>food</b> you eat and every breath of <b>oxygen</b> you take <b class=\"gs\">can be traced back to</b> this remarkable <b>chemical</b> <b>process</b>. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>Scientists are now <b class=\"gs\">working to harness photosynthesis</b> to solve some of humanity's greatest challenges. By studying how <b>plant</b>s so efficiently <b class=\"gs\">convert sunlight into stored</b> <b>energy</b>, researchers hope to <b class=\"gs\">develop artificial systems</b> that can <b>produce</b> clean fuels and <b class=\"gs\">remove excess</b> <b>carbon</b> <b>dioxide</b> from the <b>air</b>. The humble <b>green</b> <b>leaf</b> may <b class=\"gs\">hold the key to</b> a <b class=\"gs\">sustainable future</b>. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p>"}},{"name":"火山的力量","entries":[{"cn":"火山","en":"volcano","type":"word"},{"cn":"地球;土,泥;大地","en":"earth","type":"word"},{"cn":"岩石；摇滚乐","en":"rock","type":"word"},{"cn":"热的;辣的","en":"hot","type":"word"},{"cn":"熔化，溶解；","en":"melt","type":"word"},{"cn":"马格马","en":"magma","type":"word"},{"cn":"火山岩浆；火山所喷出的熔岩 n. (Lava)人名；(西、意)拉瓦","en":"lava","type":"word"},{"cn":"爆发；喷出","en":"erupt","type":"word"},{"cn":"山；山脉","en":"mountain","type":"word"},{"cn":"灰；灰烬 n. (Ash)人名；(英、俄、捷)阿什","en":"ash","type":"word"},{"cn":"气态；气体；煤气","en":"gas","type":"word"},{"cn":"压力；","en":"pressure","type":"word"},{"cn":"深的","en":"deep","type":"word"},{"cn":"表面；表层","en":"surface","type":"word"},{"cn":"地壳；外壳；面包皮；坚硬外皮 vi. 结硬皮；结成外壳 vt. 盖以硬皮；在…上结硬皮","en":"crust","type":"word"},{"cn":"海洋","en":"ocean","type":"word"},{"cn":"岛","en":"island","type":"word"},{"cn":"危险","en":"danger","type":"word"},{"cn":"电源；能源；动力；电力","en":"power","type":"word"},{"cn":"凉的；凉爽的；酷","en":"cool","type":"word"},{"cn":"形式；方式","en":"form","type":"word"},{"cn":"热度,热量；加热","en":"heat","type":"word"},{"cn":"火；火炉；火灾","en":"fire","type":"word"},{"cn":"烟","en":"smoke","type":"word"},{"cn":"，飘动","en":"flow","type":"word"}],"passage":{"title":"Volcanoes","html":"<p>A <b>volcano</b> is essentially a <b class=\"gs\">window into the interior</b> of our planet — a place where <b>melt</b>ed <b>rock</b>, called <b>magma</b>, <b class=\"gs\">forces its way to</b> the <b>surface</b>. The <b>earth</b>'s <b>crust</b> is not a <b class=\"gs\">single unbroken shell</b> but a <b class=\"gs\">mosaic of tectonic plates</b> that float on a layer of <b>hot</b>, semi-<b>melt</b>ed <b>rock</b> <b>deep</b> beneath our feet. When these plates <b class=\"gs\">collide or pull apart</b>, they <b class=\"gs\">create pathways for</b> <b>magma</b> to rise toward the <b>surface</b>, where it <b class=\"gs\">collects in underground chambers</b> that can <b class=\"gs\">hold vast amounts of</b> <b>melt</b>ed <b>rock</b> under enormous <b>pressure</b>. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>When the <b>pressure</b> <b class=\"gs\">becomes too great</b>, the <b>volcano</b> <b>erupt</b>s. <b>Magma</b> <b class=\"gs\">blasts upward through</b> the central vent, and once it <b class=\"gs\">reaches the surface</b> it is called <b>lava</b>. <b class=\"gs\">Depending on its chemical</b> composition, <b>lava</b> can <b>flow</b> like a thick <b class=\"gs\">river of molten</b> <b>rock</b> or <b class=\"gs\">explode violently into</b> the <b>air</b> as <b>ash</b> and volcanic bombs. The <b class=\"gs\">eruption also releases enormous</b> quantities of <b>gas</b> — water vapor, <b>carbon</b> dioxide, sulfur dioxide — along with <b>ash</b> that can <b class=\"gs\">rise tens of kilometers</b> into the atmosphere and <b class=\"gs\">travel around the globe</b>. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>Despite their <b>danger</b>, <b>volcano</b>es are also <b class=\"gs\">forces of creation</b>. Over millions of years, repeated <b>erupt</b>ions <b class=\"gs\">build enormous</b> <b>mountain</b>s — Mauna Loa in Hawaii, <b class=\"gs\">measured from its base</b> on the <b>ocean</b> floor, is taller than Mount Everest. Entire <b>island</b> chains, including Hawaii and Iceland, <b class=\"gs\">owe their existence to</b> volcanic activity. The <b>rock</b> and <b>ash</b> from <b>volcano</b>es <b class=\"gs\">weather into incredibly</b> fertile <b>soil</b> that <b class=\"gs\">supports rich agriculture</b> — which is <b class=\"gs\">why millions of people</b> <b>live</b> on the <b class=\"gs\">slopes of active volcanoes</b> despite the risks. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>Scientists monitor <b>volcano</b>es using an <b class=\"gs\">array of sophisticated instruments</b> — seismometers that <b class=\"gs\">detect tiny earthquakes</b>, GPS sensors that <b class=\"gs\">track ground deformation</b>, and <b>gas</b> analyzers that measure <b class=\"gs\">changes in volcanic emissions</b>. These tools <b class=\"gs\">can often provide days</b> or even weeks of warning before a major <b>erupt</b>ion, <b class=\"gs\">giving communities time to</b> evacuate. While we cannot <b class=\"gs\">control the immense</b> <b>power</b> of a <b>volcano</b>, understanding its behavior <b class=\"gs\">saves countless lives every</b> <b>year</b>. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p>"}},{"name":"人体免疫系统","entries":[{"cn":"免疫者；免除者 adj. 免疫的；免于……的，免除的","en":"immune","type":"word"},{"cn":"制度，体制；系统；方法","en":"system","type":"word"},{"cn":"身体","en":"body","type":"word"},{"cn":"细胞；电池；蜂房的巢室；单人小室 vi. 住在牢房或小室中 n. (Cell)人名；(英)塞尔","en":"cell","type":"word"},{"cn":"白色的 白色","en":"white","type":"word"},{"cn":"血，血液","en":"blood","type":"word"},{"cn":"比鲁斯","en":"virus","type":"word"},{"cn":"的复数","en":"bacteria","type":"word"},{"cn":"病，[医] 疾病；弊病 vt. 传染；使…有病","en":"disease","type":"word"},{"cn":"进攻，袭击","en":"attack","type":"word"},{"cn":"保护","en":"protect","type":"word"},{"cn":"打仗；打架；争论","en":"fight","type":"word"},{"cn":"防御；防卫；答辩；防卫设备","en":"defence","type":"word"},{"cn":"认出；承认，认可；识别","en":"recognise","type":"word"},{"cn":"回忆；记忆","en":"memory","type":"word"},{"cn":"皮肤；外皮 vt. 剥皮 vi. 愈合；长皮","en":"skin","type":"word"},{"cn":"障碍物，屏障；界线 vt. 把…关入栅栏 n. (Barrier)人名；(法)巴里耶","en":"barrier","type":"word"},{"cn":"侵略者；侵入物","en":"invader","type":"word"},{"cn":"健康的","en":"healthy","type":"word"},{"cn":"强壮的；坚强的","en":"strong","type":"word"},{"cn":"发烧，发热","en":"fever","type":"word"},{"cn":"响应；反应；回答","en":"response","type":"word"},{"cn":"人名；","en":"heal","type":"word"},{"cn":"抗体","en":"antibody","type":"word"},{"cn":"感染；传染；影响；传染病","en":"infection","type":"word"}],"passage":{"title":"The Human Immune System","html":"<p>Your <b>body</b> is <b class=\"gs\">under constant assault</b> — every breath you take, every surface you touch, and every bite of <b>food</b> you swallow <b class=\"gs\">introduces potentially harmful</b> microorganisms. Yet most of the time, you remain perfectly <b>healthy</b>. The reason is your <b>immune</b> <b>system</b>, a <b class=\"gs\">vast and sophisticated defence</b> network that <b class=\"gs\">operates throughout your entire</b> <b>body</b>, from your <b>skin</b> to your <b>blood</b>stream to the <b class=\"gs\">deepest recesses of your</b> organs. It is so complex that immunologists <b class=\"gs\">are still discovering new</b> components and connections. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>The <b>immune</b> <b>system</b> <b class=\"gs\">works in layers</b>. The first line of <b>defence</b> is physical: your <b>skin</b> <b class=\"gs\">forms an almost impenetrable</b> <b>barrier</b>, while mucus <b class=\"gs\">traps invaders in your</b> nose and throat. If a pathogen <b class=\"gs\">breaches these barriers</b>, the innate <b>immune</b> <b>response</b> <b class=\"gs\">kicks in immediately</b>. Specialized <b>white</b> <b>blood</b> <b>cell</b>s <b class=\"gs\">rush to the site of</b> <b>infection</b> and <b>attack</b> anything they do not <b>recognise</b> — <b class=\"gs\">engulfing and destroying</b> <b>bacteria</b> and <b>virus</b>es in a <b class=\"gs\">process that often produces</b> inflammation and <b>fever</b> as <b class=\"gs\">visible signs of battle</b>. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>Meanwhile, the adaptive <b>immune</b> <b>system</b> <b class=\"gs\">mounts a more targeted</b> <b>response</b>. Special <b>cell</b>s <b class=\"gs\">capture pieces of the</b> <b>invader</b> and <b class=\"gs\">present them to other</b> <b>cell</b>s, which then <b>produce</b> precise <b>antibody</b> proteins — each one <b class=\"gs\">custom-built to lock onto</b> that specific <b>virus</b> or <b>bacteria</b> and <b class=\"gs\">mark it for destruction</b>. After the <b>infection</b> <b class=\"gs\">has been cleared</b>, <b>memory</b> <b>cell</b>s <b class=\"gs\">remain in the body</b> for years or even a lifetime, ready to <b>recognise</b> the same <b>invader</b> and <b class=\"gs\">launch an immediate</b> <b>defence</b> if it ever returns — this is the <b class=\"gs\">principle behind vaccination</b>. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>Keeping your <b>immune</b> <b>system</b> <b>strong</b> <b class=\"gs\">requires a combination of</b> <b class=\"gs\">well-understood habits</b>: adequate <b>sleep</b>, regular <b class=\"gs\">physical activity</b>, a balanced <b>diet</b> rich in fruits and vegetables, and <b class=\"gs\">managing stress levels</b>. The <b>immune</b> <b>system</b> is not a <b class=\"gs\">switch that can be</b> turned on and off — it is a <b class=\"gs\">delicate balance that requires</b> <b class=\"gs\">consistent care to maintain</b> its remarkable ability to <b>protect</b> you from a <b class=\"gs\">world teeming with microscopic</b> threats. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p>"}},{"name":"洋流与气候","entries":[{"cn":"海洋","en":"ocean","type":"word"},{"cn":"柯伦特","en":"current","type":"word"},{"cn":"水 浇水","en":"water","type":"word"},{"cn":"温暖的；暖和的","en":"warm","type":"word"},{"cn":"冷的，寒冷的  寒冷；感冒","en":"cold","type":"word"},{"cn":"气候；风气；思潮；风土","en":"climate","type":"word"},{"cn":"风","en":"wind","type":"word"},{"cn":"地球;土,泥;大地","en":"earth","type":"word"},{"cn":"移动，搬动；搬家；感动","en":"move","type":"word"},{"cn":"表面；表层","en":"surface","type":"word"},{"cn":"深的","en":"deep","type":"word"},{"cn":"盐","en":"salt","type":"word"},{"cn":"温度","en":"temperature","type":"word"},{"cn":"热度,热量；加热","en":"heat","type":"word"},{"cn":"精力;能量","en":"energy","type":"word"},{"cn":"北的；朝北的；北方的","en":"north","type":"word"},{"cn":"南；南方","en":"south","type":"word"},{"cn":"天气﹔气象","en":"weather","type":"word"},{"cn":"海岸；滑坡 vt. 沿…岸航行 vi. 滑行；沿岸航行 n. (Coast)人名；(英)科斯特","en":"coast","type":"word"},{"cn":"冰","en":"ice","type":"word"},{"cn":"全球的；总体的；球形的","en":"global","type":"word"},{"cn":"，飘动","en":"flow","type":"word"},{"cn":"模式；图案；样品 vt. 模仿；以图","en":"pattern","type":"word"},{"cn":"改变；更换；兑换；n. 零钱；变化","en":"change","type":"word"},{"cn":"制度，体制；系统；方法","en":"system","type":"word"}],"passage":{"title":"Ocean Currents and Climate","html":"<p>The <b>ocean</b> is not a still, uniform <b class=\"gs\">body of water</b> — it is <b class=\"gs\">constantly in motion</b>, driven by a <b class=\"gs\">complex interplay of</b> <b>wind</b>, <b>temperature</b>, <b>salt</b> levels, and the <b>earth</b>'s rotation. These movements, known as <b>ocean</b> <b>current</b>s, <b class=\"gs\">form a vast circulatory</b> <b>system</b> that <b class=\"gs\">transports enormous amounts of</b> <b>heat</b> <b>energy</b> around the <b>globe</b>. Without <b>ocean</b> <b>current</b>s, the <b>earth</b>'s <b>climate</b> would be <b class=\"gs\">radically different</b> — equatorial regions would be much hotter, and <b>north</b>ern latitudes would be <b class=\"gs\">plunged into perpetual</b> <b>ice</b> ages. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>There are two main types of <b>ocean</b> <b>current</b>s. <b>Surface</b> <b>current</b>s, which <b class=\"gs\">extend to a depth of</b> about 400 meters, are primarily driven by <b>wind</b> <b>pattern</b>s and the <b>earth</b>'s rotation. These <b>current</b>s <b class=\"gs\">flow in predictable circular</b> <b>pattern</b>s called gyres, <b>move</b>ing <b>warm</b> <b>water</b> from the equator toward the poles and <b>cold</b> <b>water</b> back toward the equator. <b>Deep</b> <b>ocean</b> <b>current</b>s, collectively called the thermohaline circulation or the <b class=\"gs\">great ocean conveyor belt</b>, are driven by <b class=\"gs\">differences in water density</b> — <b>cold</b>er, <b>salt</b>ier <b>water</b> is denser and sinks, while <b>warm</b>er, fresher <b>water</b> rises. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>The <b class=\"gs\">influence of ocean currents</b> on <b>weather</b> and <b>climate</b> is <b class=\"gs\">difficult to overstate</b>. The Gulf Stream, a <b class=\"gs\">powerful warm current</b> in the Atlantic, <b class=\"gs\">carries tropical heat northward</b> and is the <b class=\"gs\">primary reason that Western</b> <b class=\"gs\">Europe enjoys relatively mild</b> winters despite its high latitude. Along the western <b>coast</b>s of continents, <b>cold</b> <b>current</b>s <b class=\"gs\">bring nutrient-rich water</b> up from the <b>deep</b>, <b class=\"gs\">supporting some of the</b> <b class=\"gs\">richest fishing grounds on</b> <b>earth</b>. When these <b>pattern</b>s <b>change</b> — as during an El Niño event — the <b class=\"gs\">effects ripple through global</b> <b>weather</b> <b>system</b>s. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p><b>Climate</b> <b>change</b> is now <b class=\"gs\">disrupting these ancient patterns</b>. As <b>global</b> <b>temperature</b>s rise, <b>ice</b> sheets <b class=\"gs\">melt at unprecedented rates</b>, <b class=\"gs\">dumping fresh water into</b> the <b>north</b> Atlantic and <b class=\"gs\">potentially slowing the thermohaline</b> circulation. Scientists <b class=\"gs\">are racing to understand</b> how these <b>change</b>s will <b class=\"gs\">play out over the coming</b> decades — because the <b>ocean</b> <b>current</b>s that <b class=\"gs\">have shaped our planet</b>'s <b>climate</b> for millions of years <b class=\"gs\">may be approaching a tipping</b> point. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p>"}},{"name":"心脏如何泵血","entries":[{"cn":"心;心脏","en":"heart","type":"word"},{"cn":"血，血液","en":"blood","type":"word"},{"cn":"身体","en":"body","type":"word"},{"cn":"泵，抽","en":"pump","type":"word"},{"cn":"敲打；跳动；打赢","en":"beat","type":"word"},{"cn":"肌肉；力量 vt. 加强；使劲搬动；使劲挤出 vi. 使劲行进","en":"muscle","type":"word"},{"cn":"动脉；干道；主流","en":"artery","type":"word"},{"cn":"血管；叶脉；[地质] 岩脉；纹理；翅脉；性情 vt. 使成脉络；象脉络般分布于 n. (Vein)人名；(英)维因","en":"vein","type":"word"},{"cn":"氧气，","en":"oxygen","type":"word"},{"cn":"肺；呼吸器 n. (Lung)人名；(越)珑；(罗、塞、匈、瑞典、德)伦格","en":"lung","type":"word"},{"cn":"细胞；电池；蜂房的巢室；单人小室 vi. 住在牢房或小室中 n. (Cell)人名；(英)塞尔","en":"cell","type":"word"},{"cn":"阀；[解剖] 瓣膜；真空管；活门 vt. 装阀于；以活门调节 n. (Valve)人名；(俄、芬)瓦尔韦","en":"valve","type":"word"},{"cn":"人名；","en":"chamber","type":"word"},{"cn":"对的；右边的 正好；向右 右边；权利","en":"right","type":"word"},{"cn":"左边的","en":"left","type":"word"},{"cn":"，飘动","en":"flow","type":"word"},{"cn":"推","en":"push","type":"word"},{"cn":"穿过；通过","en":"through","type":"word"},{"cn":"休息；剩余部分 休息","en":"rest","type":"word"},{"cn":"分钟；一会儿；瞬间","en":"minute","type":"word"},{"cn":"生命；生活；人生","en":"life","type":"word"},{"cn":"人名；","en":"organ","type":"word"},{"cn":"健康的","en":"healthy","type":"word"},{"cn":"锻炼；做操；练习；习题","en":"exercise","type":"word"},{"cn":"压力；","en":"pressure","type":"word"}],"passage":{"title":"How the Heart Pumps Blood","html":"<p>Your <b>heart</b> is an extraordinary <b>muscle</b> — about the <b class=\"gs\">size of your fist</b> — that <b>beat</b>s roughly 100,000 times every <b class=\"gs\">single day</b>, <b>pump</b>ing approximately 7,500 liters of <b>blood</b> <b>through</b> your <b>body</b>. Over an average <b>life</b>time, it will <b>beat</b> more than three billion times without ever taking a <b>rest</b>. This tireless <b>organ</b> is the <b class=\"gs\">central engine of your</b> circulatory <b>system</b>, and <b class=\"gs\">every other part of</b> your <b>body</b> <b class=\"gs\">depends on its steady</b>, rhythmic <b>pump</b>ing to <b class=\"gs\">deliver the oxygen and</b> nutrients that <b class=\"gs\">keep you alive</b>. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>The <b>heart</b> has four <b>chamber</b>s: two upper atria and two lower ventricles. <b>Blood</b> <b class=\"gs\">returns from the body</b> low in <b>oxygen</b> and <b class=\"gs\">enters the</b> <b>right</b> atrium, then <b>flow</b>s into the <b>right</b> ventricle, which <b>pump</b>s it to the <b>lung</b>s. In the <b>lung</b>s, <b>blood</b> <b class=\"gs\">picks up fresh</b> <b>oxygen</b> and <b class=\"gs\">releases carbon dioxide</b>. This newly oxygenated <b>blood</b> <b class=\"gs\">returns to the</b> <b>left</b> atrium, <b>flow</b>s into the powerful <b>left</b> ventricle, and is then <b>push</b>ed out <b>through</b> the aorta — the <b>body</b>'s largest <b>artery</b> — to <b class=\"gs\">reach every</b> <b>cell</b> from your brain to your toes. The entire circuit <b class=\"gs\">takes less than a</b> <b>minute</b>. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>Precision is <b class=\"gs\">absolutely critical in this</b> <b>system</b>. Four one-way <b>valve</b>s <b class=\"gs\">open and close with each</b> <b>beat</b>, <b class=\"gs\">ensuring that blood flows</b> in only one direction. The <b class=\"gs\">distinctive \"lub-dub\" sound</b> of a <b>heart</b><b>beat</b> is actually the sound of these <b>valve</b>s <b class=\"gs\">snapping shut in sequence</b>. The <b>heart</b>'s own electrical <b>system</b> — a <b class=\"gs\">tiny cluster of cells</b> called the sinoatrial node — <b class=\"gs\">generates the rhythmic impulses</b> that <b class=\"gs\">trigger each contraction</b>, <b class=\"gs\">adjusting the rate constantly</b> based on signals from the <b class=\"gs\">brain and hormones in</b> the <b>blood</b>stream. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>Keeping your <b>heart</b> <b>healthy</b> is one of the most important things you can do for your overall well-being. Regular <b>exercise</b> <b class=\"gs\">strengthens the heart muscle</b>, making it more <b class=\"gs\">efficient at pumping blood</b>. A <b>diet</b> low in saturated <b class=\"gs\">fats and rich in fruits</b>, vegetables, and whole grains <b class=\"gs\">helps keep arteries clear</b> and <b>blood</b> <b>pressure</b> at <b>healthy</b> levels. The <b>heart</b> <b class=\"gs\">may be an involuntary</b> <b>muscle</b>, but the <b class=\"gs\">choices we make every</b> <b>day</b> <b class=\"gs\">have a profound impact</b> on how <b>long</b> and how well it continues to <b>beat</b>. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p>"}},{"name":"闪电与雷声","entries":[{"cn":"不同","en":"difference","type":"word"},{"cn":"在(两者)之间；在……中间","en":"between","type":"word"},{"cn":"危险的","en":"dangerous","type":"word"},{"cn":"第二","en":"second","type":"word"},{"cn":"单独的；分开的","en":"separate","type":"word"},{"cn":"电的","en":"electric","type":"word"},{"cn":"强大的","en":"powerful","type":"word"},{"cn":"突然地；忽然","en":"suddenly","type":"word"},{"cn":"底部","en":"bottom","type":"word"},{"cn":"自然；本质","en":"nature","type":"word"},{"cn":"主管，掌管","en":"charge","type":"word"},{"cn":"三十","en":"thirty","type":"word"},{"cn":"的比较级","en":"longer","type":"word"},{"cn":"听见;听说;得知","en":"hear","type":"word"},{"cn":"/ pron.","en":"one","type":"word"},{"cn":"暴风雨；风暴","en":"storm","type":"word"},{"cn":"闪；闪光；转瞬间","en":"flash","type":"word"},{"cn":"声音","en":"sound","type":"word"},{"cn":"三","en":"three","type":"word"},{"cn":"大的；巨大的","en":"large","type":"word"},{"cn":"时代（time的复数）；[数] 次数 prep. 乘以 v. 使…相乘（time的第三人称单数）","en":"times","type":"word"},{"cn":"角色","en":"role","type":"word"},{"cn":"远的","en":"far","type":"word"},{"cn":"顶部；顶端 最高的；顶上的","en":"top","type":"word"},{"cn":"表演，扮演(角色)；行动","en":"act","type":"word"},{"cn":"看见；看到；领会","en":"see","type":"word"},{"cn":"间隙；缺口；差距；分歧 vt. 使形成缺口 vi. 裂开","en":"gap","type":"word"}],"passage":{"title":"Lightning and Thunder","html":"<p>Lightning is <b>one</b> of <b>nature</b>'s most dramatic displays of electrical power. During a thunderstorm, strong winds within the cloud cause ice particles to collide violently. These collisions <b>separate</b> <b>electric</b> charges — lighter positive charges rise to the <b>top</b> of the cloud while heavier negative charges sink to the <b>bottom</b>. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>When the <b>difference</b> in <b>charge</b> <b>between</b> the cloud and the ground becomes <b>large</b> enough, the air can no <b>longer</b> <b>act</b> as an insulator. A <b>powerful</b> electrical discharge — a lightning bolt — <b>suddenly</b> bridges the <b>gap</b>. The bolt heats the surrounding air to nearly <b>thirty</b> thousand degrees in a fraction of a <b>second</b>, causing it to expand explosively. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>This explosive expansion creates a shock wave that we <b>hear</b> as thunder. Because light travels much faster than <b>sound</b>, we <b>see</b> the lightning before we <b>hear</b> the thunder. By counting the seconds <b>between</b> the <b>flash</b> and the rumble, you can estimate how <b>far</b> away the <b>storm</b> is — every <b>three</b> seconds equals roughly <b>one</b> kilometer. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>Lightning strikes the Earth about <b>one</b> hundred <b>times</b> every <b>second</b>, mostly in tropical regions where warm, moist air creates ideal conditions for thunderstorms. While <b>dangerous</b>, lightning also plays a vital <b>role</b> in the nitrogen cycle — the extreme heat causes nitrogen in the air to combine with oxygen, creating compounds that rain carries down to fertilize the soil. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p>"}},{"name":"食物链与生态平衡","entries":[{"cn":"链；链条；连锁店","en":"chain","type":"word"},{"cn":"初等的，初级的","en":"primary","type":"word"},{"cn":"自然的；天然的","en":"natural","type":"word"},{"cn":"副手；代理人 adj. 第二的；中等的；次要的；中级的","en":"secondary","type":"word"},{"cn":"直接地","en":"directly","type":"word"},{"cn":"水平线；水平","en":"level","type":"word"},{"cn":"再一；另一；别的；不同的；pron. 另一个","en":"another","type":"word"},{"cn":"支持；支撑","en":"support","type":"word"},{"cn":"网络；网络系统","en":"network","type":"word"},{"cn":"活的；现存的；活跃的；逼真的 n. 生活；生存；生计 v. 生活；居住（live的ing形式）；度过 n. (Living)人名；(英)利","en":"living","type":"word"},{"cn":"有;吃;喝;进行","en":"have","type":"word"},{"cn":"最近的；紧挨着的；隔壁的；下一次的","en":"next","type":"word"},{"cn":"其他的；另外的","en":"other","type":"word"},{"cn":"东西；事情","en":"thing","type":"word"},{"cn":"吃","en":"eat","type":"word"},{"cn":"像；跟……一样","en":"like","type":"word"},{"cn":"打电话给……；称呼；呼唤；喊；叫；电话","en":"call","type":"word"},{"cn":"为…设立总部；使以…为基础﹐使以…为根据","en":"base","type":"word"},{"cn":"如此的；这样的","en":"such","type":"word"},{"cn":"脚步；步骤","en":"step","type":"word"},{"cn":"福尔；","en":"four","type":"word"},{"cn":"坐","en":"sit","type":"word"},{"cn":"十","en":"ten","type":"word"}],"passage":{"title":"The Food Chain","html":"<p>Every <b>living</b> <b>thing</b> on Earth depends on <b>other</b> organisms for survival. These feeding relationships form a complex <b>network</b> called the food <b>chain</b>, which transfers energy from one <b>level</b> to the <b>next</b>. At the <b>base</b> of every <b>chain</b> are the producers — plants that capture energy <b>directly</b> from the sun. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p><b>Primary</b> consumers, <b>such</b> as rabbits and deer, <b>eat</b> the plants and absorb the stored energy. <b>Secondary</b> consumers, <b>like</b> foxes and snakes, <b>eat</b> the <b>primary</b> consumers. At the top <b>sit</b> the apex predators — eagles, tigers, and sharks — who <b>have</b> few <b>natural</b> enemies. Each <b>step</b> up the <b>chain</b> represents a transfer of energy, but only about <b>ten</b> percent of the energy moves from one <b>level</b> to the <b>next</b>. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>This loss of energy explains why food chains rarely <b>have</b> more than <b>four</b> or five levels. There simply is not enough energy left to <b>support</b> <b>another</b> layer of large predators. The entire system depends on a constant input of fresh energy from the sun. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>When one species in a food <b>chain</b> is removed, the effects can be dramatic. Removing wolves from an ecosystem allows deer populations to explode, which leads to overgrazing and damage to plant life. Scientists <b>call</b> this a trophic cascade, and it demonstrates how delicately balanced <b>natural</b> systems truly are. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p>"}},{"name":"肌肉如何生长","entries":[{"cn":"立即,马上","en":"immediately","type":"word"},{"cn":"发展","en":"development","type":"word"},{"cn":"特别,尤其","en":"especially","type":"word"},{"cn":"获得；采煤，采掘 v. 获得；了解（get的现在分词）；抓住 n. (Getting)人名；(英)格廷","en":"getting","type":"word"},{"cn":"重要的","en":"important","type":"word"},{"cn":"注意，关心","en":"attention","type":"word"},{"cn":"重量，重力；负担；砝码；重要性 vt. 加重量于，使变重 n. (Wei","en":"weight","type":"word"},{"cn":"建筑物；大楼","en":"building","type":"word"},{"cn":"一起；共同","en":"together","type":"word"},{"cn":"继续","en":"continue","type":"word"},{"cn":"增加","en":"increase","type":"word"},{"cn":"实际上；现实地","en":"actually","type":"word"},{"cn":"需要；要求","en":"require","type":"word"},{"cn":"有害的;导致损害的","en":"harmful","type":"word"},{"cn":"特别的；特殊的","en":"special","type":"word"},{"cn":"举起的，起重的 n. 举起，起重；提高，上升 v. 举起，抬起（lift的ing形式）","en":"lifting","type":"word"},{"cn":"在……后面；在后面；向后","en":"behind","type":"word"},{"cn":"总是；一直；永远","en":"always","type":"word"},{"cn":"创造；造成","en":"create","type":"word"},{"cn":"发展；制造；形成 v. 制作（make的现在分词）","en":"making","type":"word"},{"cn":"地方；住所 放置","en":"place","type":"word"},{"cn":"开始，着手","en":"begin","type":"word"},{"cn":"关，关闭  /kləʊs/ 亲密的；近的  近，接近","en":"close","type":"word"},{"cn":"集中","en":"focus","type":"word"},{"cn":"饮食；食谱；食物","en":"diet","type":"word"},{"cn":"工作；劳动","en":"work","type":"word"},{"cn":"保持；保存；继续不断；培育，饲养","en":"keep","type":"word"},{"cn":"举起；抬起","en":"lift","type":"word"}],"passage":{"title":"How Muscles Grow","html":"<p>Your muscles are remarkable tissues that can grow stronger in direct response to the demands you <b>place</b> on them. When you exercise — <b>especially</b> during activities that <b>require</b> strength, like <b>lifting</b> weights — you <b>create</b> microscopic tears in your muscle fibers. This damage might sound <b>harmful</b>, but it is <b>actually</b> the signal that triggers growth. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>After exercise, your body <b>immediately</b> begins repairing these tiny tears. <b>Special</b> cells rush to the damaged areas and <b>begin</b> fusing muscle fibers <b>together</b>, <b>making</b> them thicker and stronger than before. This repair process requires protein, which is why athletes pay <b>close</b> <b>attention</b> to their <b>diet</b>. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>Hormones play a crucial role in muscle <b>development</b>. Testosterone and growth hormone, which are naturally produced by the body, help stimulate the repair and <b>building</b> processes. <b>Getting</b> enough sleep is equally <b>important</b>, because most of this repair <b>work</b> happens during deep sleep when the body can <b>focus</b> its resources on recovery. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>The key principle <b>behind</b> muscle growth is progressive overload: to <b>continue</b> <b>getting</b> stronger, you must gradually <b>increase</b> the demands on your muscles. If you <b>always</b> <b>lift</b> the same <b>weight</b>, your muscles will adapt and stop growing. But by steadily adding more <b>weight</b> or more repetitions, you <b>keep</b> challenging your body to become stronger. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p>"}},{"name":"冰为什么浮在水上","entries":[{"cn":"液体","en":"liquid","type":"word"},{"cn":"结冰","en":"freeze","type":"word"},{"cn":"结冰的；极冷的","en":"freezing","type":"word"},{"cn":"代替,顶替","en":"instead","type":"word"},{"cn":"数量；总数","en":"amount","type":"word"},{"cn":"原因，理由","en":"reason","type":"word"},{"cn":"结果；成果","en":"result","type":"word"},{"cn":"较少地；较小地；更小地 adj. 较少的；较小的 prep. 减去 n. 较少；较小 n. (Less)人名；(","en":"less","type":"word"},{"cn":"在……下面","en":"below","type":"word"},{"cn":"固体","en":"solid","type":"word"},{"cn":"，要点","en":"point","type":"word"},{"cn":"鱼；鱼肉","en":"fish","type":"word"},{"cn":"(指时间等)过……；走过某处 过去；昔日；往事","en":"past","type":"word"},{"cn":"规则；规定 统治","en":"rule","type":"word"},{"cn":"锁","en":"lock","type":"word"},{"cn":"同一的；相同的","en":"same","type":"word"},{"cn":"慢的；缓慢的","en":"slow","type":"word"},{"cn":"现在","en":"now","type":"word"}],"passage":{"title":"Why Ice Floats","html":"<p>Most substances become denser when they <b>freeze</b>, which means their <b>solid</b> form should sink in their <b>liquid</b> form. Water is the remarkable exception to this <b>rule</b>. When water freezes into ice, it actually expands and becomes <b>less</b> dense, which is why ice floats on top of <b>liquid</b> water. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>The <b>reason</b> lies in the unique shape of the water molecule and the hydrogen bonds that form between molecules. In <b>liquid</b> water, these bonds are constantly breaking and reforming as molecules move <b>past</b> each other. But when the temperature drops to the <b>freezing</b> <b>point</b>, the molecules <b>slow</b> down enough for the bonds to <b>lock</b> into a stable crystal structure. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>This crystal structure, shaped like a hexagon, forces the molecules apart to a greater distance than they maintain in <b>liquid</b> form. The <b>result</b> is that ice occupies about nine percent more volume than the <b>same</b> <b>amount</b> of <b>liquid</b> water. Since it is <b>now</b> <b>less</b> dense, it floats. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>This property of water has enormous consequences for life on Earth. If ice sank, lakes and oceans would <b>freeze</b> from the bottom up, killing all aquatic life. <b>Instead</b>, floating ice forms an insulating layer on the surface that protects the water <b>below</b>, allowing <b>fish</b> and other organisms to survive through the winter. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p>"}},{"name":"碳循环","entries":[{"cn":"地下的 /ˈʌndəɡraʊnd/ 地铁","en":"underground","type":"word"},{"cn":"的复数形式","en":"animals","type":"word"},{"cn":"年；年龄；岁月；年代","en":"years","type":"word"},{"cn":"材料，原料","en":"material","type":"word"},{"cn":"活动","en":"activity","type":"word"},{"cn":"回(原处)；向后；背后；后部；背","en":"back","type":"word"},{"cn":"行星","en":"planet","type":"word"},{"cn":"要紧事；麻烦事；事情；问题；物质","en":"matter","type":"word"},{"cn":"事物（thing的复数形式）；用品；形势","en":"things","type":"word"},{"cn":"人的;人类的； 人类","en":"human","type":"word"},{"cn":"在……下面；低于","en":"under","type":"word"},{"cn":"今天；当今","en":"today","type":"word"},{"cn":"基本的；基础的","en":"basic","type":"word"},{"cn":"一排房屋；街区；大块；阻止","en":"block","type":"word"},{"cn":"快的，迅速的","en":"rapid","type":"word"},{"cn":"已知的；知名的；大家知道的 v. 知道（know的过去分词）","en":"known","type":"word"},{"cn":"使用；运用 /juːs/ 利用；用途","en":"use","type":"word"},{"cn":"在……上方；越过；遍及；超过 结束；越过；翻转","en":"over","type":"word"},{"cn":"死的；无生命的","en":"dead","type":"word"},{"cn":"拿；取；花费；乘坐","en":"take","type":"word"},{"cn":"受人资助控制的 v. 保持；维持；保管（keep的过去式和过去分词）","en":"kept","type":"word"},{"cn":"得到（get的第三人称单数）；抓住；说服；受到（惩罚等）","en":"gets","type":"word"},{"cn":"油；石油","en":"oil","type":"word"},{"cn":"自己的 拥有","en":"own","type":"word"}],"passage":{"title":"The Carbon Cycle","html":"<p>Carbon is the <b>basic</b> building <b>block</b> of all <b>known</b> life, and it moves through the Earth's systems in a grand cycle that connects the atmosphere, the oceans, the land, and living organisms. This carbon cycle has <b>kept</b> the <b>planet</b>'s temperature relatively stable for hundreds of millions of <b>years</b>. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>The cycle begins with carbon dioxide in the atmosphere. Plants absorb this gas during photosynthesis and <b>use</b> the carbon to build their tissues. When <b>animals</b> eat plants, they <b>take</b> in this carbon and <b>use</b> it to build their <b>own</b> bodies. Both plants and <b>animals</b> release some carbon <b>back</b> into the atmosphere through respiration. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>When living <b>things</b> die, decomposers like bacteria and fungi break down their remains, releasing carbon <b>back</b> into the soil and air. Some <b>dead</b> organic <b>matter</b> <b>gets</b> buried <b>under</b> layers of sediment before it can fully decompose. <b>Over</b> millions of <b>years</b>, heat and pressure transform this buried <b>material</b> into fossil fuels — coal, <b>oil</b>, and natural gas. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p><b>Human</b> <b>activity</b> has dramatically altered the carbon cycle. By burning fossil fuels at an unprecedented rate, we release carbon that was stored <b>underground</b> for millions of <b>years</b> <b>back</b> into the atmosphere in just decades. This sudden release is the primary cause of the <b>rapid</b> climate change we are experiencing <b>today</b>. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p>"}},{"name":"动物的伪装术","entries":[{"cn":"环境","en":"environment","type":"word"},{"cn":"背景","en":"background","type":"word"},{"cn":"能力；才能","en":"ability","type":"word"},{"cn":"风景；风景画；景色；山水画；乡","en":"landscape","type":"word"},{"cn":"比赛，竞赛；火柴","en":"match","type":"word"},{"cn":"褐色，棕色；褐色的，棕色的","en":"brown","type":"word"},{"cn":"例子;榜样","en":"example","type":"word"},{"cn":"较远，更远；进一步；而且 促进；增进 更多的；更进一步的","en":"further","type":"word"},{"cn":"紧张的","en":"nervous","type":"word"},{"cn":"变化，改变（change的复数） v. 改变；交换（change的第三人称单数形式）","en":"changes","type":"word"},{"cn":"动物","en":"animal","type":"word"},{"cn":"普通的，一般的；共有的","en":"common","type":"word"},{"cn":"效果","en":"effect","type":"word"},{"cn":"更难的；更努力的；更坚固的（hard的比较级） n. (Harder)人名；(英、德、瑞典)哈德","en":"harder","type":"word"},{"cn":"沙；沙子","en":"sand","type":"word"},{"cn":"黑色；黑色的","en":"black","type":"word"},{"cn":"死神","en":"death","type":"word"},{"cn":"允许，准许","en":"allow","type":"word"},{"cn":"把……藏起来,隐藏","en":"hide","type":"word"},{"cn":"意思是；意味着","en":"mean","type":"word"},{"cn":"大衣﹐外套；〔套装的〕短上衣","en":"coat","type":"word"}],"passage":{"title":"Animal Camouflage","html":"<p>In nature, the <b>ability</b> to <b>hide</b> can <b>mean</b> the difference between life and <b>death</b>. Animals have evolved an astonishing variety of camouflage techniques that <b>allow</b> them to blend into their surroundings, becoming nearly invisible to both predators and prey. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>The most <b>common</b> form of camouflage is <b>background</b> matching, where an <b>animal</b>'s color and pattern closely resemble its typical <b>environment</b>. A <b>brown</b> desert lizard matches the <b>sand</b>, while a green tree frog disappears among the leaves. Some animals take this <b>further</b> — the arctic fox <b>changes</b> its <b>coat</b> from <b>brown</b> in summer to pure white in winter to <b>match</b> the changing <b>landscape</b>. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>Some species use disruptive coloration — bold patterns of stripes or spots that break up the outline of their body, making it <b>harder</b> for predators to recognize their shape. Zebras are a classic <b>example</b>: their <b>black</b> and white stripes create a confusing visual <b>effect</b>, especially when the herd is moving together. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>The most sophisticated camouflage belongs to animals like octopuses and cuttlefish, which can change not only their color but also the texture of their skin in a matter of seconds. Special cells in their skin called chromatophores expand and contract to create complex patterns that perfectly <b>match</b> rocks, coral, or <b>sand</b>. This remarkable <b>ability</b> is controlled directly by their <b>nervous</b> system, allowing an almost instant transformation. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p>"}},{"name":"声音如何传播","entries":[{"cn":"中间的；中等的","en":"medium","type":"word"},{"cn":"快地；迅速地","en":"quickly","type":"word"},{"cn":"发动机,引擎","en":"engine","type":"word"},{"cn":"演讲；演说","en":"speech","type":"word"},{"cn":"沿着；顺着；向前；和……一起；一同","en":"along","type":"word"},{"cn":"地面；地板；(楼房的)层","en":"floor","type":"word"},{"cn":"音乐；乐曲","en":"music","type":"word"},{"cn":"空间；太空","en":"space","type":"word"},{"cn":"拿，搬，提，抬，背，抱；携带；运送","en":"carry","type":"word"},{"cn":"声音；噪声；响声","en":"noise","type":"word"},{"cn":"速度","en":"speed","type":"word"},{"cn":"空的","en":"empty","type":"word"},{"cn":"安静的","en":"quiet","type":"word"},{"cn":"每，每一","en":"per","type":"word"},{"cn":"传，递；经过，路过；通过","en":"pass","type":"word"},{"cn":" link. 感觉，觉得；摸，触","en":"feel","type":"word"},{"cn":"转向；转变；转动 轮流；顺序","en":"turn","type":"word"},{"cn":"宽的；广泛的","en":"wide","type":"word"},{"cn":"电声额定系统","en":"ears","type":"word"},{"cn":"耳朵","en":"ear","type":"word"}],"passage":{"title":"How Sound Travels","html":"<p>Sound is a form of energy that travels through matter as a wave of vibrations. Unlike light, which can travel through <b>empty</b> <b>space</b>, sound requires a <b>medium</b> — a solid, liquid, or gas — to <b>carry</b> its vibrations from one place to another. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>When an object vibrates, it pushes against the particles of the surrounding <b>medium</b>. These particles bump into their neighbors, which in <b>turn</b> bump into theirs, creating a chain reaction that carries the vibration outward in all directions. This is why sound can travel through walls and water, and why you can <b>feel</b> the bass from a speaker vibrating through the <b>floor</b>. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>The <b>speed</b> of sound depends on the <b>medium</b> it travels through. Sound moves faster through solids than liquids, and faster through liquids than gases, because the particles in denser materials are closer together and can <b>pass</b> vibrations more <b>quickly</b>. In air, sound travels at about three hundred forty meters <b>per</b> second, but in steel it races <b>along</b> at over five thousand meters <b>per</b> second. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>Our <b>ears</b> are finely tuned instruments that detect these pressure waves and convert them into electrical signals that our brains interpret as <b>music</b>, <b>speech</b>, or <b>noise</b>. The human <b>ear</b> can detect an incredibly <b>wide</b> range of sounds, from the <b>quiet</b> rustle of leaves to the roar of a jet <b>engine</b> — a range of over one trillion times in terms of sound energy. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p>"}},{"name":"月球与潮汐","entries":[{"cn":"不同的，有差异的","en":"different","type":"word"},{"cn":"影响;作用;影响力;支配力；影响;左右;对……起作用;支配","en":"influence","type":"word"},{"cn":"月球；月亮","en":"moon","type":"word"},{"cn":"在……对面的；相对的；对立的","en":"opposite","type":"word"},{"cn":"规则的；经常的","en":"regular","type":"word"},{"cn":"四分之一；一刻钟","en":"quarter","type":"word"},{"cn":"高的","en":"high","type":"word"},{"cn":"横过，穿过","en":"across","type":"word"},{"cn":" 低；矮","en":"low","type":"word"},{"cn":"引起；使发生（cause的过去分词） adj. 由…引起的","en":"caused","type":"word"},{"cn":"边；侧面；方面","en":"side","type":"word"},{"cn":"生物；人","en":"being","type":"word"},{"cn":"两次；两倍","en":"twice","type":"word"},{"cn":"拉；拖；拔","en":"pull","type":"word"},{"cn":"满的，充满的；完全的","en":"full","type":"word"},{"cn":"半,一半,半个","en":"half","type":"word"},{"cn":"新的；新鲜的","en":"new","type":"word"}],"passage":{"title":"The Moon and Tides","html":"<p>The <b>moon</b>, our closest neighbor in space, exerts a powerful <b>influence</b> on the Earth despite <b>being</b> nearly four hundred thousand kilometers away. Its most visible effect is the rising and falling of the oceans, a phenomenon we call the tides. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>The <b>moon</b>'s gravity pulls on the Earth, and because water is fluid and can move freely, the oceans bulge outward on the <b>side</b> facing the <b>moon</b>. Surprisingly, there is also a bulge on the <b>opposite</b> <b>side</b> of the Earth, <b>caused</b> by the difference in gravitational <b>pull</b> <b>across</b> the planet. As the Earth rotates, <b>different</b> coastlines pass through these bulges, experiencing <b>high</b> and <b>low</b> tides roughly <b>twice</b> each day. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>The sun also influences the tides, though its effect is less than <b>half</b> as strong as the <b>moon</b>'s because of its greater distance. When the sun and <b>moon</b> align during <b>full</b> and <b>new</b> moons, their gravitational forces combine to create especially <b>high</b> and <b>low</b> tides called spring tides. When they are at right angles, during <b>quarter</b> moons, the difference between <b>high</b> and <b>low</b> tide is smallest. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>The <b>regular</b> rhythm of the tides has shaped life along coastlines for billions of years. Many marine organisms have evolved life cycles synchronized with the tides, from crabs that only emerge at <b>low</b> tide to corals that release their eggs precisely during certain tidal conditions. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p>"}},{"name":"基因与遗传","entries":[{"cn":"用法说明;命令,指令;指示;指导","en":"instruction","type":"word"},{"cn":"每件事;事事","en":"everything","type":"word"},{"cn":"代，一代","en":"generation","type":"word"},{"cn":"成果；产品；生产；作品","en":"production","type":"word"},{"cn":"知识；学问","en":"knowledge","type":"word"},{"cn":"有时；偶尔","en":"sometimes","type":"word"},{"cn":"语言","en":"language","type":"word"},{"cn":"完成的；完整的  完成，结束","en":"complete","type":"word"},{"cn":"科学；自然科学","en":"science","type":"word"},{"cn":"发展；开发，培养","en":"develop","type":"word"},{"cn":"父母；双亲（parent的复数） v. 教养；引起（parent的三单形式） n. (Parents)人名；(法)帕朗","en":"parents","type":"word"},{"cn":"父亲","en":"father","type":"word"},{"cn":"母亲","en":"mother","type":"word"},{"cn":"在……里面；在里面","en":"inside","type":"word"},{"cn":"现代的","en":"modern","type":"word"},{"cn":"分享；共用；分担","en":"share","type":"word"},{"cn":"读；朗读；阅读","en":"read","type":"word"},{"cn":"脸，面孔","en":"face","type":"word"},{"cn":"路；方法；方式","en":"way","type":"word"},{"cn":"放置；使处于","en":"set","type":"word"}],"passage":{"title":"Genes and Heredity","html":"<p><b>Inside</b> nearly every cell of your body lies a <b>complete</b> <b>set</b> of instructions for building and operating a human being. This <b>instruction</b> manual is written in a chemical <b>language</b> called DNA, and its chapters are called genes. Each gene contains the code for making specific proteins that determine <b>everything</b> from your eye color to how your body processes food. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>You inherit half of your genes from your <b>mother</b> and half from your <b>father</b>, which is why you <b>share</b> traits with both <b>parents</b> but are not identical to either one. This mixing of genetic material during reproduction is nature's <b>way</b> of creating variety within a species, ensuring that each <b>generation</b> has a fresh combination of traits to <b>face</b> changing environments. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p><b>Sometimes</b> small changes, called mutations, occur when DNA is copied during cell division. Most mutations have no noticeable effect, and some can even be beneficial — driving the evolution of new traits over countless generations. But certain mutations can cause diseases by disrupting the <b>production</b> of essential proteins. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p><b>Modern</b> <b>science</b> has given us powerful tools to <b>read</b> and even edit genes. Scientists can now identify genes associated with particular diseases, trace human ancestry back thousands of years, and <b>develop</b> treatments that target specific genetic errors. This growing understanding of genetics is transforming medicine and deepening our <b>knowledge</b> of what it means to be human. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p>"}},{"name":"货币的发明","entries":[{"cn":"国际的","en":"international","type":"word"},{"cn":"钱；货币","en":"money","type":"word"},{"cn":"运输；交通 /trænsˈpɔːt/ 运输","en":"transport","type":"word"},{"cn":"渔夫，渔民","en":"fisherman","type":"word"},{"cn":"电脑","en":"computer","type":"word"},{"cn":"交换；交流","en":"exchange","type":"word"},{"cn":"身体的；物理的","en":"physical","type":"word"},{"cn":"宝贵的，珍贵的","en":"precious","type":"word"},{"cn":"的复数","en":"problems","type":"word"},{"cn":"瓷器","en":"china","type":"word"},{"cn":"特别地；非常；另外","en":"extra","type":"word"},{"cn":"古代的；古老的","en":"ancient","type":"word"},{"cn":"世纪；百年","en":"century","type":"word"},{"cn":"严肃的；严重的；认真的","en":"serious","type":"word"},{"cn":"的复数","en":"parties","type":"word"},{"cn":"人；人们；人民","en":"people","type":"word"},{"cn":"在周围；环绕；在……周围","en":"around","type":"word"},{"cn":"欧洲","en":"europe","type":"word"},{"cn":"银；银器","en":"silver","type":"word"},{"cn":"农民，农夫","en":"farmer","type":"word"},{"cn":"分；划分；(算数用语)除","en":"divide","type":"word"},{"cn":"依靠，依赖；取决于","en":"depend","type":"word"},{"cn":"时间；次；倍数","en":"time","type":"word"},{"cn":"商店","en":"store","type":"word"},{"cn":"(不可数)纸；(可数)报纸；考卷；文件","en":"paper","type":"word"},{"cn":"早的 早地","en":"early","type":"word"},{"cn":"贸易；交易","en":"trade","type":"word"},{"cn":"信任；信赖","en":"trust","type":"word"}],"passage":{"title":"How Money Was Invented","html":"<p>Before <b>money</b> existed, <b>people</b> obtained goods through barter — directly trading one item for another. A <b>farmer</b> with <b>extra</b> grain might <b>trade</b> with a <b>fisherman</b> who had <b>extra</b> fish. But barter had <b>serious</b> limitations: both <b>parties</b> had to want what the other was offering at the same <b>time</b>, and some goods were difficult to <b>divide</b> or <b>transport</b>. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>The first forms of <b>money</b> emerged to solve these <b>problems</b>. <b>Early</b> societies used objects that were widely valued and easy to carry — shells, beads, salt, and eventually <b>precious</b> metals like gold and <b>silver</b>. These objects served three essential functions: they were a medium of <b>exchange</b>, a way to <b>store</b> value over <b>time</b>, and a unit for measuring the worth of different goods. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>Metal coins appeared independently in several <b>ancient</b> civilizations, including <b>China</b>, India, and the Mediterranean region, <b>around</b> two and a half thousand years ago. <b>Paper</b> <b>money</b> was invented in <b>China</b> during the Tang Dynasty, though it did not become common in <b>Europe</b> until the seventeenth <b>century</b>. Today, most <b>money</b> exists only as digital records in <b>computer</b> systems, transferred electronically between accounts. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>The shift from <b>physical</b> to digital <b>money</b> has changed how we think about value and <b>trust</b>. Modern economies <b>depend</b> on complex systems of banks, governments, and <b>international</b> agreements to maintain the stability of currencies. Understanding how <b>money</b> works is essential knowledge for navigating the modern world. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p>"}},{"name":"城市为什么增长","entries":[{"cn":"提供","en":"provide","type":"word"},{"cn":"政府","en":"government","type":"word"},{"cn":"人口，人数","en":"population","type":"word"},{"cn":"世界","en":"world","type":"word"},{"cn":"不可能的","en":"impossible","type":"word"},{"cn":"污染","en":"pollution","type":"word"},{"cn":"服务；服务项目（service复数形式） v. 服务（service的第三人称单数）","en":"services","type":"word"},{"cn":"交通","en":"traffic","type":"word"},{"cn":"历史;历史学","en":"history","type":"word"},{"cn":"文化","en":"culture","type":"word"},{"cn":"将来，未来","en":"future","type":"word"},{"cn":"财富；财产","en":"wealth","type":"word"},{"cn":"管理；经营；处理；设法对付","en":"manage","type":"word"},{"cn":"数；数字；号码；数量","en":"number","type":"word"},{"cn":"需要的 v. 需要（need的过去式）","en":"needed","type":"word"},{"cn":"变得（become的过去式）","en":"became","type":"word"},{"cn":"驾驶,开(车);驱赶","en":"drive","type":"word"},{"cn":"弄干净；打扫  清洁的；干净的","en":"clean","type":"word"},{"cn":"提供","en":"offer","type":"word"},{"cn":"浪费","en":"waste","type":"word"},{"cn":"第一的；最初的 第一；首先，最初 开始；开端","en":"first","type":"word"},{"cn":"生活，[生物] 生命（life的复数） v. 生活（live的三单形式）；居住","en":"lives","type":"word"},{"cn":"目标","en":"goal","type":"word"},{"cn":"制造；做；使得","en":"make","type":"word"},{"cn":"自由的；空闲的；免费的","en":"free","type":"word"},{"cn":"真实的；真的","en":"true","type":"word"},{"cn":"成功的；创造的 v. 做，使，安排（make的过去式和过去分词） n. (Made)人名；(塞)马德 原型: made 是 make 的过去式和过去分词","en":"made","type":"word"},{"cn":"以前","en":"ago","type":"word"},{"cn":"尚；还；仍然","en":"yet","type":"word"}],"passage":{"title":"Why Cities Grow","html":"<p>Throughout human <b>history</b>, cities have been centers of innovation, trade, and <b>culture</b>. The <b>first</b> <b>true</b> cities emerged around five thousand years <b>ago</b> in Mesopotamia, along the banks of the Tigris and Euphrates rivers. What <b>made</b> these early settlements grow into cities was a combination of agricultural surplus, organized <b>government</b>, and the division of labor. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>When farmers could produce more food than their families <b>needed</b>, some people were <b>free</b> to become craftsmen, traders, priests, and soldiers. This specialization led to new technologies, more efficient production, and the accumulation of <b>wealth</b>. Cities <b>became</b> magnets for people seeking opportunity, and their populations grew rapidly. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>Today, more than half of the <b>world</b>'s <b>population</b> <b>lives</b> in urban areas, and this <b>number</b> continues to rise. Modern cities face enormous challenges — housing shortages, <b>traffic</b> congestion, air <b>pollution</b>, and the need to <b>provide</b> <b>clean</b> water and reliable energy to millions of residents. <b>Yet</b> cities also <b>offer</b> unique advantages: they <b>drive</b> economic growth, foster cultural exchange, and <b>provide</b> <b>services</b> that would be <b>impossible</b> in scattered rural communities. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>The <b>future</b> of cities depends on our ability to <b>make</b> them sustainable. Planners and engineers are developing smarter transportation systems, greener buildings, and more efficient ways to <b>manage</b> <b>waste</b>. The <b>goal</b> is to create urban environments that are not only livable but also in harmony with the natural <b>world</b> around them. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p>"}},{"name":"法律如何制定","entries":[{"cn":"社会","en":"society","type":"word"},{"cn":"统治；支配；裁定（rule的第三人称单数形式）","en":"rules","type":"word"},{"cn":"比赛，竞赛","en":"competition","type":"word"},{"cn":"他(她、它)们自己","en":"themselves","type":"word"},{"cn":"讨论","en":"discussion","type":"word"},{"cn":"实践（practice的复数）；练习 v. 练习（practice的第三人称单数形式）","en":"practices","type":"word"},{"cn":"生意；事业；商业","en":"business","type":"word"},{"cn":"没有；超过；在…外面 n. 外部；外面 adv. 户外；在外面；没有或不显示某事物","en":"without","type":"word"},{"cn":"公共的，公众的","en":"public","type":"word"},{"cn":"决定；下决心","en":"decide","type":"word"},{"cn":"争论，辩论；讨论","en":"debate","type":"word"},{"cn":"安全；平安","en":"safety","type":"word"},{"cn":"较好的，更好的；更好地；较好的事物；较优者","en":"better","type":"word"},{"cn":"几乎不","en":"hardly","type":"word"},{"cn":"警察，警方；治安 adj. 警察的；有关警察的 vt. 监督；管辖；维持治安；为…配备警察","en":"police","type":"word"},{"cn":"存在","en":"exist","type":"word"},{"cn":"命令，指示；顺序","en":"order","type":"word"},{"cn":"账单；钞票，纸币","en":"bill","type":"word"},{"cn":"公平的，合理的；金色的","en":"fair","type":"word"},{"cn":"寻找；探索；搜索","en":"seek","type":"word"},{"cn":"法律","en":"law","type":"word"},{"cn":"目的；目标；打算；瞄准","en":"aim","type":"word"}],"passage":{"title":"How Laws Are Made","html":"<p>Every <b>society</b> needs <b>rules</b> to function. <b>Without</b> laws, there would be no way to resolve disputes, protect individual rights, or maintain <b>public</b> <b>order</b>. But how do societies <b>decide</b> what should be legal and what should not? The answer varies across cultures and throughout history, but the process of making laws follows certain fundamental principles. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>In modern democratic societies, laws are typically created by elected representatives who <b>debate</b> proposals in legislative bodies. A proposed <b>law</b>, called a <b>bill</b>, goes through multiple stages of <b>discussion</b>, revision, and voting before it can be passed. This deliberate process is designed to prevent hasty or poorly considered decisions from becoming binding <b>rules</b>. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>The content of laws reflects the values and priorities of a <b>society</b>. Laws against theft and violence protect basic <b>safety</b>, while laws regulating <b>business</b> <b>practices</b> <b>aim</b> to ensure <b>fair</b> <b>competition</b>. Environmental laws <b>seek</b> to preserve natural resources for future generations. As societies change, their laws must change too — which is why the legal system includes mechanisms for reviewing and updating outdated <b>rules</b>. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>Enforcement is just as important as the laws <b>themselves</b>. <b>Police</b> officers, judges, and courts form an interconnected system that investigates violations, determines guilt or innocence, and applies appropriate consequences. A <b>society</b> where laws <b>exist</b> but are not enforced is <b>hardly</b> <b>better</b> than one with no laws at all. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p>"}},{"name":"色彩心理学","entries":[{"cn":"有趣的;有意思的","en":"interesting","type":"word"},{"cn":"信息;情报;资料","en":"information","type":"word"},{"cn":"经验；经历","en":"experience","type":"word"},{"cn":"，见识","en":"sense","type":"word"},{"cn":"质疑（question的第三人称单数形式）","en":"questions","type":"word"},{"cn":"个人的；私人的","en":"personal","type":"word"},{"cn":"相信；认为","en":"believe","type":"word"},{"cn":"博学的；有学问的；学术上的 n. (Learned)人名；(英)勒尼德","en":"learned","type":"word"},{"cn":"vt. 影响；使感染","en":"affect","type":"word"},{"cn":"布告；通知；注意","en":"notice","type":"word"},{"cn":"水果；果实","en":"fruit","type":"word"},{"cn":"决不；从来没有","en":"never","type":"word"},{"cn":"经常，常常","en":"often","type":"word"},{"cn":"举起；使升高；饲养，抚养","en":"raise","type":"word"},{"cn":"标志；符号（sign的复数） v. 签字；预示；写下；用手势表示（sign的三单形式）","en":"signs","type":"word"},{"cn":"出售；销售；廉价出售","en":"sale","type":"word"},{"cn":"黄金","en":"gold","type":"word"},{"cn":"药丸","en":"pill","type":"word"},{"cn":"停止；阻止","en":"stop","type":"word"},{"cn":"快的，迅速的","en":"fast","type":"word"}],"passage":{"title":"The Psychology of Colors","html":"<p>Colors influence our emotions and behavior in ways that most people <b>never</b> consciously <b>notice</b>. Red can <b>raise</b> your heart rate and create a <b>sense</b> of urgency — which is why it is used for <b>stop</b> <b>signs</b>, warning labels, and <b>sale</b> tags in stores. Blue, by contrast, tends to have a calming effect, which is why many hospitals and corporate offices use it in their designs. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>These psychological effects are not random. Scientists <b>believe</b> they have deep evolutionary roots. Our ancestors <b>learned</b> to associate certain colors with important survival <b>information</b>: red with blood and danger, green with safe vegetation and water sources, yellow and orange with ripe <b>fruit</b>. These ancient associations still shape our responses today, even though we rarely face the same survival challenges. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>Marketers and designers use color psychology extensively. <b>Fast</b> food restaurants <b>often</b> use red and yellow because these colors are believed to stimulate appetite and create a <b>sense</b> of excitement. Luxury brands tend to use black, <b>gold</b>, and deep purple to convey sophistication and exclusivity. Even the color of a <b>pill</b> can <b>affect</b> how patients perceive its effectiveness. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>Understanding the psychology of color gives us insight into why we react the way we do to the visual world. It also raises <b>interesting</b> <b>questions</b> about whether our responses to color are universal — shared by all humans — or whether they are shaped primarily by culture and <b>personal</b> <b>experience</b>. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p>"}},{"name":"新闻如何传播","entries":[{"cn":"新闻；消息","en":"news","type":"word"},{"cn":"电视","en":"television","type":"word"},{"cn":"报纸，报章（newspaper的复数） v. 从事报纸工作（newspaper的三单形式）","en":"newspapers","type":"word"},{"cn":"伊文茨","en":"events","type":"word"},{"cn":"互联网,因特网","en":"internet","type":"word"},{"cn":"；市民","en":"citizens","type":"word"},{"cn":"职业的；专业的","en":"professional","type":"word"},{"cn":"传统的","en":"traditional","type":"word"},{"cn":"发明,创造","en":"invention","type":"word"},{"cn":"普通的，平常的","en":"ordinary","type":"word"},{"cn":"有限的；限制的","en":"limited","type":"word"},{"cn":"最后；最终","en":"finally","type":"word"},{"cn":"阅读，朗读；读物；读数 v. 阅读（read的ing形式） adj. 阅读的","en":"reading","type":"word"},{"cn":"人","en":"person","type":"word"},{"cn":"社会的；社交的","en":"social","type":"word"},{"cn":"的复数","en":"months","type":"word"},{"cn":"缺少( want的过去式和过去分词 )；应该；打算；需要…在场 adj. 受通缉的；被征求的","en":"wanted","type":"word"},{"cn":"无线电；收音机","en":"radio","type":"word"},{"cn":"马","en":"horse","type":"word"},{"cn":"嘴，口","en":"mouth","type":"word"},{"cn":"主要的","en":"major","type":"word"},{"cn":"伟大的;重要的;(口语)好极了;很好","en":"great","type":"word"},{"cn":"压，按","en":"press","type":"word"},{"cn":"事件;大事;比赛项目","en":"event","type":"word"},{"cn":"技能；技巧","en":"skill","type":"word"},{"cn":"做，制作（make的第三人称单数） n. 品质；产量；制作过程（make的复数）","en":"makes","type":"word"},{"cn":"骑(马、自行车等) 乘车旅行","en":"ride","type":"word"},{"cn":"船；轮船","en":"ship","type":"word"},{"cn":"城镇；市镇","en":"town","type":"word"},{"cn":"停留；逗留","en":"stay","type":"word"},{"cn":"步行；散步","en":"walk","type":"word"},{"cn":"单词；话","en":"word","type":"word"},{"cn":"年龄；时代","en":"age","type":"word"}],"passage":{"title":"How News Travels","html":"<p>Long before <b>newspapers</b>, <b>television</b>, or the <b>internet</b>, <b>news</b> traveled by <b>word</b> of <b>mouth</b>, carried by merchants, travelers, and <b>town</b> criers. The speed of <b>news</b> was <b>limited</b> by how fast a <b>person</b> could <b>walk</b>, <b>ride</b> a <b>horse</b>, or sail a <b>ship</b>. Important <b>events</b> could take weeks or <b>months</b> to become known in distant places. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>The <b>invention</b> of the printing <b>press</b> in the fifteenth century transformed the spread of information. For the first time, written <b>news</b> could be produced in large quantities and distributed widely. The first regular <b>newspapers</b> appeared in Europe in the seventeenth century, and they quickly became essential <b>reading</b> for <b>citizens</b> who <b>wanted</b> to <b>stay</b> informed about politics, commerce, and world <b>events</b>. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>The twentieth century brought electronic media — <b>radio</b>, <b>television</b>, and <b>finally</b> the <b>internet</b> — each making <b>news</b> faster and more accessible. Today, a <b>major</b> <b>event</b> anywhere in the world can appear on screens everywhere within seconds. <b>Social</b> media platforms allow <b>ordinary</b> people to share firsthand accounts of <b>events</b> as they happen, challenging the <b>traditional</b> role of <b>professional</b> journalists as the primary gatekeepers of <b>news</b>. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>This democratization of information has brought <b>great</b> benefits but also serious problems. False information can spread just as quickly as true information, and the sheer volume of content <b>makes</b> it difficult for people to distinguish reliable sources from unreliable ones. Learning to evaluate <b>news</b> critically has become an essential <b>skill</b> for <b>citizens</b> in the digital <b>age</b>. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p>"}},{"name":"贸易的起源","entries":[{"cn":"其他人","en":"others","type":"word"},{"cn":"有利条件；优势；优点","en":"advantage","type":"word"},{"cn":"的复数","en":"countries","type":"word"},{"cn":"旅行（用）的；移动的 v. 旅行（travel的现在分词形式） n. 走步（等于walking）","en":"traveling","type":"word"},{"cn":"前进（advance的复数）；预付款；求爱 v. 提出；使前进；提前（advance的三单形式）","en":"advances","type":"word"},{"cn":"外国的","en":"foreign","type":"word"},{"cn":"可是；然而,可是,尽管如此","en":"however","type":"word"},{"cn":"达到，获得","en":"achieve","type":"word"},{"cn":"平衡","en":"balance","type":"word"},{"cn":"简单的；简易的","en":"simple","type":"word"},{"cn":"石头；石块","en":"stone","type":"word"},{"cn":"值(多少钱)；花费","en":"cost","type":"word"},{"cn":"失去；丢失","en":"lose","type":"word"},{"cn":"然后；那时；那么","en":"then","type":"word"},{"cn":"打开；张开；开办；开设","en":"open","type":"word"},{"cn":"好的;良好的","en":"good","type":"word"},{"cn":"连接；联系","en":"link","type":"word"},{"cn":"的复数形式","en":"jobs","type":"word"},{"cn":"可以；也许，可能","en":"may","type":"word"}],"passage":{"title":"Why People Trade","html":"<p>Trade is one of the oldest and most fundamental human activities. Long before the invention of money, people exchanged goods with their neighbors — grain for pottery, tools for clothing. Archaeological evidence shows that trade networks connecting distant regions existed as early as the <b>Stone</b> Age, with materials like obsidian and shells <b>traveling</b> hundreds of kilometers from their source. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>The basic logic of trade is <b>simple</b>: people specialize in producing what they are relatively <b>good</b> at making, <b>then</b> exchange their products for things <b>others</b> produce more efficiently. This principle, called comparative <b>advantage</b>, means that trade can benefit both parties even when one is more skilled at producing everything. By focusing on their strengths and trading for the rest, societies can <b>achieve</b> a higher standard of living than any could reach in isolation. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>International trade has grown enormously in the modern era, driven by <b>advances</b> in transportation and communication. Container ships carry goods across oceans at low <b>cost</b>, while the internet enables services to be provided across borders instantly. Global supply chains now <b>link</b> factories, farms, and consumers in a web of economic interdependence that spans the entire planet. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p><b>However</b>, trade also creates challenges. Workers in industries that face <b>foreign</b> competition <b>may</b> <b>lose</b> their <b>jobs</b>, and <b>countries</b> can become dangerously dependent on <b>others</b> for essential goods. Finding the right <b>balance</b> between the benefits of <b>open</b> trade and the need to protect vulnerable communities remains one of the central debates in economic policy. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p>"}},{"name":"选举如何运作","entries":[{"cn":"国家；农村，乡下","en":"country","type":"word"},{"cn":"选举；当选；选择权；上帝的选拔","en":"election","type":"word"},{"cn":"问题","en":"question","type":"word"},{"cn":"恰当地，合适地","en":"properly","type":"word"},{"cn":"现在分词","en":"watching","type":"word"},{"cn":"公民；居民；市民","en":"citizen","type":"word"},{"cn":"私人的；私有的","en":"private","type":"word"},{"cn":"诚实的;正直的","en":"honest","type":"word"},{"cn":"接受","en":"accept","type":"word"},{"cn":"选择","en":"choose","type":"word"},{"cn":"选择","en":"choice","type":"word"},{"cn":"聚会，晚会；政党；党派","en":"party","type":"word"},{"cn":"数","en":"count","type":"word"},{"cn":"重的","en":"heavy","type":"word"},{"cn":"给；递给；付出；给予","en":"give","type":"word"},{"cn":"拿;抱;握住;举行;进行;保持;容纳","en":"hold","type":"word"},{"cn":"遇见，见到；会见；迎接；满足","en":"meet","type":"word"},{"cn":"最好的；最好地；最；最好的人(或物)","en":"best","type":"word"},{"cn":"主意;意见;打算;想法","en":"idea","type":"word"},{"cn":"天（day的复数形式）；时期 adv. 每天；在白天 n. (Days)人名；(英)戴斯","en":"days","type":"word"},{"cn":"跑；经营；运行","en":"run","type":"word"},{"cn":"尝试；努力；试","en":"try","type":"word"}],"passage":{"title":"How Elections Work","html":"<p>In a democratic system, elections are the primary mechanism through which citizens <b>choose</b> their leaders and <b>hold</b> them accountable. While the specific rules vary from <b>country</b> to <b>country</b>, the core <b>idea</b> remains the same: every eligible <b>citizen</b> gets a vote, and the candidate or <b>party</b> with the most support wins the right to govern for a set period of time. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>The process begins long before <b>election</b> day. Candidates announce their intention to <b>run</b>, organize campaigns, raise money, and <b>try</b> to convince voters that they are the <b>best</b> <b>choice</b>. They <b>give</b> speeches, participate in debates, appear in advertisements, and <b>meet</b> with citizens in towns and cities across the <b>country</b>. Modern campaigns make <b>heavy</b> use of social media and data analysis to target their messages to specific groups of voters. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>On <b>election</b> day, citizens go to polling stations to cast their ballots in <b>private</b>. The secrecy of the vote is essential — it protects people from pressure or punishment for their choices. After the polls close, officials <b>count</b> the ballots, often with observers from different parties <b>watching</b> to ensure fairness. In close races, the counting and verification process can take <b>days</b> or even weeks. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>For democracy to function <b>properly</b>, elections must be free and fair. This means that all eligible citizens can vote without facing barriers, that the counting is <b>honest</b> and transparent, and that the losers <b>accept</b> the results and allow a peaceful transfer of power. When any of these conditions is absent, the legitimacy of the entire system is called into <b>question</b>. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p>"}},{"name":"书写的历史","entries":[{"cn":"书写；作品；著作；[法] 笔迹 v. 书写（write的ing形式）","en":"writing","type":"word"},{"cn":"能适应新情况的；灵活的；可变动的；柔韧的；有弹性的","en":"flexible","type":"word"},{"cn":"说话；演讲 v. 讲（speak的ing形式） adj. 演讲的；富于表情的，雄辩的","en":"speaking","type":"word"},{"cn":"的过去式","en":"searched","type":"word"},{"cn":"中国的；中国人的；汉语的  中国人；汉语","en":"chinese","type":"word"},{"cn":"包括;包含","en":"include","type":"word"},{"cn":"目的；用途","en":"purpose","type":"word"},{"cn":"思想；思考；想法；关心 v. 想，思考；认为（think的过去式和过去分词）","en":"thought","type":"word"},{"cn":"中间，当中，中部","en":"middle","type":"word"},{"cn":"〔尤指职业〕作家﹔作者","en":"writer","type":"word"},{"cn":"学习；学会","en":"learn","type":"word"},{"cn":"拼写","en":"spell","type":"word"},{"cn":"标记，记号；唛头，分数；台面标志 n. (Marks)人名；(英、德、意、瑞典、西、捷)马克斯；(俄)马克思","en":"marks","type":"word"},{"cn":"帕尔茨","en":"parts","type":"word"},{"cn":"思想；主意（mind的复数） v. 介意；照顾；留心（mind的第三人称单数）","en":"minds","type":"word"},{"cn":"东方的;东部的 东;东方;东部","en":"east","type":"word"},{"cn":"文字材料","en":"text","type":"word"},{"cn":"墨水;油墨","en":"ink","type":"word"}],"passage":{"title":"The History of Writing","html":"<p>The invention of <b>writing</b> was one of the most important breakthroughs in human history. Before <b>writing</b>, knowledge could only be passed from person to person through speech, which limited how much information could be preserved and shared across time and distance. <b>Writing</b> changed everything — it allowed ideas to be recorded, copied, and transmitted to people the <b>writer</b> would never meet. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>The earliest <b>writing</b> systems emerged independently in several <b>parts</b> of the ancient world. The Sumerians of Mesopotamia developed cuneiform around five thousand years ago, pressing wedge-shaped <b>marks</b> into clay tablets. Egyptian hieroglyphs combined pictorial symbols with phonetic signs to create a <b>flexible</b> system for recording everything from tax records to religious texts. <b>Chinese</b> characters, which first appeared on oracle bones over three thousand years ago, represent one of the oldest continuously used <b>writing</b> systems in the world. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>The alphabet, invented by Semitic-<b>speaking</b> peoples in the <b>Middle</b> <b>East</b>, was a revolutionary simplification. Instead of requiring hundreds or thousands of symbols, an alphabet uses a small set of letters representing individual sounds, which can be combined to <b>spell</b> any word. This innovation made <b>writing</b> far easier to <b>learn</b> and spread, and it was adapted by the Greeks, Romans, and eventually most of the world's languages. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>Today, <b>writing</b> has expanded beyond paper and <b>ink</b> to <b>include</b> digital <b>text</b> on screens, which can be <b>searched</b>, copied, and shared instantly across the globe. Yet the fundamental <b>purpose</b> remains the same: to capture human <b>thought</b> in a form that can travel through time and space, connecting <b>minds</b> across generations. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p>"}},{"name":"为什么有规则","entries":[{"cn":"每个人 pron. 每个人；人人","en":"everyone","type":"word"},{"cn":"使......能够,使......有能力","en":"enable","type":"word"},{"cn":"教室","en":"classroom","type":"word"},{"cn":"社区","en":"community","type":"word"},{"cn":"挑战；质疑","en":"challenge","type":"word"},{"cn":"产生预期结果的;有效的","en":"effective","type":"word"},{"cn":"(英式)足球；(美式)橄榄球","en":"football","type":"word"},{"cn":"礼物；赠品；现在","en":"present","type":"word"},{"cn":"自由","en":"freedom","type":"word"},{"cn":"听从；跟随；仿效；跟得上","en":"follow","type":"word"},{"cn":"使守规矩；使表现得","en":"behave","type":"word"},{"cn":"每日的；日常的","en":"daily","type":"word"},{"cn":"服务；招待；端上","en":"serve","type":"word"},{"cn":"花费；度过","en":"spend","type":"word"},{"cn":"路，道路","en":"road","type":"word"},{"cn":"伤害","en":"harm","type":"word"}],"passage":{"title":"Why We Have Rules","html":"<p>Rules are <b>present</b> in every human society, from the simplest family guidelines about bedtime to the most complex international treaties governing trade between nations. Why do we have so many rules, and why do most people <b>follow</b> them most of the time? <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>The most basic reason for rules is safety. Rules about which side of the <b>road</b> to drive on, how food should be prepared, and what materials can be used in buildings all exist to prevent <b>harm</b>. Without such rules, <b>daily</b> life would be far more dangerous, and people would have to <b>spend</b> much more time and energy protecting themselves from risks that rules now manage collectively. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>Beyond safety, rules <b>enable</b> cooperation. When <b>everyone</b> follows the same rules — whether in a game of <b>football</b>, a <b>classroom</b> discussion, or a business contract — people can work together toward shared goals. Rules create predictability: you can make plans because you have a reasonable expectation of how others will <b>behave</b>. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>However, not all rules are good or fair. Throughout history, societies have created rules that benefited some groups at the expense of others. The <b>challenge</b> for any <b>community</b> is to create rules that are both <b>effective</b> and just — rules that protect people and <b>enable</b> cooperation while respecting individual <b>freedom</b> and ensuring that <b>everyone</b> is treated with dignity. This is an ongoing process that requires constant attention and the willingness to change rules that no longer <b>serve</b> their purpose. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p>"}},{"name":"地图如何改变世界","entries":[{"cn":"理解；懂得","en":"understand","type":"word"},{"cn":"开始；开端","en":"beginning","type":"word"},{"cn":"可能的；也许的","en":"possible","type":"word"},{"cn":"太平洋","en":"pacific","type":"word"},{"cn":"非洲","en":"africa","type":"word"},{"cn":"地图","en":"map","type":"word"},{"cn":"片刻，瞬间","en":"moment","type":"word"},{"cn":"附近的","en":"nearby","type":"word"},{"cn":"当地的；地方的","en":"local","type":"word"},{"cn":"亚洲","en":"asia","type":"word"},{"cn":"到……上面","en":"onto","type":"word"},{"cn":"日期；约会","en":"date","type":"word"},{"cn":"另外,其他","en":"else","type":"word"},{"cn":"一套房间；公寓","en":"flat","type":"word"},{"cn":"真实的，真正的","en":"real","type":"word"},{"cn":"知道；认识；记得（know的过去式） n. (Knew)人名；(英)纽","en":"knew","type":"word"},{"cn":"眼睛（eye的复数） n. (Eyes)人名；(英)艾斯","en":"eyes","type":"word"}],"passage":{"title":"How Maps Changed the World","html":"<p>For most of human history, people's knowledge of the world was limited to what they could see with their own <b>eyes</b> or hear about from travelers. Maps changed this by allowing knowledge about distant places to be recorded, shared, and accumulated over generations. A good <b>map</b> is like a time capsule of geographic understanding, preserving what a society <b>knew</b> about the world at a particular <b>moment</b>. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>The earliest known maps <b>date</b> back thousands of years and were often carved into stone or drawn on clay. They showed <b>local</b> features — rivers, mountains, villages — that were important for hunting, farming, or travel. As societies grew more complex, maps became more sophisticated. The ancient Greeks were the first to develop the idea that the Earth is a sphere and to calculate its circumference with surprising accuracy. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>The Age of Exploration, <b>beginning</b> in the fifteenth century, drove a revolution in mapmaking. European voyages to the Americas, around <b>Africa</b> to <b>Asia</b>, and eventually across the <b>Pacific</b> filled in the blank spaces on the world <b>map</b>. Cartographers combined reports from explorers with mathematical techniques for projecting the curved surface of the Earth <b>onto</b> <b>flat</b> paper, creating maps that made global navigation <b>possible</b>. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>Today, digital maps on our phones give us information that would have seemed miraculous to earlier generations — not just where we are, but the fastest route to our destination, <b>real</b>-time traffic conditions, and reviews of <b>nearby</b> restaurants. Yet the fundamental purpose of maps has not changed: they help us <b>understand</b> where we are in relation to everything <b>else</b>. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p>"}},{"name":"团队合作的力量","entries":[{"cn":"工作；活动；制作；操纵 v. 工作；影响；受雇用（work的ing形式） ad","en":"working","type":"word"},{"cn":"成员；会员（member的复数）","en":"members","type":"word"},{"cn":"清晰的；明亮的；清楚的  清除；清扫","en":"clear","type":"word"},{"cn":"受到鼓舞的","en":"encourages","type":"word"},{"cn":"某事；某物","en":"something","type":"word"},{"cn":"小心地；仔细地","en":"carefully","type":"word"},{"cn":"发现；看出","en":"discover","type":"word"},{"cn":"队；组","en":"team","type":"word"},{"cn":"尊重，敬重","en":"respect","type":"word"},{"cn":"表达；表示","en":"express","type":"word"},{"cn":"自己；亲自","en":"oneself","type":"word"},{"cn":"听；仔细听","en":"listen","type":"word"},{"cn":"拿来，带来","en":"bring","type":"word"},{"cn":"单独的；单独地","en":"alone","type":"word"},{"cn":"桌子；表格","en":"table","type":"word"},{"cn":"部分；角色；部件；零件","en":"part","type":"word"},{"cn":"钥匙；答案；关键","en":"key","type":"word"}],"passage":{"title":"Teamwork","html":"<p>Human beings are social animals, and our ability to cooperate in large groups is one of the defining features of our species. Teamwork allows us to accomplish tasks that would be impossible for any individual <b>working</b> <b>alone</b> — from building a cathedral to sending a spacecraft to Mars. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>Effective teamwork depends on several <b>key</b> elements. <b>Clear</b> communication is essential: <b>team</b> <b>members</b> need to share information, <b>express</b> their ideas, and <b>listen</b> <b>carefully</b> to others. Trust is equally important — people must believe that their teammates are competent and committed to the shared goal. Good teams also benefit from diversity, because people with different backgrounds and perspectives <b>bring</b> complementary skills and fresh ideas to the <b>table</b>. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>The benefits of teamwork extend beyond the practical results. <b>Working</b> closely with others builds social bonds and a sense of belonging. When a <b>team</b> succeeds, the satisfaction is shared by all its <b>members</b>, and individuals often <b>discover</b> that they can achieve more than they thought possible. The experience of being <b>part</b> of <b>something</b> larger than <b>oneself</b> is deeply meaningful to most people. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>Yet teamwork also presents challenges. Conflicts can arise from disagreements about goals or methods, and some individuals may contribute less than their fair share. Effective teams develop ways to manage these problems — through <b>clear</b> roles, fair processes for making decisions, and a culture that <b>encourages</b> honest feedback while maintaining mutual <b>respect</b>. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p>"}},{"name":"语言如何演化","entries":[{"cn":"英国的;英国人的;英语的 英语;英国人","en":"english","type":"word"},{"cn":"的三单形式","en":"words","type":"word"},{"cn":"地理","en":"geography","type":"word"},{"cn":"孩子们（child的复数）","en":"children","type":"word"},{"cn":"意大利人；意大利语","en":"italian","type":"word"},{"cn":"意思，意义；含义","en":"meaning","type":"word"},{"cn":"比较，对照","en":"compare","type":"word"},{"cn":"法国的；法国人的；法语的 法国人；法语","en":"french","type":"word"},{"cn":"本地的；本国的；当地的","en":"native","type":"word"},{"cn":"年老的；古老的；旧的","en":"old","type":"word"},{"cn":"取得；捕获；营业收入 v. 拿；捕捉；夺取（take的ing形式） adj. 可爱的；迷人的；会传染的","en":"taking","type":"word"},{"cn":"说；讲","en":"speak","type":"word"},{"cn":"曾经;无论何时","en":"ever","type":"word"},{"cn":"知道；了解；认识；懂得","en":"know","type":"word"},{"cn":"最近刚过去的；最后的","en":"last","type":"word"}],"passage":{"title":"How Languages Evolve","html":"<p>Language is one of the most remarkable abilities that humans possess, yet we still do not fully understand how it first emerged. What we do <b>know</b> is that all human societies have language, and that <b>children</b> everywhere learn to <b>speak</b> their <b>native</b> language in roughly the same way and at roughly the same pace. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>Languages are not fixed — they change constantly over time. <b>Words</b> shift in <b>meaning</b>, new <b>words</b> are invented, <b>old</b> <b>words</b> fall out of use, and grammatical structures gradually transform. If you <b>compare</b> <b>English</b> from a thousand years ago with modern <b>English</b>, they are almost entirely different languages, even though one evolved directly from the other. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>When groups of speakers become separated — by <b>geography</b>, migration, or social barriers — their languages drift apart. Over centuries, what began as regional dialects can develop into separate languages. This process explains why Spanish, <b>French</b>, <b>Italian</b>, and Portuguese are all descended from Latin, and why they share many similarities despite being distinct languages today. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>In the modern world, languages are evolving faster than <b>ever</b> before. The internet has created new forms of communication, from emojis to memes. <b>English</b> has become a global language, absorbing <b>words</b> from hundreds of other tongues. Meanwhile, many smaller languages are disappearing as their <b>last</b> speakers grow <b>old</b>, <b>taking</b> with them unique ways of seeing and describing the world. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p>"}},{"name":"国家为何有贫富","entries":[{"cn":"的复数","en":"countries","type":"word"},{"cn":"困难的；费力的","en":"difficult","type":"word"},{"cn":"今天；当今","en":"today","type":"word"},{"cn":"自然的；天然的","en":"natural","type":"word"},{"cn":"病，[医] 疾病；弊病 vt. 传染；使…有病","en":"disease","type":"word"},{"cn":"发展","en":"development","type":"word"},{"cn":"历史的,历史上的","en":"historical","type":"word"},{"cn":"不同","en":"difference","type":"word"},{"cn":"经验；经历","en":"experience","type":"word"},{"cn":"教育","en":"education","type":"word"},{"cn":"地理","en":"geography","type":"word"},{"cn":"重要的","en":"important","type":"word"},{"cn":"建筑物；大楼","en":"building","type":"word"},{"cn":"贫穷的；可怜的；不好的","en":"poor","type":"word"},{"cn":"继续","en":"continue","type":"word"},{"cn":"普通的，平常的","en":"ordinary","type":"word"},{"cn":"可能的；也许的","en":"possible","type":"word"},{"cn":"的复数","en":"problems","type":"word"},{"cn":"；市民","en":"citizens","type":"word"},{"cn":"在(两者)之间；在……中间","en":"between","type":"word"},{"cn":"历史;历史学","en":"history","type":"word"},{"cn":"有…相貌的；有…样子的","en":"looking","type":"word"},{"cn":"人；人们；人民","en":"people","type":"word"},{"cn":"强壮的；坚强的","en":"strong","type":"word"},{"cn":"活的；现存的；活跃的；逼真的 n. 生活；生存；生计 v. 生活；居住（live的ing形式）；度过 n. (Living)人名；(英)利","en":"living","type":"word"},{"cn":"其他人","en":"others","type":"word"},{"cn":"间隙；缺口；差距；分歧 vt. 使形成缺口 vi. 裂开","en":"gap","type":"word"},{"cn":"欣赏;享受;喜欢","en":"enjoy","type":"word"},{"cn":"当地的；地方的","en":"local","type":"word"},{"cn":"贸易；交易","en":"trade","type":"word"}],"passage":{"title":"Why Some Countries Are Rich","html":"<p>The <b>gap</b> <b>between</b> rich and <b>poor</b> <b>countries</b> is one of the most persistent and <b>difficult</b> <b>problems</b> in the world <b>today</b>. While some nations <b>enjoy</b> high standards of <b>living</b> with advanced healthcare, <b>education</b>, and infrastructure, <b>others</b> struggle with poverty, <b>disease</b>, and political instability. Understanding why this <b>gap</b> exists requires <b>looking</b> at a complex mix of <b>historical</b>, geographic, and institutional factors. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p><b>Geography</b> plays a significant role. <b>Countries</b> with access to navigable rivers and <b>natural</b> harbors have historically had advantages in <b>trade</b> and transportation. Those in tropical regions face challenges like higher rates of infectious <b>disease</b> and soils that are less suitable for productive agriculture. Climate and <b>natural</b> resources shape economic possibilities, though they do not determine them absolutely. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p><b>History</b> matters enormously. Many of <b>today</b>'s <b>poor</b> <b>countries</b> were colonized by European powers, which extracted their resources and established economic systems designed to benefit the colonizers rather than <b>local</b> populations. The effects of colonialism — including arbitrary borders, weak institutions, and economies dependent on exporting raw materials — <b>continue</b> to shape <b>development</b> <b>today</b>. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>Institutions are perhaps the most <b>important</b> factor. <b>Countries</b> with <b>strong</b> legal systems, protection of property rights, reliable infrastructure, and governments that are accountable to their <b>citizens</b> tend to prosper. <b>Building</b> such institutions is <b>difficult</b> and takes time, but <b>experience</b> shows that it is <b>possible</b> — and that it makes a tremendous <b>difference</b> in the lives of <b>ordinary</b> <b>people</b>. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p>"}},{"name":"广告的力量","entries":[{"cn":"友谊","en":"friendship","type":"word"},{"cn":"幸福;快乐","en":"happiness","type":"word"},{"cn":"给……看；展示；表明","en":"show","type":"word"},{"cn":"服务","en":"service","type":"word"},{"cn":"产品","en":"product","type":"word"},{"cn":"数量，总额（amount的复数） v. 总和（amount的第三人称单数形式）","en":"amounts","type":"word"},{"cn":"成功，成就；胜利；大获成功的人或事物","en":"success","type":"word"},{"cn":"买","en":"buy","type":"word"},{"cn":"搜索；搜寻","en":"search","type":"word"},{"cn":"设计；策划","en":"design","type":"word"},{"cn":"在线的","en":"online","type":"word"},{"cn":"高度地；非常；非常赞许地","en":"highly","type":"word"},{"cn":"海滨，海滩","en":"beach","type":"word"},{"cn":"(鼠标)点击","en":"click","type":"word"},{"cn":"赫尔普斯","en":"helps","type":"word"},{"cn":"绘画；绘制；拉，拖","en":"draw","type":"word"},{"cn":"看；瞧","en":"look","type":"word"},{"cn":"软的；柔软的","en":"soft","type":"word"},{"cn":"欢乐；高兴；乐趣","en":"joy","type":"word"}],"passage":{"title":"The Power of Advertising","html":"<p>Advertising surrounds us in modern life. On television, on websites, on billboards, on the sides of buses, and now on our phones — we encounter thousands of commercial messages every day. Advertising is so common that we often stop noticing it, but its influence on our decisions and desires is profound. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>The basic goal of advertising is simple: to persuade people to <b>buy</b> a <b>product</b>, use a <b>service</b>, or support a cause. To achieve this, advertisers <b>draw</b> on psychology, storytelling, and <b>design</b>. They create associations between their products and positive emotions — <b>happiness</b>, <b>success</b>, attractiveness, belonging. A <b>soft</b> drink commercial might <b>show</b> young people laughing together at a <b>beach</b> party, suggesting that buying the drink will bring <b>friendship</b> and <b>joy</b>. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>Modern advertising has become <b>highly</b> targeted. Companies collect vast <b>amounts</b> of data about our <b>online</b> behavior — what we <b>search</b> for, what we <b>click</b> on, how long we <b>look</b> at certain items — and use this information to <b>show</b> us advertisements tailored to our individual interests and vulnerabilities. This makes advertising more effective but also raises serious concerns about privacy and manipulation. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>As consumers, the best defense against the power of advertising is awareness. Understanding how advertisements work — the techniques they use, the emotions they appeal to, the promises they make — <b>helps</b> us make more deliberate choices about what we <b>buy</b> and why. In a world saturated with commercial messages, critical thinking is an essential survival skill. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p>"}},{"name":"互联网如何连接世界","entries":[{"cn":"的复数","en":"computers","type":"word"},{"cn":"技术","en":"technology","type":"word"},{"cn":"可用的；可得到的","en":"available","type":"word"},{"cn":"地址","en":"address","type":"word"},{"cn":"正确的  v. 改正；纠正","en":"correct","type":"word"},{"cn":"现实；实际；真实","en":"reality","type":"word"},{"cn":"忘记；忘掉","en":"forget","type":"word"},{"cn":"到达；达到","en":"arrive","type":"word"},{"cn":"商店","en":"shop","type":"word"},{"cn":"发送；寄；派遣","en":"send","type":"word"},{"cn":"容易的;不费力的","en":"easy","type":"word"}],"passage":{"title":"How the Internet Connects Us","html":"<p>The internet has transformed human communication more dramatically than any <b>technology</b> since the printing press. In just a few decades, it has changed how we work, learn, <b>shop</b>, socialize, and access information. To understand how the internet connects us, it helps to understand what it actually is: a global network of <b>computers</b> linked by cables, satellites, and wireless signals, all speaking a common set of digital languages called protocols. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>When you <b>send</b> an email or load a webpage, your computer breaks the information into small packets of data. Each packet is labeled with its destination <b>address</b> and sent out into the network. Routers — specialized <b>computers</b> that direct traffic — read these labels and forward each packet along the best <b>available</b> path. The packets may travel through different routes, but they are reassembled in the <b>correct</b> order when they <b>arrive</b> at their destination. All of this happens in milliseconds. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>The physical infrastructure of the internet is staggering in its scale. Undersea fiber optic cables, some stretching over ten thousand kilometers across ocean floors, carry most intercontinental traffic. Data centers — enormous warehouses filled with thousands of <b>computers</b> — store and process the information that powers websites, apps, and cloud services. This physical <b>reality</b> is <b>easy</b> to <b>forget</b> because the internet feels invisible and weightless, but it is very much a material thing. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>The social impact of the internet continues to unfold. It has democratized access to knowledge, enabled global social movements, created entirely new industries, and allowed people separated by vast distances to maintain close relationships. It has also amplified misinformation, eroded privacy, and concentrated enormous power in a handful of <b>technology</b> companies. The challenge for society is to preserve the benefits of connection while addressing the harms. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p>"}},{"name":"人口迁徙的原因","entries":[{"cn":"离开；把……留下；剩下","en":"leave","type":"word"},{"cn":"开始；启动","en":"start","type":"word"},{"cn":"的名词复数","en":"businesses","type":"word"},{"cn":"离开","en":"departure","type":"word"},{"cn":"在……外 在外面","en":"outside","type":"word"},{"cn":"欢迎","en":"welcome","type":"word"},{"cn":"吸引；引起","en":"attract","type":"word"},{"cn":"问题，难题，习题","en":"problem","type":"word"},{"cn":"百万；无数 adj. 百万的；无数的 num. 百万 n. (Million)人名；(法、罗、埃塞)米利翁","en":"million","type":"word"},{"cn":"出生﹐诞生；产生﹐出现﹐形成","en":"born","type":"word"},{"cn":"填空；装满；充满","en":"fill","type":"word"},{"cn":"伤害(身体、感情等);痛;使受伤痛;使烦恼；受伤的","en":"hurt","type":"word"},{"cn":"顺利地﹔令人满意地","en":"well","type":"word"},{"cn":"需要；缺乏；贫困；必","en":"want","type":"word"},{"cn":"二","en":"two","type":"word"}],"passage":{"title":"Why People Migrate","html":"<p>People have always moved from one place to another, but the scale and patterns of human migration have changed dramatically throughout history. Today, more than 280 <b>million</b> people live <b>outside</b> the country where they were <b>born</b>, making migration one of the defining issues of our time. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>People migrate for many reasons, but they generally fall into <b>two</b> categories: push factors and pull factors. Push factors are conditions that make people <b>want</b> to <b>leave</b> their homes — war, persecution, natural disasters, lack of economic opportunity, political oppression. Pull factors are conditions that <b>attract</b> people to a particular destination — jobs, safety, freedom, family connections, better education for their children. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>Migration is often portrayed as a <b>problem</b>, but it brings significant benefits. Migrants <b>fill</b> labor shortages, <b>start</b> <b>businesses</b> at high rates, contribute to cultural diversity, and send money back to their home countries — remittances that often exceed foreign aid. Countries that <b>welcome</b> immigrants tend to be more dynamic and innovative, in part because people who choose to uproot their lives and <b>start</b> over in a new place tend to be especially motivated and resourceful. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>At the same time, migration poses genuine challenges. Rapid influxes of people can strain housing, schools, and healthcare systems. Cultural differences can create tensions. And the <b>departure</b> of large numbers of young, skilled workers can <b>hurt</b> the countries they <b>leave</b> behind. Managing migration <b>well</b> — with policies that are both humane and practical — is one of the great tests facing governments around the world. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p>"}},{"name":"教育的角色","entries":[{"cn":"的复数","en":"students","type":"word"},{"cn":"研究；调查","en":"research","type":"word"},{"cn":"一贯地；一致地；坚实地","en":"consistently","type":"word"},{"cn":"教育的","en":"educational","type":"word"},{"cn":"重要性","en":"importance","type":"word"},{"cn":"准备（prepare的ing形式） adj. 准备的","en":"preparing","type":"word"},{"cn":"创造性的，有创意的","en":"creative","type":"word"},{"cn":"训练；教导；培育（educate的过去分词形式） adj. 受过教育的；有教养的","en":"educated","type":"word"},{"cn":"错误（mistake的复数形式） v. 误解（mistake的第三人称单数形式）；弄错","en":"mistakes","type":"word"},{"cn":"很可能的","en":"likely","type":"word"},{"cn":"孩子，儿童","en":"child","type":"word"},{"cn":"年","en":"year","type":"word"}],"passage":{"title":"The Role of Education","html":"<p>Education is one of the most powerful tools for improving individual lives and entire societies. <b>Research</b> <b>consistently</b> shows that each additional <b>year</b> of schooling increases a person's future earnings, improves their health, and makes them more <b>likely</b> to participate in civic life. The benefits extend beyond the individual: <b>educated</b> populations drive economic growth, foster innovation, and strengthen democratic institutions. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>The purpose of education has been debated for centuries. Is it primarily about <b>preparing</b> young people for the workforce, or is it about developing thoughtful, well-rounded citizens? Should schools focus on practical skills or on exposing <b>students</b> to the great ideas of human civilization? Most modern education systems try to balance these goals, offering a combination of academic subjects, vocational training, and opportunities for <b>creative</b> and physical development. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>How children learn is just as important as what they learn. <b>Educational</b> <b>research</b> has shown that <b>students</b> learn best when they are actively engaged — asking questions, solving problems, discussing ideas with peers — rather than passively listening to lectures. Effective teachers create environments where <b>students</b> feel safe to make <b>mistakes</b>, where curiosity is encouraged, and where each <b>child</b>'s individual strengths and challenges are recognized and addressed. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>Despite its <b>importance</b>, quality education remains out of reach for millions of children around the world. Poverty, conflict, discrimination, and lack of infrastructure keep many young people from attending school. Closing this gap is not only a moral imperative but also one of the smartest investments any society can make in its own future. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p>"}},{"name":"市场如何运作","entries":[{"cn":"市场；集市","en":"market","type":"word"},{"cn":"价格","en":"price","type":"word"},{"cn":"鼓励","en":"encourage","type":"word"},{"cn":"客户；[贸易] 顾客（customer的复数）","en":"customers","type":"word"},{"cn":"完美的；极好的","en":"perfect","type":"word"},{"cn":"答案，回答（answer的复数） v. 回答（answer的三单形式）","en":"answers","type":"word"},{"cn":"面包","en":"bread","type":"word"},{"cn":"史密斯（男子姓氏）","en":"smith","type":"word"},{"cn":"给，传递（hand的单三形式） n. (Hands)人名；(英)汉兹","en":"hands","type":"word"},{"cn":"牛奶","en":"milk","type":"word"},{"cn":"失败；不及格","en":"fail","type":"word"},{"cn":"手;指针；递;给;交付;交进","en":"hand","type":"word"},{"cn":"付钱，给……报酬 工资","en":"pay","type":"word"},{"cn":"切；剪；削；割","en":"cut","type":"word"}],"passage":{"title":"How Markets Work","html":"<p>A <b>market</b> is any arrangement that allows buyers and sellers to exchange goods or services. The simplest <b>market</b> might be a neighborhood shop where <b>customers</b> <b>pay</b> money for <b>bread</b> and <b>milk</b>. At the other extreme, global financial markets handle trillions of dollars in trades every day, connecting investors in Tokyo with borrowers in New York. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>The <b>price</b> mechanism is the central feature of markets. When many people want to buy a product but the supply is limited, the <b>price</b> rises. Higher prices <b>encourage</b> producers to make more of the product, while also encouraging some buyers to seek alternatives. When supply exceeds demand, prices fall, producers <b>cut</b> back, and buyers are attracted by the lower cost. This constant adjustment, described by the economist Adam <b>Smith</b> as an invisible <b>hand</b>, coordinates the decisions of millions of people without any central planner. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>Markets are remarkably efficient at allocating resources, but they are not <b>perfect</b>. They can <b>fail</b> to account for environmental costs, leading to pollution and resource depletion. They can produce extreme inequality, concentrating wealth in the <b>hands</b> of a few while others struggle. And they can be unstable, swinging between booms and crashes that cause widespread hardship. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>Governments intervene in markets to address these failures — through regulation, taxation, public services, and social safety nets. The debate about the proper balance between <b>market</b> freedom and government intervention is one of the central questions of modern politics, and different societies have arrived at very different <b>answers</b>. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p>"}},{"name":"数字时代的隐私","entries":[{"cn":"控制","en":"control","type":"word"},{"cn":"你自己","en":"yourself","type":"word"},{"cn":"班长；监视器","en":"monitor","type":"word"},{"cn":"保管；一致；协调；遵守 v. 保持；遵守（keep的ing形式）","en":"keeping","type":"word"},{"cn":"照相机","en":"camera","type":"word"},{"cn":"行动；活动；功能；战斗；情节 n. (Action)人名；(英)埃克申","en":"action","type":"word"},{"cn":"日记；日记簿","en":"diary","type":"word"},{"cn":"极限；限制；限度；界限","en":"limit","type":"word"},{"cn":"参观；访问；拜访","en":"visit","type":"word"},{"cn":"门；通道","en":"door","type":"word"}],"passage":{"title":"Privacy in the Digital Age","html":"<p>Privacy, the ability to <b>control</b> what information about <b>yourself</b> is shared with others, has been valued across cultures and throughout history. But the digital age has transformed privacy from a relatively simple matter — closing your <b>door</b>, speaking in private, <b>keeping</b> a <b>diary</b> under lock and key — into an extraordinarily complex challenge. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>Every time you use a smartphone, <b>visit</b> a website, make an electronic payment, or walk past a security <b>camera</b>, you leave behind digital traces. Companies collect this data and combine it with information from other sources to build detailed profiles of your habits, preferences, relationships, and movements. This data has enormous commercial value — it allows advertisers to target you with uncanny precision and helps companies decide what products to develop and how to price them. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>The loss of privacy has consequences that go beyond annoying advertisements. Detailed personal data can be used to manipulate behavior, discriminate against certain groups, or expose people to harm. In authoritarian countries, surveillance technology enables governments to <b>monitor</b> and suppress dissent on an unprecedented scale. Even in democratic societies, the concentration of data in the hands of a few powerful companies raises troubling questions about accountability. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>Protecting privacy in the digital age requires <b>action</b> on multiple fronts: laws that <b>limit</b> what data can be collected and how it can be used, technology that gives users more <b>control</b> over their information, and education that helps people understand the tradeoffs they are making. The goal is not to reject technology but to ensure that it serves human values rather than undermining them. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p>"}},{"name":"社区如何解决问题","entries":[{"cn":"准确的","en":"accurate","type":"word"},{"cn":"清晰地；明亮地；清楚地","en":"clearly","type":"word"},{"cn":"单一的；单个的；单身的","en":"single","type":"word"},{"cn":"精力,努力","en":"effort","type":"word"},{"cn":"折断；打碎；损坏（break的过去分词） adj. 破碎的；坏掉的","en":"broken","type":"word"},{"cn":"解决（solve的过去式）；解答 adj. 解决了的","en":"solved","type":"word"},{"cn":"组;群","en":"group","type":"word"},{"cn":"解决；解答","en":"solve","type":"word"},{"cn":"一次；一度；从前","en":"once","type":"word"},{"cn":"来；来到","en":"come","type":"word"},{"cn":"计划，打算","en":"plan","type":"word"},{"cn":"坏的；有害的；糟糕的","en":"bad","type":"word"}],"passage":{"title":"How Communities Solve Problems","html":"<p>Every community faces problems — from <b>broken</b> streetlights to rising crime rates to polluted waterways. What distinguishes successful communities is not the absence of problems but the ability to <b>solve</b> them effectively. The most powerful solutions often <b>come</b> not from distant governments or outside experts, but from the people who live in the community and understand its challenges firsthand. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>Effective community problem-solving begins with identifying issues <b>clearly</b> and gathering <b>accurate</b> information. This might involve surveys, public meetings, or simply conversations among neighbors. The next step is to bring together the people and organizations that have a stake in the issue — residents, business owners, local officials, schools, and community groups. Building trust among these stakeholders is essential, because problems are rarely <b>solved</b> by any <b>single</b> person or <b>group</b> acting alone. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p><b>Once</b> a <b>plan</b> is developed, implementation requires sustained <b>effort</b>. This means finding resources — money, materials, volunteers, expertise — and coordinating the work over time. Many promising ideas fail not because they were <b>bad</b> ideas but because no one followed through. Successful communities build institutions and habits that keep projects moving forward even when initial enthusiasm fades. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>The benefits of community problem-solving extend far beyond the specific issues addressed. The process itself builds social connections, develops leadership skills, and creates a sense of shared ownership and pride. When people work together to make their neighborhood better, they strengthen the fabric of trust and cooperation that makes democracy possible at every level of society. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p>"}},{"name":"人体日常运转","entries":[{"cn":"考虑","en":"consider","type":"word"},{"cn":"极小的；微小的","en":"tiny","type":"word"},{"cn":"胃；腹部","en":"stomach","type":"word"},{"cn":"讲话，谈论 v. 谈论；讲话（talk的ing形式） adj. 说话的，多嘴的；有表情的 n. (Talking)人名；(英)托金","en":"talking","type":"word"},{"cn":"七十；七十个；七十岁；七十年代 num. 七十 adj. 七十的；七十个的；七十岁的","en":"seventy","type":"word"},{"cn":"手指","en":"finger","type":"word"},{"cn":"末尾;终点;结束 结束,终止","en":"end","type":"word"},{"cn":"睡着的","en":"asleep","type":"word"},{"cn":"二十的","en":"twenty","type":"word"},{"cn":"想；认为；思考","en":"think","type":"word"},{"cn":"活着的；存在的","en":"alive","type":"word"},{"cn":"心脏跳动（beat的复数）；音乐节拍；[物] 差拍振动 v. 敲打（beat的第三人称单数形式）；（心脏等）跳动（beat的第三人称单数）；搜索；（风、雨等）吹打；（鼓）咚咚地响","en":"beats","type":"word"},{"cn":"书；本子；预订，订(房间、车票、座位等)","en":"book","type":"word"},{"cn":"书桌，写字台","en":"desk","type":"word"},{"cn":"心情，语气，气氛","en":"mood","type":"word"},{"cn":"事实；现实；实际","en":"fact","type":"word"},{"cn":"放；铺设；安排（lay的过去分词） adj. 松弛的；从容不迫的 n. (Laid)人名；(瑞典)莱德","en":"laid","type":"word"},{"cn":"公共汽车","en":"bus","type":"word"}],"passage":{"title":"How Your Body Works Every Day","html":"<p>Every ordinary day, your body performs millions of complex operations without any conscious effort on your part. From the moment you wake up in the morning until you fall <b>asleep</b> at night, systems that evolved over hundreds of millions of years work together to keep you <b>alive</b>, alert, and functioning. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p><b>Consider</b> what happens when you eat breakfast. Your teeth and tongue work together to break food into smaller pieces, while enzymes in your saliva begin the chemical process of digestion. The food travels down your esophagus to your <b>stomach</b>, where powerful acids and more enzymes continue breaking it down. In your small intestine, nutrients are absorbed through <b>tiny</b> <b>finger</b>-like projections into your bloodstream, from where they travel to every cell in your body. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>While you go about your daily activities — walking to the <b>bus</b> stop, climbing stairs, carrying bags — your muscles, bones, and joints coordinate with remarkable precision. Your heart <b>beats</b> about <b>seventy</b> times each minute, pumping blood through a network of vessels that would stretch over one hundred thousand kilometers if <b>laid</b> <b>end</b> to <b>end</b>. Your lungs expand and contract roughly <b>twenty</b> thousand times each day, extracting oxygen from the air and expelling carbon dioxide. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>Even during quiet moments — sitting at a <b>desk</b>, reading a <b>book</b>, <b>talking</b> with a friend — your brain hums with activity. It processes sensory information from your eyes, ears, skin, and internal organs. It retrieves memories, generates thoughts, regulates your <b>mood</b>, and makes countless <b>tiny</b> decisions. The <b>fact</b> that all of this happens seamlessly, billions of times each day, without you having to <b>think</b> about it, is one of the true wonders of human biology. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p>"}},{"name":"人类为什么讲故事","entries":[{"cn":"经验；经历","en":"experience","type":"word"},{"cn":"的复数","en":"stories","type":"word"},{"cn":"娱乐;消遣;款待","en":"entertainment","type":"word"},{"cn":"发展；制造；形成 v. 制作（make的现在分词）","en":"making","type":"word"},{"cn":"人的;人类的； 人类","en":"human","type":"word"},{"cn":"脑","en":"brain","type":"word"},{"cn":"技术","en":"technology","type":"word"},{"cn":"历史的,历史上的","en":"historical","type":"word"},{"cn":"庆祝","en":"celebrate","type":"word"},{"cn":"知识；学问","en":"knowledge","type":"word"},{"cn":"语言","en":"language","type":"word"},{"cn":"强大的","en":"powerful","type":"word"},{"cn":"活动","en":"activity","type":"word"},{"cn":"旅行；旅程","en":"journey","type":"word"},{"cn":"穿过；通过","en":"through","type":"word"},{"cn":"意思，意义；含义","en":"meaning","type":"word"},{"cn":"社会","en":"society","type":"word"},{"cn":"解释；说明","en":"explain","type":"word"},{"cn":"想象;设想","en":"imagine","type":"word"},{"cn":"很多地﹐大量地﹔非常﹔严重地；睡得沉","en":"heavily","type":"word"},{"cn":"文化","en":"culture","type":"word"},{"cn":"没有；超过；在…外面 n. 外部；外面 adv. 户外；在外面；没有或不显示某事物","en":"without","type":"word"},{"cn":"人；人们；人民","en":"people","type":"word"},{"cn":"横过，穿过","en":"across","type":"word"},{"cn":"在周围；环绕；在……周围","en":"around","type":"word"},{"cn":"将来，未来","en":"future","type":"word"},{"cn":"现代的","en":"modern","type":"word"},{"cn":"社会的；社交的","en":"social","type":"word"},{"cn":"屏幕；银幕","en":"screen","type":"word"},{"cn":"单一的；单个的；单身的","en":"single","type":"word"}],"passage":{"title":"Why We Tell Stories","html":"<p><b>Stories</b> are among the most fundamental <b>human</b> creations, predating written <b>language</b> and spanning every <b>culture</b> on Earth. At their core, <b>stories</b> serve as vehicles for <b>meaning</b>-<b>making</b> — they help us organize the chaos of <b>experience</b> into coherent narratives that <b>explain</b> who we are, where we come from, and what we value. This drive to narrate is not merely <b>entertainment</b>; it is a cognitive imperative deeply wired into the <b>human</b> <b>brain</b>. From an evolutionary perspective, storytelling likely conferred significant survival advantages. By sharing accounts of dangers, successful hunts, or medicinal plants, early humans transmitted crucial <b>knowledge</b> <b>across</b> generations <b>without</b> requiring every individual to learn <b>through</b> direct <b>experience</b>. A well-told story about a poisonous berry could save countless lives, <b>making</b> narrative a form of cultural <b>technology</b> more <b>powerful</b> than any <b>single</b> tool. <b>Stories</b> also function as <b>social</b> glue. When <b>people</b> gather <b>around</b> a fire or a <b>screen</b> and share a narrative, they <b>experience</b> a synchronization of <b>brain</b> <b>activity</b> that fosters empathy and group cohesion. This shared emotional <b>journey</b> builds trust and reinforces communal values, which is why every <b>society</b> invests so <b>heavily</b> in its myths, legends, and <b>historical</b> accounts. In the <b>modern</b> era, storytelling has expanded into countless media including novels, films, video games, and podcasts, yet the essential function remains unchanged. We tell <b>stories</b> to make sense of suffering, to <b>celebrate</b> joy, to warn against danger, and to <b>imagine</b> possibilities beyond our immediate circumstances. In doing so, we not only preserve the past but also shape the <b>future</b>, one narrative at a time. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p>"}},{"name":"丝绸之路","entries":[{"cn":"丝绸；丝织品","en":"silk","type":"word"},{"cn":"连接（connect的过去式） adj. [计] 连接的；有联系的；连贯的","en":"connected","type":"word"},{"cn":"相似的","en":"similar","type":"word"},{"cn":"十五；十五个；十五人组成的橄榄球队 num. 十五 adj. 十五的","en":"fifteen","type":"word"},{"cn":"美","en":"beauty","type":"word"},{"cn":"日本","en":"japan","type":"word"},{"cn":"真相；事实；真理","en":"truth","type":"word"},{"cn":"名字；姓名；名称","en":"name","type":"word"},{"cn":"罗马","en":"rome","type":"word"},{"cn":"羊毛","en":"wool","type":"word"},{"cn":"茶；茶叶","en":"tea","type":"word"},{"cn":"六","en":"six","type":"word"}],"passage":{"title":"The Silk Road","html":"<p>The <b>Silk</b> Road was not a single road but a vast network of trade routes that <b>connected</b> East Asia with the Mediterranean world for over <b>fifteen</b> hundred years. Spanning approximately <b>six</b> thousand four hundred kilometers across some of the world's most challenging terrains including deserts, mountains, and steppes, this network facilitated an unprecedented exchange of goods, ideas, technologies, and cultures. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>The <b>name</b> <b>Silk</b> Road highlights the commodity most famously associated with these routes. Chinese <b>silk</b>, a fabric of extraordinary <b>beauty</b> and durability, was highly prized in <b>Rome</b>, Persia, and beyond. But the trade was never one-directional. While <b>silk</b>, <b>tea</b>, and porcelain traveled westward, goods such as glassware, <b>wool</b>, gold, and silver moved eastward. Horses from the Ferghana Valley were another crucial commodity. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>Yet the <b>Silk</b> Road's most transformative exchanges were not material but intellectual. Buddhism traveled from its birthplace in India through Central Asia to China, Korea, and <b>Japan</b>, profoundly reshaping the religious and cultural landscape of East Asia. Technologies moved as well: papermaking reached the Islamic world and eventually Europe through <b>Silk</b> Road contacts, revolutionizing the transmission of knowledge. Gunpowder and the compass followed <b>similar</b> paths. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>The <b>Silk</b> Road also facilitated the spread of disease, most notably the bubonic plague that devastated both East Asia and Europe in the fourteenth century. The routes declined with the rise of maritime trade in the age of exploration. Nevertheless, the <b>Silk</b> Road's legacy endures in the shared heritage of the lands it once linked, and in the enduring <b>truth</b> that human flourishing has always depended on exchange across borders. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p>"}},{"name":"改变世界的发明","entries":[{"cn":"组织；团体；机构","en":"organization","type":"word"},{"cn":"电","en":"electricity","type":"word"},{"cn":"全国性的；国家的；民族的","en":"national","type":"word"},{"cn":"动手术，开刀；操作；运转","en":"operate","type":"word"},{"cn":"钟","en":"clock","type":"word"},{"cn":"嗓音；声音","en":"voice","type":"word"},{"cn":"找到（find的过去分词） vt. 创立，建立；创办","en":"found","type":"word"},{"cn":"书籍（book的复数）；书评 v. 预订；领会（book的第三人称单数）；把…记载入册","en":"books","type":"word"},{"cn":"晚的；迟的","en":"late","type":"word"},{"cn":"握住（hold的过去分词）；举起,抬起；使升高；展示；提出(作为榜样)(后与as连用) n. (Held)人名；(英、瑞典)赫尔德；(德、捷)黑尔德；(罗、匈、塞)海尔德","en":"held","type":"word"}],"passage":{"title":"Inventions That Changed Life","html":"<p>Throughout history, certain inventions have fundamentally restructured human existence, altering not just how we perform tasks but how we conceive of ourselves and our possibilities. These transformative innovations rarely announce their full significance at the moment of their creation; instead, their true impact unfolds across generations as societies adapt to new capabilities and abandon old constraints. The printing press, developed by Johannes Gutenberg in the fifteenth century, exemplifies this pattern. By making <b>books</b> affordable and widely available, it shattered the monopoly on knowledge that had been <b>held</b> by religious and political elites. Literacy spread, the Reformation <b>found</b> its <b>voice</b>, and the scientific revolution accelerated as ideas could be shared, challenged, and refined across continents. <b>Electricity</b> represents another threshold moment in human history. Before its widespread adoption, daily life was governed by the rhythm of the sun; after electrification, the night became a domain of productivity and leisure. Factories could <b>operate</b> around the <b>clock</b>, homes gained refrigeration and lighting, and entirely new industries emerged. The internet, arguably the most consequential invention of the <b>late</b> twentieth century, has reshaped communication, commerce, and community. It has collapsed geographic distance, democratized access to information, and created new forms of social <b>organization</b> that transcend <b>national</b> borders. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p>"}},{"name":"时尚如何反映文化","entries":[{"cn":"时尚","en":"fashion","type":"word"},{"cn":"历史的,历史上的","en":"historical","type":"word"},{"cn":"社会的；社交的","en":"social","type":"word"},{"cn":"世界","en":"world","type":"word"},{"cn":"会话；谈话","en":"conversation","type":"word"},{"cn":"传统的","en":"traditional","type":"word"},{"cn":"挑战；质疑","en":"challenge","type":"word"},{"cn":"交换；交流","en":"exchange","type":"word"},{"cn":"丝绸；丝织品","en":"silk","type":"word"},{"cn":"/, worn /wɔːn/) 穿；戴","en":"wear","type":"word"},{"cn":"个人的；私人的","en":"personal","type":"word"},{"cn":"中国的；中国人的；汉语的  中国人；汉语","en":"chinese","type":"word"},{"cn":"世纪；百年","en":"century","type":"word"},{"cn":"衣服","en":"clothes","type":"word"},{"cn":"的复数","en":"stories","type":"word"},{"cn":"人；人们；人民","en":"people","type":"word"},{"cn":"欧洲","en":"europe","type":"word"},{"cn":"黄色的 黄色","en":"yellow","type":"word"},{"cn":"镜子","en":"mirror","type":"word"},{"cn":"变得；成为","en":"become","type":"word"},{"cn":"改变；更换；兑换；n. 零钱；变化","en":"change","type":"word"},{"cn":"选择","en":"choose","type":"word"},{"cn":"要紧事；麻烦事；事情；问题；物质","en":"matter","type":"word"},{"cn":"记录；唱片 /rɪˈkɔːd/ 录制；记录","en":"record","type":"word"},{"cn":"活的；现存的；活跃的；逼真的 n. 生活；生存；生计 v. 生活；居住（live的ing形式）；度过 n. (Living)人名；(英)利","en":"living","type":"word"},{"cn":"伊文茨","en":"events","type":"word"},{"cn":"发展；制造；形成 v. 制作（make的现在分词）","en":"making","type":"word"},{"cn":"品尝；尝起来 味道；品味","en":"taste","type":"word"},{"cn":"瓷器","en":"china","type":"word"},{"cn":"离开；把……留下；剩下","en":"leave","type":"word"}],"passage":{"title":"How Fashion Reflects Culture","html":"<p><b>Fashion</b> is far more than a <b>matter</b> of <b>personal</b> <b>taste</b> or seasonal trends; it is a <b>living</b> <b>record</b> of cultural values, <b>social</b> hierarchies, and <b>historical</b> <b>change</b>. The <b>clothes</b> <b>people</b> <b>wear</b>, the fabrics they <b>choose</b>, and the silhouettes they favor all tell <b>stories</b> about economic conditions, political movements, technological capabilities, and collective identity. Clothing has long served as a marker of <b>social</b> status and group affiliation. In medieval <b>Europe</b>, sumptuary laws explicitly regulated who could <b>wear</b> certain colors, furs, or fabrics, <b>making</b> the <b>social</b> order legible at a glance. In imperial <b>China</b>, the color <b>yellow</b> was reserved for the emperor, and the intricate rank badges worn by officials communicated precise positions within the bureaucratic hierarchy. Cultural <b>exchange</b> and <b>historical</b> <b>events</b> <b>leave</b> deep imprints on <b>fashion</b>. The <b>Silk</b> Road brought <b>Chinese</b> <b>silk</b> to Roman elites, transforming Mediterranean ideas of luxury. The upheavals of the twentieth <b>century</b> including two <b>world</b> wars and women's suffrage each produced distinctive sartorial responses. In the contemporary <b>world</b>, <b>fashion</b> has <b>become</b> a global <b>conversation</b> in which <b>traditional</b> garments are reinterpreted, subcultures coin new styles, and sustainability concerns <b>challenge</b> the fast-<b>fashion</b> model. <b>Fashion</b> remains a <b>mirror</b> in which we see not just ourselves but the complex cultural currents that shape our <b>world</b>. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p>"}},{"name":"勇气的含义","entries":[{"cn":"某人的","en":"one's","type":"word"},{"cn":"害怕，恐惧","en":"fear","type":"word"},{"cn":"熟悉的","en":"familiar","type":"word"},{"cn":"诚实","en":"honesty","type":"word"},{"cn":"提醒","en":"remind","type":"word"},{"cn":"金色的","en":"golden","type":"word"},{"cn":"裁判；审判员；法官","en":"judge","type":"word"},{"cn":"站；站立","en":"stand","type":"word"},{"cn":"值得的；有……价值的","en":"worth","type":"word"},{"cn":"不顾；恶意；怨恨 vt. 刁难；使恼怒","en":"spite","type":"word"},{"cn":"爱；热爱；很喜欢","en":"love","type":"word"}],"passage":{"title":"The Meaning of Courage","html":"<p>Courage is among the most admired of human virtues, yet its meaning resists simple definition. It is not the absence of <b>fear</b>, as a <b>familiar</b> adage reminds us, but rather the capacity to act in <b>spite</b> of <b>fear</b> — to recognize a threat and to proceed nevertheless because something of greater value is at stake. Philosophers have long debated the nature of courage. Aristotle placed it as the <b>golden</b> mean between cowardice and recklessness, emphasizing that true courage requires not just boldness but wisdom — the ability to <b>judge</b> which risks are <b>worth</b> taking and for what ends. Courage takes many forms beyond the battlefield. There is moral courage — the willingness to <b>stand</b> by <b>one's</b> convictions in the face of social pressure, to speak truth to power, or to defend unpopular ideas. There is emotional courage — the strength to be vulnerable, to <b>love</b> after loss, to face <b>one's</b> own flaws with <b>honesty</b>. In every culture, stories of courage inspire because they <b>remind</b> us of human potential. From the ancient Chinese concept of righteousness which calls for action in the face of injustice, to modern accounts of activists and ordinary people doing extraordinary things, the courageous act affirms that individuals are not merely products of their circumstances. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p>"}},{"name":"二十四节气","entries":[{"cn":"中国的；中国人的；汉语的  中国人；汉语","en":"chinese","type":"word"},{"cn":"二十的","en":"twenty","type":"word"},{"cn":"穿过；通过","en":"through","type":"word"},{"cn":"年","en":"year","type":"word"},{"cn":"福尔；","en":"four","type":"word"},{"cn":"春天﹐春季","en":"spring","type":"word"},{"cn":"传统的","en":"traditional","type":"word"},{"cn":"向导,导游;指南","en":"guide","type":"word"},{"cn":"知识；学问","en":"knowledge","type":"word"},{"cn":"开始；开端","en":"beginning","type":"word"},{"cn":"实践（practice的复数）；练习 v. 练习（practice的第三人称单数形式）","en":"practices","type":"word"},{"cn":"练习；实践","en":"practice","type":"word"},{"cn":"药","en":"medicine","type":"word"},{"cn":"千","en":"thousand","type":"word"},{"cn":"自然的；天然的","en":"natural","type":"word"},{"cn":"古代的；古老的","en":"ancient","type":"word"},{"cn":"到达","en":"arrival","type":"word"},{"cn":"文化","en":"culture","type":"word"},{"cn":"天气﹔气象","en":"weather","type":"word"},{"cn":"十五；十五个；十五人组成的橄榄球队 num. 十五 adj. 十五的","en":"fifteen","type":"word"},{"cn":"黄色的 黄色","en":"yellow","type":"word"},{"cn":"健康","en":"health","type":"word"},{"cn":"社会的；社交的","en":"social","type":"word"},{"cn":"长度","en":"length","type":"word"},{"cn":"活的；现存的；活跃的；逼真的 n. 生活；生存；生计 v. 生活；居住（live的ing形式）；度过 n. (Living)人名；(英)利","en":"living","type":"word"},{"cn":"年来最好最精确的指标","en":"year's","type":"word"},{"cn":"每日的；日常的","en":"daily","type":"word"},{"cn":"今天；当今","en":"today","type":"word"},{"cn":"第一的；最初的 第一；首先，最初 开始；开端","en":"first","type":"word"},{"cn":"年轻的","en":"young","type":"word"}],"passage":{"title":"The 24 Solar Terms","html":"<p>The <b>Twenty</b>-<b>Four</b> Solar Terms form an <b>ancient</b> <b>Chinese</b> calendrical system that divides the solar <b>year</b> into <b>twenty</b>-<b>four</b> precise segments, each approximately <b>fifteen</b> days in <b>length</b>. Originating in the <b>Yellow</b> River basin over two <b>thousand</b> years ago, this system was developed to <b>guide</b> agricultural activities by tracking the sun's annual movement <b>through</b> the ecliptic. Each solar term bears a name that vividly describes the seasonal phenomena occurring at that time. <b>Beginning</b> of <b>Spring</b> marks the <b><b>year</b>'s</b> <b>first</b> stirrings of warmth; Awakening of Insects signals the <b>arrival</b> of <b>spring</b> thunder that rouses hibernating creatures; Grain Rain indicates the crucial rains that nourish <b>young</b> crops. These names encode centuries of empirical <b>knowledge</b> about <b>weather</b> patterns and optimal planting times. The practical wisdom embedded in the solar terms extended far beyond farming. <b>Traditional</b> <b>Chinese</b> <b>medicine</b> used the terms to <b>guide</b> dietary adjustments and <b>health</b> <b>practices</b> throughout the <b>year</b>. Festivals and <b>social</b> customs likewise aligned with the solar terms, weaving the agricultural calendar into the fabric of <b>daily</b> life. UNESCO inscribed the <b>Twenty</b>-<b>Four</b> Solar Terms on its Representative List of the Intangible Cultural Heritage of Humanity, recognizing the system as a remarkable fusion of astronomical observation and cultural <b>practice</b>. <b>Today</b>, the solar terms persist in <b>Chinese</b> <b>culture</b> <b>through</b> poetry, culinary traditions, and a renewed appreciation for <b>living</b> in harmony with <b>natural</b> cycles. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p>"}},{"name":"万里长城","entries":[{"cn":"墙壁，围墙；似墙之物 adj. 墙壁的 vt. 用墙围住，围以墙 n. (Wall)人名；(英)沃尔；(德","en":"wall","type":"word"},{"cn":"中国的；中国人的；汉语的  中国人；汉语","en":"chinese","type":"word"},{"cn":"伟大的;重要的;(口语)好极了;很好","en":"great","type":"word"},{"cn":"横过，穿过","en":"across","type":"word"},{"cn":"想象力；空想；幻想物","en":"imagination","type":"word"},{"cn":"人的;人类的； 人类","en":"human","type":"word"},{"cn":"强大的","en":"powerful","type":"word"},{"cn":"在(两者)之间；在……中间","en":"between","type":"word"},{"cn":"历史;历史学","en":"history","type":"word"},{"cn":"/ pron.","en":"one","type":"word"},{"cn":"单一的；单个的；单身的","en":"single","type":"word"},{"cn":"著名的","en":"famous","type":"word"},{"cn":"象征；符号","en":"symbol","type":"word"},{"cn":"沿着；顺着；向前；和……一起；一同","en":"along","type":"word"},{"cn":"瓷器","en":"china","type":"word"},{"cn":"当地的；地方的","en":"local","type":"word"},{"cn":"在……下面；低于","en":"under","type":"word"},{"cn":"夜；夜间","en":"night","type":"word"},{"cn":"今天；当今","en":"today","type":"word"},{"cn":"贸易；交易","en":"trade","type":"word"},{"cn":"到达，抵达；伸手够到","en":"reach","type":"word"},{"cn":"州；国家；状态","en":"state","type":"word"},{"cn":"世界","en":"world","type":"word"},{"cn":"快的，迅速的","en":"rapid","type":"word"},{"cn":"生活，[生物] 生命（life的复数） v. 生活（live的三单形式）；居住","en":"lives","type":"word"},{"cn":"使用（use的现在分词）","en":"using","type":"word"},{"cn":"值(多少钱)；花费","en":"cost","type":"word"},{"cn":"在……上方；越过；遍及；超过 结束；越过；翻转","en":"over","type":"word"},{"cn":"路，道路","en":"road","type":"word"},{"cn":"火；火炉；火灾","en":"fire","type":"word"}],"passage":{"title":"The Great Wall","html":"<p>The <b>Great</b> <b>Wall</b> of <b>China</b> stands as <b>one</b> of the most ambitious construction projects in <b>human</b> <b>history</b>, stretching thousands of kilometers <b>across</b> diverse terrain from the eastern seaboard to the deserts of the far west. It is not a <b>single</b> continuous structure built in <b>one</b> era but rather a series of fortifications constructed, expanded, and repaired by multiple dynasties <b>over</b> nearly two millennia. The most <b>famous</b> sections of the <b>Wall</b> were built during the Ming Dynasty when the threat of Mongol invasions prompted a massive program of military engineering. Ming builders employed advanced techniques suited to <b>local</b> conditions. Signal towers <b>using</b> smoke by day and <b>fire</b> by <b>night</b> enabled <b>rapid</b> communication <b>across</b> vast distances. The <b>human</b> <b>cost</b> of the <b>Wall</b>'s construction was immense. Hundreds of thousands of laborers including soldiers, peasants, and convicts toiled <b>under</b> harsh conditions, and many lost their <b>lives</b>. This suffering embedded the <b>Wall</b> deeply in the <b>Chinese</b> cultural <b>imagination</b>, giving rise to folk tales such as the legend of Meng Jiangnu. Beyond its military function, the <b>Great</b> <b>Wall</b> served as a <b>symbol</b> of the boundary <b>between</b> settled agricultural civilization and the nomadic steppe cultures. It regulated <b>trade</b> <b>along</b> the Silk <b>Road</b>, controlled migration, and asserted the <b>reach</b> of the <b>Chinese</b> <b>state</b>. <b>Today</b>, the <b>Great</b> <b>Wall</b> endures as a UNESCO <b>World</b> Heritage site and a <b>powerful</b> emblem of <b>Chinese</b> cultural identity. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p>"}},{"name":"十二生肖","entries":[{"cn":"老虎","en":"tiger","type":"word"},{"cn":"自信心；信任","en":"confidence","type":"word"},{"cn":"雄心；野心","en":"ambition","type":"word"},{"cn":"流行的；大众的；受欢迎的","en":"popular","type":"word"},{"cn":"猴子","en":"monkey","type":"word"},{"cn":"聪明的","en":"clever","type":"word"},{"cn":"结束；做完","en":"finish","type":"word"},{"cn":"十字形的东西","en":"cross","type":"word"},{"cn":"立基于，以…为基础（base的过去式和过去分词） adj. 有根基的","en":"based","type":"word"},{"cn":"比赛；赛跑","en":"race","type":"word"},{"cn":"希望","en":"hope","type":"word"},{"cn":"排，行；线路","en":"line","type":"word"},{"cn":"标志；符号；迹象","en":"sign","type":"word"},{"cn":"狗","en":"dog","type":"word"},{"cn":"猪","en":"pig","type":"word"}],"passage":{"title":"The Chinese Zodiac","html":"<p>The Chinese zodiac, known as Shengxiao, is a twelve-year cycle in which each year is associated with a specific animal: Rat, Ox, <b>Tiger</b>, Rabbit, Dragon, Snake, Horse, Goat, <b>Monkey</b>, Rooster, <b>Dog</b>, and <b>Pig</b>. Unlike the Western zodiac, which divides the year into monthly signs <b>based</b> on constellations, the Chinese system assigns an animal to an entire lunar year. The origins of the zodiac are shrouded in legend. The most <b>popular</b> story recounts how the Jade Emperor summoned all animals to a <b>race</b>, promising to name a year after the first twelve to <b>cross</b> a river. The <b>clever</b> Rat hitched a ride on the Ox's back and leaped ahead at the <b>finish</b> <b>line</b>, securing first place. Each animal is believed to impart specific personality traits to those born under its <b>sign</b>. The Dragon is associated with <b>confidence</b> and <b>ambition</b>, the Rabbit with gentleness and elegance, the <b>Tiger</b> with bravery and competitiveness. These characterizations influence everything from career choices to marital compatibility. The zodiac permeates Chinese social and economic life in profound ways. Birth rates demonstrably spike during Dragon years, as parents <b>hope</b> to bestow auspicious qualities on their children. During the Lunar New Year, the incoming animal becomes the motif for decorations, gifts, and celebrations. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p>"}},{"name":"京杭大运河","entries":[{"cn":"世界","en":"world","type":"word"},{"cn":"运输；交通 /trænsˈpɔːt/ 运输","en":"transport","type":"word"},{"cn":"旅行（用）的；移动的 v. 旅行（travel的现在分词形式） n. 走步（等于walking）","en":"traveling","type":"word"},{"cn":"交换；交流","en":"exchange","type":"word"},{"cn":"在(两者)之间；在……中间","en":"between","type":"word"},{"cn":"初等的，初级的","en":"primary","type":"word"},{"cn":"世纪；百年","en":"century","type":"word"},{"cn":"文化","en":"culture","type":"word"},{"cn":"目的；用途","en":"purpose","type":"word"},{"cn":"北京","en":"beijing","type":"word"},{"cn":"变得（become的过去式）","en":"became","type":"word"},{"cn":"水 浇水","en":"water","type":"word"},{"cn":"沿着；顺着；向前；和……一起；一同","en":"along","type":"word"},{"cn":"瓷器","en":"china","type":"word"},{"cn":"北的；朝北的；北方的","en":"north","type":"word"},{"cn":"南；南方","en":"south","type":"word"},{"cn":"重的","en":"heavy","type":"word"},{"cn":"已知的；知名的；大家知道的 v. 知道（know的过去分词）","en":"known","type":"word"},{"cn":"江，河","en":"river","type":"word"},{"cn":"第五","en":"fifth","type":"word"},{"cn":"食物，食品","en":"food","type":"word"},{"cn":"日期；约会","en":"date","type":"word"},{"cn":"如此的；这样的","en":"such","type":"word"},{"cn":"满的，充满的；完全的","en":"full","type":"word"},{"cn":"风险；危险；冒险 vt. 冒…的危险 n. (Risk)人名；(英、阿拉伯)里斯","en":"risk","type":"word"},{"cn":"远的","en":"far","type":"word"}],"passage":{"title":"The Grand Canal","html":"<p>The Grand Canal of <b>China</b> is the <b>world</b>'s longest and oldest artificial waterway, a monumental feat of engineering that connects the fertile Yangtze <b>River</b> basin in the <b>south</b> with the political centers of the <b>north</b>, including <b>Beijing</b>. Its oldest sections <b>date</b> to the <b>fifth</b> <b>century</b> BCE, but the canal reached its <b>full</b> scale during the Sui Dynasty. The canal's <b>primary</b> <b>purpose</b> was economic and administrative integration. In an era before railways and highways, <b>water</b> <b>transport</b> was by <b>far</b> the most efficient means of moving <b>heavy</b> goods. The Grand Canal enabled the shipment of southern grain to the imperial capitals and northern garrisons, stabilizing <b>food</b> supply and reducing the <b>risk</b> of famine. Beyond commerce, the Grand Canal served as a corridor of cultural <b>exchange</b>. Scholars, artists, and officials <b>traveling</b> <b>along</b> its waters spread ideas, dialects, and artistic styles <b>between</b> regions. Canal towns <b>such</b> as Suzhou, Hangzhou, and Yangzhou <b>became</b> centers of refinement, <b>known</b> for their gardens, cuisine, and literary <b>culture</b>. The engineering challenges overcome by the canal's builders were formidable. The waterway traverses complex terrain with significant elevation differences; the solution was an elaborate system of locks, dams, and sluice gates. UNESCO recognized the Grand Canal as a <b>World</b> Heritage site, acknowledging it as a masterpiece of hydraulic engineering that sustained an empire. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p>"}},{"name":"音乐的起源","entries":[{"cn":"音乐；乐曲","en":"music","type":"word"},{"cn":"发展","en":"development","type":"word"},{"cn":"教育","en":"education","type":"word"},{"cn":"古代的；古老的","en":"ancient","type":"word"},{"cn":"独立的;有主见的","en":"independent","type":"word"},{"cn":"早的 早地","en":"early","type":"word"},{"cn":"技术","en":"technology","type":"word"},{"cn":"世界","en":"world","type":"word"},{"cn":"经验；经历","en":"experience","type":"word"},{"cn":"年；年龄；岁月；年代","en":"years","type":"word"},{"cn":"发明,创造","en":"invention","type":"word"},{"cn":"语言","en":"language","type":"word"},{"cn":"千","en":"thousand","type":"word"},{"cn":"在(两者)之间；在……中间","en":"between","type":"word"},{"cn":"私人的；私有的","en":"private","type":"word"},{"cn":"欧洲","en":"europe","type":"word"},{"cn":"中间，当中，中部","en":"middle","type":"word"},{"cn":"现代的","en":"modern","type":"word"},{"cn":"社会的；社交的","en":"social","type":"word"},{"cn":"变得；成为","en":"become","type":"word"},{"cn":"很可能的","en":"likely","type":"word"},{"cn":"瓷器","en":"china","type":"word"},{"cn":"今天；当今","en":"today","type":"word"},{"cn":"回(原处)；向后；背后；后部；背","en":"back","type":"word"},{"cn":"像；跟……一样","en":"like","type":"word"},{"cn":"有;吃;喝;进行","en":"have","type":"word"},{"cn":"生活；居住；活着","en":"live","type":"word"},{"cn":"部分；角色；部件；零件","en":"part","type":"word"},{"cn":"成功的；创造的 v. 做，使，安排（make的过去式和过去分词） n. (Made)人名；(塞)马德 原型: made 是 make 的过去式和过去分词","en":"made","type":"word"},{"cn":"顺利地﹔令人满意地","en":"well","type":"word"}],"passage":{"title":"The History of Music","html":"<p><b>Music</b> is one of humanity's oldest and most universal forms of expression, predating written <b>language</b> by tens of thousands of <b>years</b>. Archaeological evidence suggests that <b>early</b> humans used bone flutes and percussion instruments as far <b>back</b> as forty <b>thousand</b> <b>years</b> ago, <b>likely</b> for ritual purposes, communication, and <b>social</b> bonding. The <b>development</b> of <b>music</b> in the <b>ancient</b> <b>world</b> was closely tied to religion, governance, and <b>education</b>. In <b>ancient</b> Greece, <b>music</b> was considered a fundamental <b>part</b> of a <b>well</b>-rounded <b>education</b>, and philosophers <b>like</b> Pythagoras explored the mathematical relationships <b>between</b> musical intervals. In <b>China</b>, the pentatonic scale emerged as <b>early</b> as the Zhou Dynasty. The <b>Middle</b> Ages and Renaissance saw <b>music</b> <b>become</b> increasingly structured in <b>Europe</b>, with the <b>development</b> of musical notation which allowed compositions to be preserved and transmitted with precision. This innovation enabled polyphony — multiple <b>independent</b> melodic lines sounding simultaneously. The <b>modern</b> era of <b>music</b> has been defined by recording <b>technology</b> and globalization. The <b>invention</b> of the phonograph revolutionized how <b>music</b> was consumed, transforming it from a <b>live</b>, communal <b>experience</b> into a <b>private</b>, reproducible commodity. <b>Today</b>, digital streaming platforms <b>have</b> <b>made</b> virtually all of the <b>world</b>'s musical heritage instantly accessible. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p>"}},{"name":"善良的力量","entries":[{"cn":"仁慈；好意","en":"kindness","type":"word"},{"cn":"研究；调查","en":"research","type":"word"},{"cn":"社会的；社交的","en":"social","type":"word"},{"cn":"比赛，竞赛","en":"competition","type":"word"},{"cn":"教育","en":"education","type":"word"},{"cn":"注意，关心","en":"attention","type":"word"},{"cn":"相符的；一致的；相应的；和谐的；调和的 adv. 依照；根据；按照 v. 给予；使和谐一致；使符合；使适合","en":"according","type":"word"},{"cn":"副手；代理人 adj. 第二的；中等的；次要的；中级的","en":"secondary","type":"word"},{"cn":"种；类","en":"kind","type":"word"},{"cn":"有;吃;喝;进行","en":"have","type":"word"},{"cn":"强大的","en":"powerful","type":"word"},{"cn":"的复数","en":"problems","type":"word"},{"cn":"穿过；通过","en":"through","type":"word"},{"cn":"改进,更新","en":"improve","type":"word"},{"cn":"释放，排放；发表","en":"release","type":"word"},{"cn":"变化，改变（change的复数） v. 改变；交换（change的第三人称单数形式）","en":"changes","type":"word"},{"cn":"研究；学习；学业（study的复数） v. 学习（study的第三人称单数形式）","en":"studies","type":"word"},{"cn":"人；人们；人民","en":"people","type":"word"},{"cn":"横过，穿过","en":"across","type":"word"},{"cn":"健康","en":"health","type":"word"},{"cn":"减少；缩减","en":"reduce","type":"word"},{"cn":"报道；报告 报告","en":"report","type":"word"},{"cn":"自己的 拥有","en":"own","type":"word"},{"cn":"安全；平安","en":"safety","type":"word"},{"cn":"简单的；简易的","en":"simple","type":"word"},{"cn":"效果","en":"effect","type":"word"},{"cn":"其他人","en":"others","type":"word"},{"cn":"经常，常常","en":"often","type":"word"},{"cn":"血，血液","en":"blood","type":"word"},{"cn":"电源；能源；动力；电力","en":"power","type":"word"}],"passage":{"title":"The Power of Kindness","html":"<p><b>Kindness</b> is <b>often</b> underestimated as a soft or <b>secondary</b> virtue, yet its transformative <b>power</b> extends far beyond <b>simple</b> pleasantries. Scientific <b>research</b> has shown that acts of <b>kindness</b> trigger measurable physiological <b>changes</b> in both the giver and the receiver. When we perform <b>kind</b> acts, our brains <b>release</b> oxytocin which lowers <b>blood</b> pressure and promotes cardiovascular <b>health</b>. The psychological benefits of <b>kindness</b> are equally profound. <b>Studies</b> in positive psychology <b>have</b> demonstrated that <b>people</b> who regularly engage in acts of <b>kindness</b> <b>report</b> higher levels of life satisfaction and lower rates of depression and anxiety. <b>Kindness</b> shifts our <b>attention</b> away from our <b>own</b> <b>problems</b> and toward the needs of <b>others</b>. <b>Kindness</b> also functions as a <b>powerful</b> <b>social</b> lubricant that strengthens communities and institutions. In the workplace, cultures characterized by <b>kindness</b> and psychological <b>safety</b> outperform those driven by <b>competition</b> and fear. In schools, anti-bullying programs built on <b>kindness</b> <b>education</b> <b>have</b> been shown to <b>reduce</b> aggression and <b>improve</b> academic outcomes. Perhaps most remarkably, <b>kindness</b> operates <b>according</b> to a principle of contagion. <b>Research</b> has shown that witnessing an act of <b>kindness</b> inspires observers to perform <b>kind</b> acts of their <b>own</b>, creating a ripple <b>effect</b> that can spread <b>through</b> <b>social</b> networks <b>across</b> multiple degrees of separation. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p>"}},{"name":"烹饪的艺术与科学","entries":[{"cn":"形式；方式","en":"form","type":"word"},{"cn":"人的;人类的； 人类","en":"human","type":"word"},{"cn":"技术","en":"technology","type":"word"},{"cn":"历史的,历史上的","en":"historical","type":"word"},{"cn":"化学","en":"chemistry","type":"word"},{"cn":"可用的；可得到的","en":"available","type":"word"},{"cn":"发明,创造","en":"invention","type":"word"},{"cn":"食物，食品","en":"food","type":"word"},{"cn":"一起；共同","en":"together","type":"word"},{"cn":"强大的","en":"powerful","type":"word"},{"cn":"活动","en":"activity","type":"word"},{"cn":"交付；分娩；递送","en":"delivery","type":"word"},{"cn":"穿过；通过","en":"through","type":"word"},{"cn":"物理(学)","en":"physics","type":"word"},{"cn":"科学；自然科学","en":"science","type":"word"},{"cn":"理查德（人名）","en":"richard","type":"word"},{"cn":"横过，穿过","en":"across","type":"word"},{"cn":"现代的","en":"modern","type":"word"},{"cn":"社会的；社交的","en":"social","type":"word"},{"cn":"表演，扮演(角色)；行动","en":"act","type":"word"},{"cn":"回忆；记忆","en":"memory","type":"word"},{"cn":"象征；符号","en":"symbol","type":"word"},{"cn":"不能；无法","en":"cannot","type":"word"},{"cn":"其他人","en":"others","type":"word"},{"cn":"发展；制造；形成 v. 制作（make的现在分词）","en":"making","type":"word"},{"cn":"面包","en":"bread","type":"word"},{"cn":"当地的；地方的","en":"local","type":"word"},{"cn":"种植；播种 植物","en":"plant","type":"word"},{"cn":"世界","en":"world","type":"word"},{"cn":"事件;大事;比赛项目","en":"event","type":"word"}],"passage":{"title":"The Art and Science of Cooking","html":"<p>Cooking is a uniquely <b>human</b> <b>activity</b> that sits at the intersection of art and <b>science</b>. On the scientific side, cooking is essentially applied <b>chemistry</b> and <b>physics</b>: heat denatures proteins, caramelizes sugars, emulsifies fats into liquids, and breaks down the cellulose fibers that make raw plants tough and indigestible. The nutritional significance of cooking <b>cannot</b> be overstated. The anthropologist <b>Richard</b> Wrangham has argued that the <b>invention</b> of cooking was a pivotal <b>event</b> in <b>human</b> evolution. Cooking breaks down tough <b>plant</b> fibers and denatures proteins, <b>making</b> <b>food</b> easier to chew and digest, which in turn allowed our ancestors to evolve smaller jaws and shorter digestive tracts. Yet cooking is far more than just a nutrient-extraction <b>technology</b>; it is also a profound <b>form</b> of cultural expression and creativity. Every cuisine in the <b>world</b> represents a unique adaptation to <b>local</b> environments, <b>available</b> ingredients, and <b>historical</b> influences. Recipes are passed down <b>through</b> generations as a <b>form</b> of cultural <b>memory</b>. The <b>act</b> of cooking for <b>others</b> is also a <b>powerful</b> <b>social</b> ritual. Breaking <b>bread</b> <b>together</b> has been a <b>symbol</b> of peace and fellowship <b>across</b> cultures for millennia. In an era of fast <b>food</b> and meal <b>delivery</b> apps, the deliberate <b>act</b> of cooking from scratch has taken on new significance as a <b>form</b> of mindfulness and resistance against the acceleration of <b>modern</b> life. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p>"}},{"name":"伟大探险家的旅程","entries":[{"cn":"危险的","en":"dangerous","type":"word"},{"cn":"旅行（用）的；移动的 v. 旅行（travel的现在分词形式） n. 走步（等于walking）","en":"traveling","type":"word"},{"cn":"像；跟……一样","en":"like","type":"word"},{"cn":"交换；交流","en":"exchange","type":"word"},{"cn":"雄心；野心","en":"ambition","type":"word"},{"cn":"旅行；旅程","en":"journey","type":"word"},{"cn":"穿过；通过","en":"through","type":"word"},{"cn":"历史;历史学","en":"history","type":"word"},{"cn":"世纪；百年","en":"century","type":"word"},{"cn":"可是；然而,可是,尽管如此","en":"however","type":"word"},{"cn":"破坏，毁坏","en":"destroy","type":"word"},{"cn":"混合物","en":"mixture","type":"word"},{"cn":"答应；承诺","en":"promise","type":"word"},{"cn":"父亲","en":"father","type":"word"},{"cn":"在周围；环绕；在……周围","en":"around","type":"word"},{"cn":"中间，当中，中部","en":"middle","type":"word"},{"cn":"现代的","en":"modern","type":"word"},{"cn":"财富；财产","en":"wealth","type":"word"},{"cn":"变得（become的过去式）","en":"became","type":"word"},{"cn":"叔；伯；舅；姑父；姨父","en":"uncle","type":"word"},{"cn":"沿着；顺着；向前；和……一起；一同","en":"along","type":"word"},{"cn":"瓷器","en":"china","type":"word"},{"cn":"地球;土,泥;大地","en":"earth","type":"word"},{"cn":"贸易；交易","en":"trade","type":"word"},{"cn":"第一的；最初的 第一；首先，最初 开始；开端","en":"first","type":"word"},{"cn":"圆的 转一圈 围绕","en":"round","type":"word"},{"cn":"世界","en":"world","type":"word"},{"cn":"错误的；有毛病的","en":"wrong","type":"word"},{"cn":"找到（find的过去分词） vt. 创立，建立；创办","en":"found","type":"word"},{"cn":"亚洲","en":"asia","type":"word"}],"passage":{"title":"Great Explorers and Their Journeys","html":"<p>The age of exploration dramatically reshaped humanity's understanding of the <b>world</b>. Long before <b>modern</b> GPS and satellite imagery, intrepid individuals set out into the unknown, motivated by a <b>mixture</b> of curiosity, <b>ambition</b>, faith, and the <b>promise</b> of <b>wealth</b>. Their journeys were extraordinarily <b>dangerous</b> — ships were wooden, maps were incomplete or entirely <b>wrong</b>, and diseases <b>like</b> scurvy killed more sailors than storms or shipwrecks. Marco Polo's <b>journey</b> <b>along</b> the Silk Road in the thirteenth <b>century</b> stands as one of <b>history</b>'s most influential expeditions. Setting out from Venice with his <b>father</b> and <b>uncle</b>, Polo spent over two decades <b>traveling</b> <b>through</b> the <b>Middle</b> East, Central <b>Asia</b>, and <b>China</b>, serving in the court of Kublai Khan. The fifteenth and sixteenth centuries saw an unprecedented wave of maritime exploration. Portuguese navigators <b>like</b> Vasco da Gama pioneered the route <b>around</b> the Cape of Good Hope to India. Ferdinand Magellan's expedition <b>became</b> the <b>first</b> to circumnavigate the globe — a feat that definitively proved the <b>Earth</b> was <b>round</b> and far larger than anyone had imagined. The consequences of these explorations were both transformative and devastating. The Columbian <b>Exchange</b> reshaped global ecosystems and diets. <b>However</b>, exploration also brought colonization, the transatlantic slave <b>trade</b>, and demographic catastrophe for indigenous peoples. The legacy of these journeys contains both the courage to venture into the unknown and the capacity to <b>destroy</b> what was <b>found</b> there. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p>"}},{"name":"汉字的故事","entries":[{"cn":"中国的；中国人的；汉语的  中国人；汉语","en":"chinese","type":"word"},{"cn":"意思，意义；含义","en":"meaning","type":"word"},{"cn":"书写；作品；著作；[法] 笔迹 v. 书写（write的ing形式）","en":"writing","type":"word"},{"cn":"在周围；环绕；在……周围","en":"around","type":"word"},{"cn":"瓷器","en":"china","type":"word"},{"cn":"不同","en":"difference","type":"word"},{"cn":"性格；特性；特点","en":"character","type":"word"},{"cn":"的复数","en":"countries","type":"word"},{"cn":"在……上方；越过；遍及；超过 结束；越过；翻转","en":"over","type":"word"},{"cn":"继续","en":"continue","type":"word"},{"cn":"千","en":"thousand","type":"word"},{"cn":"历史;历史学","en":"history","type":"word"},{"cn":"规则的；经常的","en":"regular","type":"word"},{"cn":"文化","en":"culture","type":"word"},{"cn":"问题，难题，习题","en":"problem","type":"word"},{"cn":"答案，回答（answer的复数） v. 回答（answer的三单形式）","en":"answers","type":"word"},{"cn":"横过，穿过","en":"across","type":"word"},{"cn":"出现","en":"appear","type":"word"},{"cn":"美","en":"beauty","type":"word"},{"cn":"解决（solve的过去式）；解答 adj. 解决了的","en":"solved","type":"word"},{"cn":"日本","en":"japan","type":"word"},{"cn":"今天；当今","en":"today","type":"word"},{"cn":"其他的；另外的","en":"other","type":"word"},{"cn":"三","en":"three","type":"word"},{"cn":"世界","en":"world","type":"word"},{"cn":"年；年龄；岁月；年代","en":"years","type":"word"},{"cn":"亚洲的；亚洲人","en":"asian","type":"word"},{"cn":"已知的；知名的；大家知道的 v. 知道（know的过去分词）","en":"known","type":"word"},{"cn":"到……上面","en":"onto","type":"word"},{"cn":"然后；那时；那么","en":"then","type":"word"}],"passage":{"title":"The Story of Chinese Characters","html":"<p><b>Chinese</b> characters represent one of the <b>world</b>'s oldest continuously used <b>writing</b> systems, with a <b>history</b> spanning more than <b>three</b> <b>thousand</b> <b>years</b>. Unlike alphabetic scripts that represent sounds, <b>Chinese</b> characters are logographic — each <b>character</b> primarily represents a unit of <b>meaning</b> rather than a phoneme. This fundamental <b>difference</b> has had profound implications for <b>Chinese</b> <b>culture</b>, literature, and even cognition. The earliest <b>known</b> <b>Chinese</b> characters <b>appear</b> on oracle bones dating to the Shang Dynasty <b>around</b> 1200 BCE. These inscriptions were carved <b>onto</b> turtle plastrons and ox shoulder blades, which were <b>then</b> heated until they cracked; diviners interpreted the crack patterns as <b>answers</b> from ancestors and spirits. The evolution of <b>Chinese</b> characters <b>over</b> the centuries reflects both aesthetic sensibilities and practical needs. The Qin Dynasty's unification of the <b>writing</b> system <b>around</b> 221 BCE standardized the script <b>across</b> <b>China</b>'s vast territory. <b>Over</b> time, the clerical script, <b>regular</b> script, and cursive styles each developed their own aesthetic and functional identities. <b>Today</b>, digital input methods have <b>solved</b> the <b>problem</b> of typing characters on standard keyboards, and <b>Chinese</b> characters <b>continue</b> to thrive not only in <b>China</b> but in <b>Japan</b> and <b>other</b> East <b>Asian</b> <b>countries</b>, carrying with them a rich heritage of <b>meaning</b> and <b>beauty</b>. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p>"}},{"name":"中国造纸术","entries":[{"cn":"(不可数)纸；(可数)报纸；考卷；文件","en":"paper","type":"word"},{"cn":"传统的","en":"traditional","type":"word"},{"cn":"瓷器","en":"china","type":"word"},{"cn":"发明,创造","en":"invention","type":"word"},{"cn":"变得（become的过去式）","en":"became","type":"word"},{"cn":"发展；制造；形成 v. 制作（make的现在分词）","en":"making","type":"word"},{"cn":"今天；当今","en":"today","type":"word"},{"cn":"技术","en":"technology","type":"word"},{"cn":"世界","en":"world","type":"word"},{"cn":"知识；学问","en":"knowledge","type":"word"},{"cn":"(公司、团体或政府的)官员","en":"official","type":"word"},{"cn":"穿过；通过","en":"through","type":"word"},{"cn":"中国的；中国人的；汉语的  中国人；汉语","en":"chinese","type":"word"},{"cn":"古代的；古老的","en":"ancient","type":"word"},{"cn":"可是；然而,可是,尽管如此","en":"however","type":"word"},{"cn":"处理；加工","en":"process","type":"word"},{"cn":"书写；作品；著作；[法] 笔迹 v. 书写（write的ing形式）","en":"writing","type":"word"},{"cn":"横过，穿过","en":"across","type":"word"},{"cn":"在周围；环绕；在……周围","en":"around","type":"word"},{"cn":"战斗；战役","en":"battle","type":"word"},{"cn":"沿着；顺着；向前；和……一起；一同","en":"along","type":"word"},{"cn":"种植；播种 植物","en":"plant","type":"word"},{"cn":"伟大的;重要的;(口语)好极了;很好","en":"great","type":"word"},{"cn":"第一的；最初的 第一；首先，最初 开始；开端","en":"first","type":"word"},{"cn":"纸张；薄片；被单","en":"sheet","type":"word"},{"cn":"故事；小说","en":"story","type":"word"},{"cn":"最小的；最少的（little的最高级） adv. 最小；最少 n. 最小；最少","en":"least","type":"word"},{"cn":"路，道路","en":"road","type":"word"},{"cn":"像；跟……一样","en":"like","type":"word"},{"cn":"有;吃;喝;进行","en":"have","type":"word"}],"passage":{"title":"Chinese Paper-Making","html":"<p>The <b>invention</b> of <b>paper</b> is widely considered one of the Four <b>Great</b> Inventions of <b>ancient</b> <b>China</b>. While <b>writing</b> surfaces existed long before <b>paper</b>, <b>paper</b> as we know it <b>today</b> — a thin <b>sheet</b> made from macerated <b>plant</b> fibers — was <b>first</b> developed in <b>China</b> during the Han Dynasty. This innovation would eventually transform the entire <b>world</b>. The <b>traditional</b> account credits Cai Lun, a court <b>official</b> serving Emperor He of the Han Dynasty, with the <b>invention</b> of <b>paper</b> <b>around</b> 105 CE. <b>However</b>, archaeological evidence suggests that a cruder form of <b>paper</b> existed in <b>China</b> at <b>least</b> two centuries earlier. Cai Lun's contribution was to refine the <b>process</b> by experimenting with materials <b>like</b> mulberry bark, rags, and old fishing nets. The <b>technology</b> of <b>paper</b>-<b>making</b> spread gradually <b>along</b> the Silk <b>Road</b> and <b>through</b> Islamic expansion. <b>Chinese</b> <b>paper</b>-makers were captured by Arab forces after the <b>Battle</b> of Talas in 751 CE, and the <b>knowledge</b> they carried led to the establishment of <b>paper</b> mills in Baghdad, Damascus, and eventually <b>across</b> the Islamic <b>world</b>. In <b>China</b> itself, <b>paper</b> <b>became</b> far more than a practical tool; it <b>became</b> an integral part of cultural and spiritual life. <b>Paper</b> offerings are burned at funerals and during ancestral rites as a way of providing for the deceased in the afterlife. <b>Today</b>, fine <b>paper</b>-<b>making</b> remains a respected <b>traditional</b> craft, and the <b>story</b> of <b>paper</b> serves as a reminder that the simplest technologies can <b>have</b> the most profound consequences. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p>"}},{"name":"中国书法艺术","entries":[{"cn":"中国的；中国人的；汉语的  中国人；汉语","en":"chinese","type":"word"},{"cn":"石头；石块","en":"stone","type":"word"},{"cn":"墨水;油墨","en":"ink","type":"word"},{"cn":"水 浇水","en":"water","type":"word"},{"cn":"刷子；毛刷；画笔；毛笔；灌木丛","en":"brush","type":"word"},{"cn":"木棍；枝条","en":"stick","type":"word"},{"cn":"性格；特性；特点","en":"character","type":"word"},{"cn":"美丽的","en":"beautiful","type":"word"},{"cn":"相符的；一致的；相应的；和谐的；调和的 adv. 依照；根据；按照 v. 给予；使和谐一致；使符合；使适合","en":"according","type":"word"},{"cn":"练习；实践","en":"practice","type":"word"},{"cn":"千","en":"thousand","type":"word"},{"cn":"流行的；大众的；受欢迎的","en":"popular","type":"word"},{"cn":"文化","en":"culture","type":"word"},{"cn":"处理；加工","en":"process","type":"word"},{"cn":"平衡","en":"balance","type":"word"},{"cn":"书写；作品；著作；[法] 笔迹 v. 书写（write的ing形式）","en":"writing","type":"word"},{"cn":"横过，穿过","en":"across","type":"word"},{"cn":"艺术","en":"art","type":"word"},{"cn":"动物","en":"animal","type":"word"},{"cn":"地面","en":"ground","type":"word"},{"cn":"数量；总数","en":"amount","type":"word"},{"cn":"〔尤指职业〕作家﹔作者","en":"writer","type":"word"},{"cn":"新鲜的","en":"fresh","type":"word"},{"cn":"瓷器","en":"china","type":"word"},{"cn":"(不可数)纸；(可数)报纸；考卷；文件","en":"paper","type":"word"},{"cn":"学习；研究","en":"study","type":"word"},{"cn":"今天；当今","en":"today","type":"word"},{"cn":"伟大的;重要的;(口语)好极了;很好","en":"great","type":"word"},{"cn":"固体","en":"solid","type":"word"},{"cn":"速度","en":"speed","type":"word"}],"passage":{"title":"Chinese Calligraphy","html":"<p><b>Chinese</b> calligraphy is far more than <b>beautiful</b> handwriting; it is a revered <b>art</b> form that has been central to <b>Chinese</b> <b>culture</b> for over two <b>thousand</b> years. Regarded as the highest of the classical <b>Chinese</b> arts, calligraphy embodies the belief that the way one writes reveals the inner <b>character</b>, emotional state, and spiritual cultivation of the <b>writer</b>. The tools of calligraphy are collectively known as the Four Treasures of the <b>Study</b>: the <b>brush</b>, the <b>ink</b> <b>stick</b>, the <b>ink</b> <b>stone</b>, and the <b>paper</b>. The <b>brush</b>, typically made of <b>animal</b> hair, must be held vertically with a relaxed but controlled grip. The <b>ink</b> is <b>ground</b> <b>fresh</b> from a <b>solid</b> <b>ink</b> <b>stick</b> on an <b>ink</b> <b>stone</b> with a small <b>amount</b> of <b>water</b>, a meditative <b>process</b> that prepares the mind for focused work. The aesthetic principles of <b>Chinese</b> calligraphy are rooted in dynamic <b>balance</b> and expressive variation. Characters are not rigidly uniform but vary in thickness, darkness, and flow <b>according</b> to the calligrapher's pressure, <b>speed</b>, and intention. <b>Great</b> calligraphers are admired not for mechanical precision but for the vitality and rhythm of their brushwork. <b>Today</b>, <b>Chinese</b> calligraphy continues to be practiced both as a fine <b>art</b> and as a <b>popular</b> pastime. Parks <b>across</b> <b>China</b> feature practitioners <b>writing</b> with oversized brushes dipped in <b>water</b> on <b>stone</b> — a transient <b>practice</b> that leaves no trace and embodies the Buddhist and Daoist sensibility of impermanence. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p>"}},{"name":"艺术如何反映社会","entries":[{"cn":"社会","en":"society","type":"word"},{"cn":"画，油画，水彩画","en":"painting","type":"word"},{"cn":"人；人们；人民","en":"people","type":"word"},{"cn":"艺术","en":"art","type":"word"},{"cn":"地方；住所 放置","en":"place","type":"word"},{"cn":"人口，人数","en":"population","type":"word"},{"cn":"在……上方；越过；遍及；超过 结束；越过；翻转","en":"over","type":"word"},{"cn":"时间；次；倍数","en":"time","type":"word"},{"cn":"考虑","en":"consider","type":"word"},{"cn":"像；跟……一样","en":"like","type":"word"},{"cn":"千","en":"thousand","type":"word"},{"cn":"创造性的，有创意的","en":"creative","type":"word"},{"cn":"直接地","en":"directly","type":"word"},{"cn":"穿过；通过","en":"through","type":"word"},{"cn":"自然的；天然的","en":"natural","type":"word"},{"cn":"控制","en":"control","type":"word"},{"cn":"的复数形式","en":"animals","type":"word"},{"cn":"横过，穿过","en":"across","type":"word"},{"cn":"在周围；环绕；在……周围","en":"around","type":"word"},{"cn":"欧洲","en":"europe","type":"word"},{"cn":"总是；一直；永远","en":"always","type":"word"},{"cn":"现代的","en":"modern","type":"word"},{"cn":"镜子","en":"mirror","type":"word"},{"cn":"变得；成为","en":"become","type":"word"},{"cn":"音乐；乐曲","en":"music","type":"word"},{"cn":"经常，常常","en":"often","type":"word"},{"cn":"玻璃杯；玻璃；(复)眼镜","en":"glass","type":"word"},{"cn":"世界","en":"world","type":"word"},{"cn":"年；年龄；岁月；年代","en":"years","type":"word"},{"cn":"有;吃;喝;进行","en":"have","type":"word"}],"passage":{"title":"How Art Reflects Society","html":"<p><b>Art</b> has <b>always</b> served as a <b>mirror</b> to the <b>society</b> that produces it, capturing the values, struggles, and aspirations of <b>people</b> <b>across</b> <b>time</b> and <b>place</b>. Whether <b>through</b> <b>painting</b>, sculpture, <b>music</b>, or literature, <b>creative</b> expression encodes the cultural DNA of its era. By examining the <b>art</b> of any civilization, we can discern what its <b>people</b> held sacred, what they feared, and how they understood their <b>place</b> in the cosmos. <b>Consider</b> the cave paintings of Lascaux, created <b>over</b> seventeen <b>thousand</b> <b>years</b> ago. These images of bison, deer, and horses reflected a hunter-gatherer <b>society</b> deeply dependent on and reverent toward the <b>animals</b> that sustained it. The act of <b>painting</b> itself may <b>have</b> been a ritual, an attempt to exert symbolic <b>control</b> <b>over</b> the <b>natural</b> <b>world</b>. Moving forward in <b>time</b>, the grand cathedrals and religious iconography of medieval <b>Europe</b> reveal a <b>society</b> organized <b>around</b> Christian faith. Stained <b>glass</b> windows and illuminated manuscripts were didactic tools, designed to instruct a largely illiterate <b>population</b> in biblical narratives. In the <b>modern</b> era, <b>art</b> has <b>become</b> increasingly individualistic and critical. The rise of photography freed painters from the obligation of realistic representation, leading to movements <b>like</b> Impressionism and Cubism. Contemporary <b>art</b> continues this tradition, <b>often</b> engaging <b>directly</b> with issues <b>like</b> inequality, identity, and environmental crisis. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p>"}},{"name":"诗歌如何打动人心","entries":[{"cn":"单元；单位","en":"unit","type":"word"},{"cn":"他(她、它)们自己","en":"themselves","type":"word"},{"cn":"作品；工厂；工程结构 n. (Works)人名；(英)沃克斯","en":"works","type":"word"},{"cn":"某事；某物","en":"something","type":"word"},{"cn":"注意，关心","en":"attention","type":"word"},{"cn":"建筑物；大楼","en":"building","type":"word"},{"cn":"语言","en":"language","type":"word"},{"cn":"排，行；线路","en":"line","type":"word"},{"cn":"材料，原料","en":"material","type":"word"},{"cn":"在(两者)之间；在……中间","en":"between","type":"word"},{"cn":"穿过；通过","en":"through","type":"word"},{"cn":"意思，意义；含义","en":"meaning","type":"word"},{"cn":"再一；另一；别的；不同的；pron. 另一个","en":"another","type":"word"},{"cn":"解释；说明","en":"explain","type":"word"},{"cn":"规则的；经常的","en":"regular","type":"word"},{"cn":"思想；思考；想法；关心 v. 想，思考；认为（think的过去式和过去分词）","en":"thought","type":"word"},{"cn":"片刻，瞬间","en":"moment","type":"word"},{"cn":"创造；造成","en":"create","type":"word"},{"cn":"简单的；简易的","en":"simple","type":"word"},{"cn":"不能；无法","en":"cannot","type":"word"},{"cn":"人的;人类的； 人类","en":"human","type":"word"},{"cn":"在……下面","en":"below","type":"word"},{"cn":"打破(断、碎)；损坏；休息；间隙","en":"break","type":"word"},{"cn":"声音","en":"sound","type":"word"},{"cn":"水平线；水平","en":"level","type":"word"},{"cn":"的三单形式","en":"words","type":"word"},{"cn":"工作；劳动","en":"work","type":"word"},{"cn":"似乎；好像；看来","en":"seem","type":"word"},{"cn":"工具","en":"tool","type":"word"},{"cn":"好的;良好的","en":"good","type":"word"}],"passage":{"title":"How Poetry Works","html":"<p>Poetry is one of humanity's oldest and most enduring forms of verbal art, yet its inner workings can <b>seem</b> mysterious. At its core, poetry <b>works</b> by compressing <b>language</b> to its most potent and suggestive form. Unlike prose, which typically prioritizes clarity and narrative flow, poetry foregrounds the <b>material</b> qualities of <b>words</b> <b>themselves</b>. The most fundamental mechanism of poetry is the poetic <b>line</b>. Unlike prose sentences that run continuously to the margin, the <b>line</b> <b>break</b> in poetry creates a <b>unit</b> of <b>attention</b>. It controls pacing, creates emphasis, and introduces tension <b>between</b> the grammatical <b>unit</b> and the rhythmic <b>unit</b>. <b>Sound</b> patterning is <b>another</b> essential <b>tool</b>. Rhyme, alliteration, assonance, and consonance <b>create</b> musical textures that <b>work</b> on the listener <b>below</b> the <b>level</b> of conscious <b>thought</b>. Meter, the <b>regular</b> pattern of stressed and unstressed syllables, taps into <b>something</b> primal in <b>human</b> cognition. Perhaps most importantly, poetry <b>works</b> <b>through</b> compression and imagery. A <b>good</b> poem does not <b>explain</b>; it shows. By presenting concrete, sensory details, the poet invites the reader into a <b>moment</b> of vivid perception. These images accumulate and interact, <b>building</b> patterns of <b>meaning</b> that <b>cannot</b> be reduced to a <b>simple</b> paraphrase. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p>"}},{"name":"节日的意义","entries":[{"cn":"一起；共同","en":"together","type":"word"},{"cn":"历史;历史学","en":"history","type":"word"},{"cn":"组织；团体；机构","en":"organization","type":"word"},{"cn":"社会的；社交的","en":"social","type":"word"},{"cn":"人的;人类的； 人类","en":"human","type":"word"},{"cn":"代，一代","en":"generation","type":"word"},{"cn":"社区","en":"community","type":"word"},{"cn":"节日","en":"festival","type":"word"},{"cn":"强大的","en":"powerful","type":"word"},{"cn":"活动","en":"activity","type":"word"},{"cn":"穿过；通过","en":"through","type":"word"},{"cn":"中国的；中国人的；汉语的  中国人；汉语","en":"chinese","type":"word"},{"cn":"意思，意义；含义","en":"meaning","type":"word"},{"cn":"自然的；天然的","en":"natural","type":"word"},{"cn":"古代的；古老的","en":"ancient","type":"word"},{"cn":"社会","en":"society","type":"word"},{"cn":"(文章等的)一节，一段；通道","en":"passage","type":"word"},{"cn":"文化","en":"culture","type":"word"},{"cn":"家庭；家族；家人","en":"family","type":"word"},{"cn":"横过，穿过","en":"across","type":"word"},{"cn":"自然；本质","en":"nature","type":"word"},{"cn":"简单的；简易的","en":"simple","type":"word"},{"cn":"春天﹐春季","en":"spring","type":"word"},{"cn":"服务；招待；端上","en":"serve","type":"word"},{"cn":"分享；共用；分担","en":"share","type":"word"},{"cn":"第一的；最初的 第一；首先，最初 开始；开端","en":"first","type":"word"},{"cn":"组;群","en":"group","type":"word"},{"cn":"找到（find的过去分词） vt. 创立，建立；创办","en":"found","type":"word"},{"cn":"一餐(饭)","en":"meal","type":"word"},{"cn":"时间；次；倍数","en":"time","type":"word"}],"passage":{"title":"Why We Celebrate Holidays","html":"<p>Holidays are a universal feature of <b>human</b> <b>culture</b>, <b>found</b> in every <b>society</b> <b>across</b> recorded <b>history</b>. At <b>first</b> glance, they might seem like <b>simple</b> breaks from routine — opportunities for rest and recreation. But the deeper functions of holidays reveal much about <b>human</b> psychology and <b>social</b> <b>organization</b>. The most <b>ancient</b> function of holidays is to structure the <b>passage</b> of <b>time</b>. Agricultural societies celebrated planting and harvest festivals, aligning communal <b>activity</b> with the rhythms of <b>nature</b>. By ritualizing these <b>natural</b> transitions, humans imposed <b>meaning</b> on the cyclical patterns of the seasons. Holidays also <b>serve</b> as <b>powerful</b> mechanisms for <b>social</b> cohesion. When a <b>community</b> comes <b>together</b> to <b>share</b> a <b>meal</b>, perform rituals, or participate in collective festivities, it reinforces the bonds that hold the <b>group</b> <b>together</b>. Furthermore, holidays act as vehicles for cultural transmission. <b>Through</b> repeated annual observances, each <b>generation</b> teaches the next about its <b>history</b>, values, and beliefs. The <b>Chinese</b> <b>Spring</b> <b>Festival</b> reinforces the centrality of <b>family</b>, the honoring of ancestors, and the hope for prosperity. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p>"}},{"name":"美为什么重要","entries":[{"cn":"美","en":"beauty","type":"word"},{"cn":"美丽的","en":"beautiful","type":"word"},{"cn":"横过，穿过","en":"across","type":"word"},{"cn":"一贯地；一致地；坚实地","en":"consistently","type":"word"},{"cn":"人的;人类的； 人类","en":"human","type":"word"},{"cn":"有;吃;喝;进行","en":"have","type":"word"},{"cn":"装饰","en":"decorate","type":"word"},{"cn":"研究；调查","en":"research","type":"word"},{"cn":"历史;历史学","en":"history","type":"word"},{"cn":"意思，意义；含义","en":"meaning","type":"word"},{"cn":"自然的；天然的","en":"natural","type":"word"},{"cn":"生产；产生；制造","en":"produce","type":"word"},{"cn":"安排；布置","en":"arrange","type":"word"},{"cn":"时尚","en":"fashion","type":"word"},{"cn":"弗劳尔斯","en":"flowers","type":"word"},{"cn":"人；人们；人民","en":"people","type":"word"},{"cn":"艺术","en":"art","type":"word"},{"cn":"自然；本质","en":"nature","type":"word"},{"cn":"减少；缩减","en":"reduce","type":"word"},{"cn":"要紧事；麻烦事；事情；问题；物质","en":"matter","type":"word"},{"cn":"其他人","en":"others","type":"word"},{"cn":"品尝；尝起来 味道；品味","en":"taste","type":"word"},{"cn":"水 浇水","en":"water","type":"word"},{"cn":"音乐；乐曲","en":"music","type":"word"},{"cn":"经常，常常","en":"often","type":"word"},{"cn":"脑","en":"brain","type":"word"},{"cn":"桌子；表格","en":"table","type":"word"},{"cn":"树木；[植] 乔木；[化学] 树状结构（tree的复数） n. (Trees)人名；(德)特雷斯；(英)特里斯","en":"trees","type":"word"},{"cn":"，见识","en":"sense","type":"word"},{"cn":"唱；唱歌","en":"sing","type":"word"}],"passage":{"title":"Why Beauty Matters","html":"<p><b>Beauty</b> is <b>often</b> dismissed as superficial — a mere <b>matter</b> of appearance, subjective <b>taste</b>, or commercial manipulation. Yet the <b>human</b> concern with <b>beauty</b> runs far deeper than <b>fashion</b> or cosmetics. <b>Across</b> cultures and throughout <b>history</b>, <b>people</b> <b>have</b> sought <b>beauty</b> in <b>art</b>, <b>nature</b>, architecture, <b>music</b>, and even mathematics. From an evolutionary perspective, our sensitivity to <b>beauty</b> may <b>have</b> adaptive roots. Certain landscapes — open vistas with <b>water</b>, <b>trees</b>, and refuge — are <b>consistently</b> rated as <b>beautiful</b> <b>across</b> cultures, suggesting an inherited preference for environments that offered survival advantages to our ancestors. Psychologically, encounters with <b>beauty</b> <b>produce</b> measurable effects. <b>Research</b> shows that viewing <b>beautiful</b> <b>art</b> or <b>natural</b> scenes can <b>reduce</b> stress, lower cortisol levels, and activate the <b>brain</b>'s reward centers. <b>Beauty</b> can evoke awe — an emotion that expands our <b>sense</b> of time and increases feelings of connection to <b>others</b>. Ultimately, <b>beauty</b> matters because it reminds us that life is not merely about survival and efficiency. The impulse to <b>decorate</b> a tool, to <b>sing</b> a song, to <b>arrange</b> <b>flowers</b> on a <b>table</b> speaks to a <b>human</b> need for <b>meaning</b> that transcends the purely practical. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p>"}},{"name":"四大发明","entries":[{"cn":"(不可数)纸；(可数)报纸；考卷；文件","en":"paper","type":"word"},{"cn":"世界","en":"world","type":"word"},{"cn":"中国的；中国人的；汉语的  中国人；汉语","en":"chinese","type":"word"},{"cn":"瓷器","en":"china","type":"word"},{"cn":"技术","en":"technology","type":"word"},{"cn":"不可能的","en":"impossible","type":"word"},{"cn":"历史的,历史上的","en":"historical","type":"word"},{"cn":"传播（spread的ing形式）；摊开","en":"spreading","type":"word"},{"cn":"有;吃;喝;进行","en":"have","type":"word"},{"cn":"事故；意外的事","en":"accident","type":"word"},{"cn":"福尔；","en":"four","type":"word"},{"cn":"历史;历史学","en":"history","type":"word"},{"cn":"自然的；天然的","en":"natural","type":"word"},{"cn":"古代的；古老的","en":"ancient","type":"word"},{"cn":"世纪；百年","en":"century","type":"word"},{"cn":"没有；超过；在…外面 n. 外部；外面 adv. 户外；在外面；没有或不显示某事物","en":"without","type":"word"},{"cn":"书写；作品；著作；[法] 笔迹 v. 书写（write的ing形式）","en":"writing","type":"word"},{"cn":"横过，穿过","en":"across","type":"word"},{"cn":"在周围；环绕；在……周围","en":"around","type":"word"},{"cn":"便宜的","en":"cheap","type":"word"},{"cn":"决不；从来没有","en":"never","type":"word"},{"cn":"站；站立","en":"stand","type":"word"},{"cn":"压，按","en":"press","type":"word"},{"cn":"使用（use的现在分词）","en":"using","type":"word"},{"cn":"真实的，真正的","en":"real","type":"word"},{"cn":"的过去式","en":"came","type":"word"},{"cn":"年龄；时代","en":"age","type":"word"}],"passage":{"title":"The Four Great Inventions of Ancient China","html":"<p>Among the many technological achievements of <b>Chinese</b> civilization, <b>four</b> <b>stand</b> out for their transformative impact on <b>world</b> <b>history</b>: <b>paper</b>, printing, gunpowder, and the compass. Each emerged from specific <b>historical</b> circumstances in <b>China</b> before <b>spreading</b> <b>across</b> Eurasia, reshaping societies in ways their inventors could <b>never</b> <b>have</b> anticipated. <b>Paper</b>, traditionally attributed to Cai Lun <b>around</b> 105 CE, was a revolutionary alternative to cumbersome <b>writing</b> materials of the <b>ancient</b> <b>world</b>. <b>Paper</b> was lightweight, <b>cheap</b>, and versatile. <b>Without</b> <b>paper</b>, the explosion of learning that fueled the Renaissance and the Scientific Revolution would <b>have</b> been <b>impossible</b>. Printing emerged as a <b>natural</b> extension of <b>paper</b> <b>technology</b>. Woodblock printing appeared in <b>China</b> during the Tang dynasty. The <b>real</b> breakthrough <b>came</b> in the eleventh <b>century</b> when Bi Sheng invented movable type <b>using</b> baked clay characters, anticipating Gutenberg's <b>press</b> by <b>four</b> centuries. Gunpowder, discovered by Daoist alchemists seeking an elixir of immortality, was a serendipitous <b>accident</b> with <b>world</b>-altering consequences. The magnetic compass, developed from the <b>Chinese</b> discovery of lodestone's directional properties, transformed navigation and enabled the <b>age</b> of exploration. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p>"}},{"name":"中医的智慧","entries":[{"cn":"药","en":"medicine","type":"word"},{"cn":"传统的","en":"traditional","type":"word"},{"cn":"中国的；中国人的；汉语的  中国人；汉语","en":"chinese","type":"word"},{"cn":"健康","en":"health","type":"word"},{"cn":"相符的；一致的；相应的；和谐的；调和的 adv. 依照；根据；按照 v. 给予；使和谐一致；使符合；使适合","en":"according","type":"word"},{"cn":"连接（connect的过去式） adj. [计] 连接的；有联系的；连贯的","en":"connected","type":"word"},{"cn":"练习；实践","en":"practice","type":"word"},{"cn":"身体","en":"body","type":"word"},{"cn":"单独的；分开的","en":"separate","type":"word"},{"cn":"兴趣;趣味","en":"interest","type":"word"},{"cn":"研究；调查","en":"research","type":"word"},{"cn":"千","en":"thousand","type":"word"},{"cn":"穿过；通过","en":"through","type":"word"},{"cn":"自然的；天然的","en":"natural","type":"word"},{"cn":"古代的；古老的","en":"ancient","type":"word"},{"cn":"机器","en":"machine","type":"word"},{"cn":"比赛；演奏 v. 玩耍（play的ing形式）","en":"playing","type":"word"},{"cn":"病，[医] 疾病；弊病 vt. 传染；使…有病","en":"disease","type":"word"},{"cn":"动物","en":"animal","type":"word"},{"cn":"精力;能量","en":"energy","type":"word"},{"cn":"现代的","en":"modern","type":"word"},{"cn":"近来的，最近的","en":"recent","type":"word"},{"cn":"积极的；活跃的","en":"active","type":"word"},{"cn":"人的;人类的； 人类","en":"human","type":"word"},{"cn":"沿着；顺着；向前；和……一起；一同","en":"along","type":"word"},{"cn":"田地；牧场；场地","en":"field","type":"word"},{"cn":"经常，常常","en":"often","type":"word"},{"cn":"世界","en":"world","type":"word"},{"cn":"年；年龄；岁月；年代","en":"years","type":"word"},{"cn":"整体；全部 adj. 完整的；纯粹的","en":"whole","type":"word"}],"passage":{"title":"Traditional Chinese Medicine","html":"<p><b>Traditional</b> <b>Chinese</b> <b>Medicine</b>, or TCM, is a comprehensive system of <b>health</b> and healing that has evolved over more than two <b>thousand</b> <b>years</b>. Rooted in <b>ancient</b> <b>Chinese</b> philosophy, particularly Daoism, TCM understands the <b>human</b> <b>body</b> not as a <b>machine</b> composed of <b>separate</b> parts but as an integrated <b>whole</b>, dynamically <b>connected</b> to the <b>natural</b> <b>world</b>. Central to TCM is the concept of qi, <b>often</b> translated as vital <b>energy</b> or life force. <b>According</b> to TCM theory, qi flows <b>through</b> the <b>body</b> <b>along</b> specific pathways called meridians, nourishing organs and tissues. <b>Health</b> is understood as the smooth, balanced flow of qi, while <b>disease</b> results from blockages, deficiencies, or imbalances. Herbal <b>medicine</b> forms the largest component of TCM <b>practice</b>. Formulas typically combine multiple herbs in precise proportions, with each ingredient <b>playing</b> a specific role. The pharmacopoeia includes thousands of substances derived from plants, minerals, and some <b>animal</b> products. In <b>recent</b> decades, TCM has attracted significant scientific <b>interest</b>. <b>Research</b> has identified <b>active</b> compounds in many <b>traditional</b> herbs and demonstrated the efficacy of acupuncture for conditions such as chronic pain and nausea. The growing <b>field</b> of integrative <b>medicine</b> seeks to combine the strengths of TCM's holistic approach with <b>modern</b> biomedicine. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p>"}},{"name":"运动的起源","entries":[{"cn":"古代的；古老的","en":"ancient","type":"word"},{"cn":"竞争，对抗（compete的过去分词）","en":"competed","type":"word"},{"cn":"比赛，竞赛","en":"competition","type":"word"},{"cn":"人的;人类的； 人类","en":"human","type":"word"},{"cn":"世界","en":"world","type":"word"},{"cn":"经验；经历","en":"experience","type":"word"},{"cn":"统治；支配；裁定（rule的第三人称单数形式）","en":"rules","type":"word"},{"cn":"开始；开端","en":"beginning","type":"word"},{"cn":"一起；共同","en":"together","type":"word"},{"cn":"朋友般的；友好的","en":"friendly","type":"word"},{"cn":"身体的；物理的","en":"physical","type":"word"},{"cn":"游泳","en":"swimming","type":"word"},{"cn":"英国的；英国人的","en":"british","type":"word"},{"cn":"意思，意义；含义","en":"meaning","type":"word"},{"cn":"世纪；百年","en":"century","type":"word"},{"cn":"奥林匹克的","en":"olympic","type":"word"},{"cn":"自己；亲自","en":"oneself","type":"word"},{"cn":"竞争；比赛；对抗","en":"compete","type":"word"},{"cn":"人；人们；人民","en":"people","type":"word"},{"cn":"横过，穿过","en":"across","type":"word"},{"cn":"自然；本质","en":"nature","type":"word"},{"cn":"现代的","en":"modern","type":"word"},{"cn":"公共的，公众的","en":"public","type":"word"},{"cn":"社会的；社交的","en":"social","type":"word"},{"cn":"著名的","en":"famous","type":"word"},{"cn":"其他人","en":"others","type":"word"},{"cn":"运动；运动会（sport的复数）；（报纸）体育版面；突变；娱乐 adj. 运动的；适用于运动的 v. 娱乐；戏弄（sport的第三人称单数）","en":"sports","type":"word"},{"cn":"钱；货币","en":"money","type":"word"},{"cn":"石头；石块","en":"stone","type":"word"},{"cn":"早的 早地","en":"early","type":"word"}],"passage":{"title":"The Origin of Sports","html":"<p>The impulse to run, throw, jump, and <b>compete</b> is among the most <b>ancient</b> elements of <b>human</b> <b>nature</b>. Long before any formal <b>rules</b> were written down, our ancestors engaged in <b>physical</b> contests that tested strength, speed, and skill. Archaeological evidence suggests that wrestling, sprinting, and archery were practiced in prehistoric societies not merely as survival training but also as communal rituals that brought <b>people</b> <b>together</b> in celebration and <b>friendly</b> rivalry. As <b>early</b> civilizations took shape, <b>sports</b> acquired deeper <b>social</b> <b>meaning</b>. In <b>ancient</b> Egypt, tomb paintings depict scenes of <b>swimming</b>, javelin throwing, and a kind of hockey played with palm branches. In Mesoamerica, the Olmec and Maya peoples built great <b>stone</b> ball courts where teams <b>competed</b> in a game that carried profound religious significance. The most <b>famous</b> athletic tradition of the <b>ancient</b> <b>world</b> was the <b>Olympic</b> Games of Greece. <b>Beginning</b> in 776 BCE at Olympia, these contests drew athletes from city-states <b>across</b> the Hellenic <b>world</b> who <b>competed</b> in foot races, wrestling, chariot racing, and the pentathlon. Victory brought not <b>money</b> but an olive wreath and enduring honor. <b>Modern</b> sport, shaped by nineteenth-<b>century</b> <b>British</b> <b>public</b> schools and the global spread of <b>rules</b>-based <b>competition</b>, may seem far removed from its <b>ancient</b> roots. Yet beneath the standardized fields and instant replays, the same <b>human</b> desires endure: to test <b>oneself</b> against <b>others</b>, to <b>experience</b> the thrill of mastery, and to share in collective excitement. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p>"}},{"name":"记忆为什么重要","entries":[{"cn":"回忆；记忆","en":"memory","type":"word"},{"cn":"经验；经历","en":"experience","type":"word"},{"cn":"历史的,历史上的","en":"historical","type":"word"},{"cn":"，见识","en":"sense","type":"word"},{"cn":"幼年时代，童年","en":"childhood","type":"word"},{"cn":"运输；交通 /trænsˈpɔːt/ 运输","en":"transport","type":"word"},{"cn":"某事；某物","en":"something","type":"word"},{"cn":"一起；共同","en":"together","type":"word"},{"cn":"个人的；私人的","en":"personal","type":"word"},{"cn":"学期；术语","en":"term","type":"word"},{"cn":"突然地；忽然","en":"suddenly","type":"word"},{"cn":"礼物；赠品；现在","en":"present","type":"word"},{"cn":"在(两者)之间；在……中间","en":"between","type":"word"},{"cn":"永远；永恒地","en":"forever","type":"word"},{"cn":"想象;设想","en":"imagine","type":"word"},{"cn":"处理；加工","en":"process","type":"word"},{"cn":"质量","en":"quality","type":"word"},{"cn":"思想；思考；想法；关心 v. 想，思考；认为（think的过去式和过去分词）","en":"thought","type":"word"},{"cn":"没有；超过；在…外面 n. 外部；外面 adv. 户外；在外面；没有或不显示某事物","en":"without","type":"word"},{"cn":"自然；本质","en":"nature","type":"word"},{"cn":"将来，未来","en":"future","type":"word"},{"cn":"片刻，瞬间","en":"moment","type":"word"},{"cn":"尚；还；仍然","en":"yet","type":"word"},{"cn":"到达；达到","en":"arrive","type":"word"},{"cn":"创造；造成","en":"create","type":"word"},{"cn":"普通的，一般的；共有的","en":"common","type":"word"},{"cn":"活的；现存的；活跃的；逼真的 n. 生活；生存；生计 v. 生活；居住（live的ing形式）；度过 n. (Living)人名；(英)利","en":"living","type":"word"},{"cn":"伊文茨","en":"events","type":"word"},{"cn":"人的;人类的； 人类","en":"human","type":"word"},{"cn":"学习；学会","en":"learn","type":"word"}],"passage":{"title":"Why Memory Matters","html":"<p><b>Memory</b> is far more than a mental filing cabinet. It is the foundation upon which we construct our <b>personal</b> identity, navigate the <b>present</b>, and <b>imagine</b> the <b>future</b>. <b>Without</b> <b>memory</b>, each <b>moment</b> would <b>arrive</b> in isolation, unconnected to any past <b>experience</b>, and our <b>sense</b> of self would simply dissolve. At the biological level, <b>memory</b> is a marvel of neural plasticity. When we <b>learn</b> <b>something</b> new, the connections <b>between</b> neurons strengthen or weaken in patterns that encode the <b>experience</b>. The hippocampus plays a crucial role in consolidating short-<b>term</b> recollections into lasting long-<b>term</b> memories, a <b>process</b> that often occurs during sleep. Culturally, <b>memory</b> serves as the glue that holds communities <b>together</b>. Shared memories of <b>historical</b> <b>events</b>, collective triumphs, and <b>common</b> tragedies <b>create</b> a <b>sense</b> of belonging that transcends individual <b>experience</b>. In an age of digital storage and instant recall, the <b>nature</b> of <b>memory</b> is changing <b>yet</b> again. <b>Yet</b> external storage can never replace the <b>living</b>, emotional, and interpretive <b>quality</b> of <b>human</b> <b>memory</b> — the way a scent can <b>suddenly</b> <b>transport</b> us to <b>childhood</b> or a song can evoke a feeling we <b>thought</b> was lost <b>forever</b>. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p>"}},{"name":"民主的诞生","entries":[{"cn":"；市民","en":"citizens","type":"word"},{"cn":"改革（reform的复数） v. 改革（reform的单数第三人称）","en":"reforms","type":"word"},{"cn":"实验","en":"experiment","type":"word"},{"cn":"社区","en":"community","type":"word"},{"cn":"不同的，有差异的","en":"different","type":"word"},{"cn":"普通的，平常的","en":"ordinary","type":"word"},{"cn":"公民；居民；市民","en":"citizen","type":"word"},{"cn":"穿过；通过","en":"through","type":"word"},{"cn":"古代的；古老的","en":"ancient","type":"word"},{"cn":"世纪；百年","en":"century","type":"word"},{"cn":"人；人们；人民","en":"people","type":"word"},{"cn":"在周围；环绕；在……周围","en":"around","type":"word"},{"cn":"现代的","en":"modern","type":"word"},{"cn":"公共的，公众的","en":"public","type":"word"},{"cn":"到达；达到","en":"arrive","type":"word"},{"cn":"在……下面；低于","en":"under","type":"word"},{"cn":"经常，常常","en":"often","type":"word"},{"cn":"证明","en":"prove","type":"word"},{"cn":"世界","en":"world","type":"word"},{"cn":"电源；能源；动力；电力","en":"power","type":"word"},{"cn":"第五","en":"fifth","type":"word"},{"cn":"城市","en":"city","type":"word"},{"cn":"身体","en":"body","type":"word"},{"cn":"握住（hold的过去分词）；举起,抬起；使升高；展示；提出(作为榜样)(后与as连用) n. (Held)人名；(英、瑞典)赫尔德；(德、捷)黑尔德；(罗、匈、塞)海尔德","en":"held","type":"word"},{"cn":"的过去式","en":"came","type":"word"},{"cn":"拿；取；接受（take的过去式）","en":"took","type":"word"},{"cn":"十","en":"ten","type":"word"},{"cn":"新的；新鲜的","en":"new","type":"word"}],"passage":{"title":"The Birth of Democracy","html":"<p>Democracy did not <b>arrive</b> in the <b>world</b> fully formed. It emerged gradually in <b>ancient</b> Athens during the <b>fifth</b> <b>century</b> BCE <b>through</b> a series of <b>reforms</b> that transformed a <b>city</b> ruled by aristocrats and tyrants into a political <b>community</b> where <b>ordinary</b> <b>citizens</b> <b>held</b> genuine <b>power</b>. The path to Athenian democracy began with the lawgiver Solon in 594 BCE, who introduced <b>reforms</b> that broke the stranglehold of aristocratic clans. The decisive shift <b>came</b> <b>under</b> Cleisthenes <b>around</b> 508 BCE, who reorganized the <b>citizen</b> <b>body</b> into <b>ten</b> <b>new</b> tribes that mixed <b>people</b> from <b>different</b> regions. The Athenians <b>took</b> the principle of direct participation to lengths that <b>modern</b> democracies rarely attempt. <b>Citizens</b> did not merely elect representatives; they served personally on juries, in the council, and in most <b>public</b> offices, with positions <b>often</b> filled by random lottery. Despite its imperfections, the Athenian <b>experiment</b> planted a seed that would <b>prove</b> extraordinarily durable. After centuries of monarchy and empire, democratic ideas reemerged during the Enlightenment. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p>"}},{"name":"书籍的历史","entries":[{"cn":"古代的；古老的","en":"ancient","type":"word"},{"cn":"世纪；百年","en":"century","type":"word"},{"cn":"书；本子；预订，订(房间、车票、座位等)","en":"book","type":"word"},{"cn":"伟大的;重要的;(口语)好极了;很好","en":"great","type":"word"},{"cn":"第一的；最初的 第一；首先，最初 开始；开端","en":"first","type":"word"},{"cn":"世界","en":"world","type":"word"},{"cn":"知识；学问","en":"knowledge","type":"word"},{"cn":"发明,创造","en":"invention","type":"word"},{"cn":"身体的；物理的","en":"physical","type":"word"},{"cn":"穿过；通过","en":"through","type":"word"},{"cn":"历史;历史学","en":"history","type":"word"},{"cn":"再一；另一；别的；不同的；pron. 另一个","en":"another","type":"word"},{"cn":"横过，穿过","en":"across","type":"word"},{"cn":"在周围；环绕；在……周围","en":"around","type":"word"},{"cn":"欧洲","en":"europe","type":"word"},{"cn":"尚；还；仍然","en":"yet","type":"word"},{"cn":"变得（become的过去式）","en":"became","type":"word"},{"cn":"伊文茨","en":"events","type":"word"},{"cn":"人的;人类的； 人类","en":"human","type":"word"},{"cn":"商店","en":"store","type":"word"},{"cn":"(不可数)纸；(可数)报纸；考卷；文件","en":"paper","type":"word"},{"cn":"种植；播种 植物","en":"plant","type":"word"},{"cn":"今天；当今","en":"today","type":"word"},{"cn":"故事；小说","en":"story","type":"word"},{"cn":"五十；五十个；编号为50的东西 adj. 五十的；五十个的；众多的","en":"fifty","type":"word"},{"cn":"年；年龄；岁月；年代","en":"years","type":"word"},{"cn":"书籍（book的复数）；书评 v. 预订；领会（book的第三人称单数）；把…记载入册","en":"books","type":"word"},{"cn":"标记，记号；唛头，分数；台面标志 n. (Marks)人名；(英、德、意、瑞典、西、捷)马克斯；(俄)马克思","en":"marks","type":"word"},{"cn":"最近的；紧挨着的；隔壁的；下一次的","en":"next","type":"word"},{"cn":"页；页码","en":"page","type":"word"}],"passage":{"title":"The History of Books","html":"<p>The <b>book</b>, as a <b>physical</b> object designed to <b>store</b> and transmit <b>knowledge</b>, has undergone a remarkable evolution spanning more than five millennia. Its <b>story</b> begins not with <b>paper</b> and ink but with clay. In <b>ancient</b> Mesopotamia, Sumerian scribes pressed wedge-shaped <b>marks</b> into damp clay tablets, creating the <b>first</b> durable written records. The <b>next</b> <b>great</b> innovation came from Egypt, where the papyrus scroll <b>became</b> the dominant format of the <b>ancient</b> Mediterranean <b>world</b>. Made from the pith of the papyrus <b>plant</b>, these scrolls were lightweight and portable, enabling the <b>great</b> libraries of Alexandria and Pergamum to amass vast collections. The codex, or bound <b>book</b> with pages, emerged in the Roman <b>world</b> <b>around</b> the <b>first</b> <b>century</b> CE and gradually replaced the scroll. The codex offered revolutionary advantages: it could be opened to any <b>page</b> instantly, written on both sides, and stacked on shelves with the spine facing outward. The <b>invention</b> of movable-type printing by Johannes Gutenberg in the mid-fifteenth <b>century</b> stands as one of the most consequential <b>events</b> in <b>human</b> <b>history</b>. Within <b>fifty</b> <b>years</b>, millions of <b>books</b> circulated <b>across</b> <b>Europe</b>. <b>Today</b>, the <b>book</b> is undergoing <b>yet</b> <b>another</b> metamorphosis <b>through</b> digital texts, <b>yet</b> the codex has proven remarkably resilient. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p>"}},{"name":"中国传统节日","entries":[{"cn":"节日","en":"festival","type":"word"},{"cn":"中国的；中国人的；汉语的  中国人；汉语","en":"chinese","type":"word"},{"cn":"年","en":"year","type":"word"},{"cn":"家庭；家族；家人","en":"family","type":"word"},{"cn":"人；人们；人民","en":"people","type":"word"},{"cn":"传统的","en":"traditional","type":"word"},{"cn":"重要的","en":"important","type":"word"},{"cn":"亲属","en":"relative","type":"word"},{"cn":"时间；次；倍数","en":"time","type":"word"},{"cn":"历史;历史学","en":"history","type":"word"},{"cn":"自然的；天然的","en":"natural","type":"word"},{"cn":"欢迎","en":"welcome","type":"word"},{"cn":"秋天，秋季","en":"autumn","type":"word"},{"cn":"听从；跟随；仿效；跟得上","en":"follow","type":"word"},{"cn":"春天﹐春季","en":"spring","type":"word"},{"cn":"水 浇水","en":"water","type":"word"},{"cn":"当地的；地方的","en":"local","type":"word"},{"cn":"扫；打扫","en":"sweep","type":"word"},{"cn":"圆的 转一圈 围绕","en":"round","type":"word"},{"cn":"世界","en":"world","type":"word"},{"cn":"标记，记号；唛头，分数；台面标志 n. (Marks)人名；(英、德、意、瑞典、西、捷)马克斯；(俄)马克思","en":"marks","type":"word"},{"cn":"小船，小舟；v. 划船（游玩）","en":"boat","type":"word"},{"cn":"月球；月亮","en":"moon","type":"word"},{"cn":"富裕的；丰富的","en":"rich","type":"word"},{"cn":"救；挽救；节省；储蓄","en":"save","type":"word"},{"cn":"转向；转变；转动 轮流；顺序","en":"turn","type":"word"},{"cn":"满的，充满的；完全的","en":"full","type":"word"},{"cn":"形式；方式","en":"form","type":"word"},{"cn":"说（第三人称单数）","en":"says","type":"word"},{"cn":"米﹔米饭","en":"rice","type":"word"}],"passage":{"title":"Traditional Chinese Festivals","html":"<p><b>Traditional</b> <b>Chinese</b> festivals <b>form</b> a <b>rich</b> tapestry of celebration that connects the <b>Chinese</b> <b>people</b> to their <b>history</b>, their families, and the rhythms of the <b>natural</b> <b>world</b>. Most of these festivals <b>follow</b> the lunar calendar, which means their dates shift from <b>year</b> to <b>year</b> <b>relative</b> to the Western solar calendar. The <b>Spring</b> <b>Festival</b>, or <b>Chinese</b> New <b>Year</b>, is the most <b>important</b> celebration of the <b>year</b>. It <b>marks</b> the <b>turn</b> of the lunar calendar and is a <b>time</b> for <b>family</b> reunions, elaborate feasts, and rituals designed to <b>sweep</b> away misfortune and <b>welcome</b> prosperity. The Dragon <b>Boat</b> <b>Festival</b> commemorates the patriotic poet Qu Yuan, who drowned himself in protest against political corruption. Legend <b>says</b> that <b>local</b> <b>people</b> raced out in boats to <b>save</b> him and threw <b>rice</b> dumplings into the <b>water</b>. The Mid-<b>Autumn</b> <b>Festival</b> centers on the <b>full</b> <b>moon</b> at its brightest and roundest. It is a harvest celebration and a <b>time</b> for <b>family</b> togetherness, symbolized by the <b>round</b> mooncakes shared among loved ones. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p>"}},{"name":"中国文化中的龙","entries":[{"cn":"中国的；中国人的；汉语的  中国人；汉语","en":"chinese","type":"word"},{"cn":"想象力；空想；幻想物","en":"imagination","type":"word"},{"cn":"水 浇水","en":"water","type":"word"},{"cn":"不同的，有差异的","en":"different","type":"word"},{"cn":"呼吸；瞬间；微风 adj. 呼吸的；逼真的 v. 呼吸（breathe的现在分词）","en":"breathing","type":"word"},{"cn":"控制","en":"control","type":"word"},{"cn":"特别的；特殊的","en":"special","type":"word"},{"cn":"文化","en":"culture","type":"word"},{"cn":"高度","en":"height","type":"word"},{"cn":"几乎不","en":"hardly","type":"word"},{"cn":"要紧事；麻烦事；事情；问题；物质","en":"matter","type":"word"},{"cn":"变得（become的过去式）","en":"became","type":"word"},{"cn":"今天；当今","en":"today","type":"word"},{"cn":"死神","en":"death","type":"word"},{"cn":"勇敢的","en":"brave","type":"word"},{"cn":"已知的；知名的；大家知道的 v. 知道（know的过去分词）","en":"known","type":"word"},{"cn":"火；火炉；火灾","en":"fire","type":"word"},{"cn":"头;头脑;首脑","en":"head","type":"word"},{"cn":"明智的；聪明的","en":"wise","type":"word"},{"cn":"生命；生活；人生","en":"life","type":"word"},{"cn":"好的;良好的","en":"good","type":"word"},{"cn":"(时间)长的；(距离)远的","en":"long","type":"word"},{"cn":"眼睛（eye的复数） n. (Eyes)人名；(英)艾斯","en":"eyes","type":"word"}],"passage":{"title":"Dragons in Chinese Culture","html":"<p>In the Western <b>imagination</b>, dragons are typically fearsome, <b>fire</b>-<b>breathing</b> monsters to be slain by <b>brave</b> heroes. <b>Chinese</b> dragons could <b>hardly</b> be more <b>different</b>. <b>Known</b> as <b>long</b>, these serpentine beings are benevolent, <b>wise</b>, and intimately associated with <b>water</b>, fertility, and <b>good</b> fortune. The <b>Chinese</b> dragon is a composite creature, traditionally described as having the <b>head</b> of a camel, the horns of a deer, the <b>eyes</b> of a rabbit, the neck of a snake, and the scales of a carp. <b>Water</b> is the dragon's <b>special</b> domain. <b>Chinese</b> dragons are believed to dwell in rivers, lakes, and oceans, where they <b>control</b> rainfall, tides, and floods. In an agricultural civilization, the dragon's goodwill was literally a <b>matter</b> of <b>life</b> and <b>death</b>. The dragon's imperial association reached its <b>height</b> during the Ming and Qing dynasties, when the five-clawed dragon <b>became</b> the exclusive emblem of the emperor. <b>Today</b>, the dragon remains a beloved presence in <b>Chinese</b> <b>culture</b>. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p>"}},{"name":"中国饮食文化","entries":[{"cn":"中国的；中国人的；汉语的  中国人；汉语","en":"chinese","type":"word"},{"cn":"经验；经历","en":"experience","type":"word"},{"cn":"重要性","en":"importance","type":"word"},{"cn":"收集","en":"collection","type":"word"},{"cn":"练习；实践","en":"practice","type":"word"},{"cn":"快乐；希望；娱乐；令人高兴的事 vt. 使高兴；使满意 vi. 高兴；寻欢作乐","en":"pleasure","type":"word"},{"cn":"古代的；古老的","en":"ancient","type":"word"},{"cn":"医学的；医疗的","en":"medical","type":"word"},{"cn":"再一；另一；别的；不同的；pron. 另一个","en":"another","type":"word"},{"cn":"包括;包含","en":"include","type":"word"},{"cn":"平衡","en":"balance","type":"word"},{"cn":"健康","en":"health","type":"word"},{"cn":"三十","en":"thirty","type":"word"},{"cn":"不能；无法","en":"cannot","type":"word"},{"cn":"吃；食物 v. 吃（eat的ing形式） adj. 侵蚀的；可生食的；进餐用的","en":"eating","type":"word"},{"cn":"在……上面","en":"above","type":"word"},{"cn":"当地的；地方的","en":"local","type":"word"},{"cn":"主要的","en":"major","type":"word"},{"cn":"其他的；另外的","en":"other","type":"word"},{"cn":"伟大的;重要的;(口语)好极了;很好","en":"great","type":"word"},{"cn":"小的；少的","en":"small","type":"word"},{"cn":"食物，食品","en":"food","type":"word"},{"cn":"在……上方；越过；遍及；超过 结束；越过；翻转","en":"over","type":"word"},{"cn":"另外,其他","en":"else","type":"word"},{"cn":"热度,热量；加热","en":"heat","type":"word"},{"cn":"深的","en":"deep","type":"word"},{"cn":"高的","en":"high","type":"word"},{"cn":"形式；方式","en":"form","type":"word"},{"cn":"福尔；","en":"four","type":"word"},{"cn":"红色的 红色","en":"red","type":"word"}],"passage":{"title":"Chinese Cooking: Culinary Philosophy and Techniques","html":"<p><b>Chinese</b> cuisine is not merely a <b>collection</b> of recipes but a comprehensive philosophy of <b>food</b> that integrates concerns for flavor, <b>health</b>, texture, and aesthetic <b>pleasure</b>. At its foundation lies the <b>ancient</b> concept of <b>balance</b>, rooted in the complementary forces of yin and yang. The <b>importance</b> of texture in <b>Chinese</b> cooking <b>cannot</b> be overstated. While Western cuisines tend to prioritize flavor <b>above</b> all <b>else</b>, <b>Chinese</b> gastronomy values mouthfeel as an equally essential dimension of the <b>eating</b> <b>experience</b>. <b>Chinese</b> culinary technique is remarkably diverse, encompassing <b>over</b> <b>thirty</b> distinct cooking methods. Stir-frying involves cooking <b>small</b>, uniformly cut ingredients at <b>high</b> <b>heat</b> in a wok with constant motion. <b>Other</b> <b>major</b> techniques <b>include</b> steaming, <b>red</b>-cooking, and <b>deep</b>-frying. Regional diversity is <b>another</b> defining feature. The <b>four</b> <b>great</b> traditions each embody distinct climatic conditions, <b>local</b> ingredients, and culinary sensibilities. Underlying all these techniques is a deeper conviction: that cooking is a <b>form</b> of cultural and <b>medical</b> <b>practice</b>. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p>"}},{"name":"笑声的科学与艺术","entries":[{"cn":"某事；某物","en":"something","type":"word"},{"cn":"语言","en":"language","type":"word"},{"cn":"研究；调查","en":"research","type":"word"},{"cn":"身体的；物理的","en":"physical","type":"word"},{"cn":"自然的；天然的","en":"natural","type":"word"},{"cn":"解释；说明","en":"explain","type":"word"},{"cn":"释放，排放；发表","en":"release","type":"word"},{"cn":"环境；上下文；来龙去脉","en":"context","type":"word"},{"cn":"人；人们；人民","en":"people","type":"word"},{"cn":"社会的；社交的","en":"social","type":"word"},{"cn":"出现","en":"appear","type":"word"},{"cn":"三十","en":"thirty","type":"word"},{"cn":"很可能的","en":"likely","type":"word"},{"cn":"其他人","en":"others","type":"word"},{"cn":"人的;人类的； 人类","en":"human","type":"word"},{"cn":"笑，大笑；嘲笑","en":"laugh","type":"word"},{"cn":"其他的；另外的","en":"other","type":"word"},{"cn":"信任；信赖","en":"trust","type":"word"},{"cn":"第一的；最初的 第一；首先，最初 开始；开端","en":"first","type":"word"},{"cn":"单独的；单独地","en":"alone","type":"word"},{"cn":"思想；主意（mind的复数） v. 介意；照顾；留心（mind的第三人称单数）","en":"minds","type":"word"},{"cn":"时代（time的复数）；[数] 次数 prep. 乘以 v. 使…相乘（time的第三人称单数）","en":"times","type":"word"},{"cn":"作品；工厂；工程结构 n. (Works)人名；(英)沃克斯","en":"works","type":"word"},{"cn":"身体","en":"body","type":"word"},{"cn":"有;吃;喝;进行","en":"have","type":"word"},{"cn":"同一的；相同的","en":"same","type":"word"},{"cn":"真实的；真的","en":"true","type":"word"},{"cn":"路；方法；方式","en":"way","type":"word"},{"cn":"可以；也许，可能","en":"may","type":"word"},{"cn":"尚；还；仍然","en":"yet","type":"word"}],"passage":{"title":"Why We Laugh","html":"<p>Laughter is one of the most universal <b>human</b> behaviors, <b>yet</b> its origins and functions are more complex than they <b>first</b> <b>appear</b>. At its core, laughter is a nonverbal vocalization that predates <b>language</b>, emerging from the <b>same</b> evolutionary pressures that shaped <b>other</b> primate vocal signals. From a psychological perspective, the incongruity theory holds that humor arises when we encounter <b>something</b> that violates our expectations in a nonthreatening <b>way</b>. A punchline <b>works</b> because it subverts the logical path our <b>minds</b> <b>have</b> been tracing. The <b>physical</b> act of laughing involves a complex choreography of muscles and physiological systems. Remarkably, laughter triggers the <b>release</b> of endorphins, the <b>body</b>'s <b>natural</b> painkillers, which <b>may</b> <b>explain</b> why shared laughter can foster feelings of closeness and <b>trust</b>. <b>Social</b> <b>context</b> is central to understanding laughter's <b>true</b> function. <b>Research</b> has shown that <b>people</b> are approximately <b>thirty</b> <b>times</b> more <b>likely</b> to <b>laugh</b> in the presence of <b>others</b> than when <b>alone</b>. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p>"}},{"name":"数字的历史","entries":[{"cn":"为…设立总部；使以…为基础﹐使以…为根据","en":"base","type":"word"},{"cn":"发展","en":"development","type":"word"},{"cn":"故事；小说","en":"story","type":"word"},{"cn":"不同的，有差异的","en":"different","type":"word"},{"cn":"语言","en":"language","type":"word"},{"cn":"前进（advance的复数）；预付款；求爱 v. 提出；使前进；提前（advance的三单形式）","en":"advances","type":"word"},{"cn":"在(两者)之间；在……中间","en":"between","type":"word"},{"cn":"发展；开发，培养","en":"develop","type":"word"},{"cn":"能力；才能","en":"ability","type":"word"},{"cn":"数；数字；号码；数量","en":"number","type":"word"},{"cn":"象征；符号","en":"symbol","type":"word"},{"cn":"二十的","en":"twenty","type":"word"},{"cn":"人的;人类的； 人类","en":"human","type":"word"},{"cn":"晚些的，迟些的","en":"later","type":"word"},{"cn":"第一的；最初的 第一；首先，最初 开始；开端","en":"first","type":"word"},{"cn":"世界","en":"world","type":"word"},{"cn":"小的；少的","en":"small","type":"word"},{"cn":"电源；能源；动力；电力","en":"power","type":"word"},{"cn":"小时（hour的复数形式） n. (Hours)人名；(法)乌尔","en":"hours","type":"word"},{"cn":"使用（use的现在分词）","en":"using","type":"word"},{"cn":"，见识","en":"sense","type":"word"},{"cn":"(时间)长的；(距离)远的","en":"long","type":"word"},{"cn":"成功的；创造的 v. 做，使，安排（make的过去式和过去分词） n. (Made)人名；(塞)马德 原型: made 是 make 的过去式和过去分词","en":"made","type":"word"},{"cn":"自己的 拥有","en":"own","type":"word"},{"cn":"十","en":"ten","type":"word"}],"passage":{"title":"The History of Numbers","html":"<p>The <b>story</b> of numbers is a <b>story</b> of <b>human</b> civilization itself, tracing our gradual awakening to the patterns and quantities that structure the <b>world</b>. <b>Long</b> before written <b>language</b>, our ancestors possessed an innate <b>number</b> <b>sense</b>, a rough <b>ability</b> to distinguish <b>between</b> <b>small</b> quantities. The earliest concrete evidence of counting comes from prehistoric tally sticks and bones marked with notches. <b>Later</b>, the Sumerians of Mesopotamia developed a sophisticated system <b>using</b> clay tokens, eventually evolving into cuneiform numerals. <b>Different</b> civilizations independently invented their <b>own</b> approaches. The Babylonians developed a <b>base</b>-sixty system whose legacy endures in our division of <b>hours</b> into sixty minutes. The Mayans crafted a <b>base</b>-<b>twenty</b> system and were among the <b>first</b> to <b>develop</b> a <b>symbol</b> for zero. The most transformative <b>development</b> was the Hindu-Arabic numeral system, which introduced zero, positional notation, and a <b>base</b>-<b>ten</b> structure. These innovations <b>made</b> arithmetic vastly more efficient, enabling the computational <b>advances</b> that would <b>power</b> the scientific revolution. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p>"}},{"name":"儿童如何学会语言","entries":[{"cn":"孩子们（child的复数）","en":"children","type":"word"},{"cn":"的三单形式","en":"words","type":"word"},{"cn":"语言","en":"language","type":"word"},{"cn":"在周围；环绕；在……周围","en":"around","type":"word"},{"cn":"的复数","en":"months","type":"word"},{"cn":"发展","en":"development","type":"word"},{"cn":"孩子，儿童","en":"child","type":"word"},{"cn":"人的;人类的； 人类","en":"human","type":"word"},{"cn":"理解；懂得","en":"understand","type":"word"},{"cn":"第一的；最初的 第一；首先，最初 开始；开端","en":"first","type":"word"},{"cn":"经验；经历","en":"experience","type":"word"},{"cn":"生日","en":"birthday","type":"word"},{"cn":"强大的","en":"powerful","type":"word"},{"cn":"旅行；旅程","en":"journey","type":"word"},{"cn":"在(两者)之间；在……中间","en":"between","type":"word"},{"cn":"代替,顶替","en":"instead","type":"word"},{"cn":"能力；才能","en":"ability","type":"word"},{"cn":"母亲","en":"mother","type":"word"},{"cn":"出现","en":"appear","type":"word"},{"cn":"单一的；单个的；单身的","en":"single","type":"word"},{"cn":"演讲；演说","en":"speech","type":"word"},{"cn":"不能；无法","en":"cannot","type":"word"},{"cn":"说；讲","en":"speak","type":"word"},{"cn":"世界","en":"world","type":"word"},{"cn":"清晰的；明亮的；清楚的  清除；清扫","en":"clear","type":"word"},{"cn":"年轻的","en":"young","type":"word"},{"cn":"年；年龄；岁月；年代","en":"years","type":"word"},{"cn":"统治；支配；裁定（rule的第三人称单数形式）","en":"rules","type":"word"},{"cn":"作品；工厂；工程结构 n. (Works)人名；(英)沃克斯","en":"works","type":"word"},{"cn":"给……看；展示；表明","en":"show","type":"word"}],"passage":{"title":"How Children Learn Language","html":"<p>The <b>ability</b> of <b>young</b> <b>children</b> to acquire <b>language</b> is one of the most remarkable phenomena in <b>human</b> <b>development</b>. Within just a few <b>years</b>, a newborn who <b>cannot</b> <b>speak</b> or <b>understand</b> a <b>single</b> word becomes a fluent conversationalist capable of producing thousands of <b>words</b> and intricate grammatical <b>rules</b>. The <b>journey</b> begins before birth. Even in the womb, a developing fetus can perceive the rhythm and melody of the <b>mother</b>'s <b>speech</b>. After birth, infants <b>show</b> a <b>clear</b> preference for <b>human</b> voices, and within <b>months</b> they can distinguish <b>between</b> the phonemes of all the <b>world</b>'s languages. The <b>first</b> <b>words</b> typically <b>appear</b> <b>around</b> the <b>child</b>'s <b>first</b> <b>birthday</b>. By <b>around</b> eighteen <b>months</b>, many <b>children</b> <b>experience</b> a vocabulary spurt, learning ten or more new <b>words</b> every day. <b>Children</b> employ <b>powerful</b> cognitive strategies to map <b>words</b> onto meanings. Grammar emerges gradually and in predictable stages. <b>Children</b>'s errors reveal systematic hypotheses about how <b>language</b> <b>works</b>. When a <b>child</b> says \"I goed\" <b>instead</b> of \"I went,\" they demonstrate that they have internalized grammatical patterns. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p>"}},{"name":"友谊如何塑造我们","entries":[{"cn":"友谊","en":"friendship","type":"word"},{"cn":"幼年时代，童年","en":"childhood","type":"word"},{"cn":"影响;作用;影响力;支配力；影响;左右;对……起作用;支配","en":"influence","type":"word"},{"cn":"早的 早地","en":"early","type":"word"},{"cn":"健康","en":"health","type":"word"},{"cn":"一贯地；一致地；坚实地","en":"consistently","type":"word"},{"cn":"独立的;有主见的","en":"independent","type":"word"},{"cn":"经历（experience的复数） v. 经历；体验到（experience的三单形式）","en":"experiences","type":"word"},{"cn":"他(她、它)们自己","en":"themselves","type":"word"},{"cn":"生活，[生物] 生命（life的复数） v. 生活（live的三单形式）；居住","en":"lives","type":"word"},{"cn":"研究；调查","en":"research","type":"word"},{"cn":"角色","en":"role","type":"word"},{"cn":"身体的；物理的","en":"physical","type":"word"},{"cn":"孩子们（child的复数）","en":"children","type":"word"},{"cn":"穿过；通过","en":"through","type":"word"},{"cn":"疾病","en":"illness","type":"word"},{"cn":"提供","en":"provide","type":"word"},{"cn":"快地；迅速地","en":"quickly","type":"word"},{"cn":"人；人们；人民","en":"people","type":"word"},{"cn":"过程；经过；课程","en":"course","type":"word"},{"cn":"将来，未来","en":"future","type":"word"},{"cn":"社会的；社交的","en":"social","type":"word"},{"cn":"较好的，更好的；更好地；较好的事物；较优者","en":"better","type":"word"},{"cn":"强壮的；坚强的","en":"strong","type":"word"},{"cn":"活的；现存的；活跃的；逼真的 n. 生活；生存；生计 v. 生活；居住（live的ing形式）；度过 n. (Living)人名；(英)利","en":"living","type":"word"},{"cn":"的比较级","en":"longer","type":"word"},{"cn":"人的;人类的； 人类","en":"human","type":"word"},{"cn":"欣赏;享受;喜欢","en":"enjoy","type":"word"},{"cn":"学习；学会","en":"learn","type":"word"},{"cn":"建筑；建造","en":"build","type":"word"}],"passage":{"title":"How Friendship Shapes Us","html":"<p><b>Friendship</b> is among the most profound and transformative forces in <b>human</b> life. From <b>early</b> <b>childhood</b> <b>through</b> old age, friendships shape our identities, <b>influence</b> our <b>health</b>, and <b>provide</b> the emotional scaffolding upon which we <b>build</b> meaningful <b>lives</b>. The developmental <b>role</b> of <b>friendship</b> begins in <b>early</b> <b>childhood</b>, when peer relationships help <b>children</b> <b>learn</b> the fundamental skills of <b>social</b> <b>living</b>: empathy, negotiation, and reciprocity. These <b>early</b> <b>experiences</b> establish templates for <b>future</b> relationships. During adolescence, friendships assume an even more central <b>role</b> as young <b>people</b> differentiate <b>themselves</b> from their families and forge <b>independent</b> identities. In adulthood, <b>research</b> <b>consistently</b> shows that adults with <b>strong</b> <b>friendship</b> networks <b>enjoy</b> <b>better</b> mental and <b>physical</b> <b>health</b>, recover more <b>quickly</b> from <b>illness</b>, and even live <b>longer</b>. The <b>influence</b> of <b>friendship</b> extends beyond individual wellbeing to shape the very <b>course</b> of our <b>lives</b>. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p>"}},{"name":"中国茶文化","entries":[{"cn":"茶；茶叶","en":"tea","type":"word"},{"cn":"中国的；中国人的；汉语的  中国人；汉语","en":"chinese","type":"word"},{"cn":"练习；实践","en":"practice","type":"word"},{"cn":"重要的","en":"important","type":"word"},{"cn":"注意，关心","en":"attention","type":"word"},{"cn":"准备（prepare的ing形式） adj. 准备的","en":"preparing","type":"word"},{"cn":"文化","en":"culture","type":"word"},{"cn":"思想；思考；想法；关心 v. 想，思考；认为（think的过去式和过去分词）","en":"thought","type":"word"},{"cn":"的过去分词","en":"enjoyed","type":"word"},{"cn":"社会的；社交的","en":"social","type":"word"},{"cn":"(人的)体型；外形；数字","en":"figure","type":"word"},{"cn":"简单的；简易的","en":"simple","type":"word"},{"cn":"美","en":"beauty","type":"word"},{"cn":"方法，办法","en":"method","type":"word"},{"cn":"空间；太空","en":"space","type":"word"},{"cn":"弄干净；打扫  清洁的；干净的","en":"clean","type":"word"},{"cn":"世界","en":"world","type":"word"},{"cn":"安静的","en":"quiet","type":"word"},{"cn":"见解；[计][建] 视图（view的复数）；景点；查看 v. 认为；观看（view的三单形式）","en":"views","type":"word"},{"cn":"房间；空间","en":"room","type":"word"},{"cn":"生命；生活；人生","en":"life","type":"word"},{"cn":"最好的；最好地；最；最好的人(或物)","en":"best","type":"word"},{"cn":"形式；方式","en":"form","type":"word"},{"cn":"学期；术语","en":"term","type":"word"},{"cn":"路；方法；方式","en":"way","type":"word"},{"cn":"艺术","en":"art","type":"word"},{"cn":"表演，扮演(角色)；行动","en":"act","type":"word"},{"cn":"/ pron.","en":"one","type":"word"}],"passage":{"title":"The Art of Chinese Tea","html":"<p><b>Chinese</b> <b>tea</b> <b>culture</b> represents <b>one</b> of the <b>world</b>'s most refined culinary traditions, a <b>practice</b> that transforms the <b>simple</b> <b>act</b> of <b>preparing</b> and drinking a beverage into an <b>art</b> <b>form</b>, a <b>social</b> ritual, and a path to spiritual cultivation. The central <b>figure</b> in classical <b>Chinese</b> <b>tea</b> is the gongfu <b>tea</b> ceremony, a <b>method</b> of preparation that originated in the Chaozhou region. The <b>term</b> gongfu hints at the ceremony's essence: it is a meditative discipline that rewards patience, <b>attention</b>, and refinement. The aesthetic principles governing <b>Chinese</b> <b>tea</b> emphasize simplicity, naturalness, and harmony. The implements are chosen for both function and <b>beauty</b>. The setting is equally <b>important</b>: <b>tea</b> is <b>best</b> <b>enjoyed</b> in a <b>quiet</b>, <b>clean</b> <b>space</b> where the senses can fully engage. Central to the philosophy is cha dao, the <b>Way</b> of <b>Tea</b>, which <b>views</b> the <b>practice</b> as a path to self-cultivation. Influenced by Daoist, Confucian, and Buddhist <b>thought</b>, cha dao teaches that virtues cultivated in the <b>tea</b> <b>room</b> extend outward into all aspects of <b>life</b>. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p>"}},{"name":"中国园林艺术","entries":[{"cn":"花园，果园，菜园","en":"garden","type":"word"},{"cn":"风景；风景画；景色；山水画；乡","en":"landscape","type":"word"},{"cn":"中国的；中国人的；汉语的  中国人；汉语","en":"chinese","type":"word"},{"cn":"自然的；天然的","en":"natural","type":"word"},{"cn":"水 浇水","en":"water","type":"word"},{"cn":"重要性","en":"importance","type":"word"},{"cn":"在(两者)之间；在……中间","en":"between","type":"word"},{"cn":"特别的；特殊的","en":"special","type":"word"},{"cn":"覆盖；包括；掩护（cover的过去分词） adj. 覆盖了的；隐蔽着的；有屋顶的","en":"covered","type":"word"},{"cn":"欧洲","en":"europe","type":"word"},{"cn":"自然；本质","en":"nature","type":"word"},{"cn":"公共的，公众的","en":"public","type":"word"},{"cn":"设计；策划","en":"design","type":"word"},{"cn":"活的；现存的；活跃的；逼真的 n. 生活；生存；生计 v. 生活；居住（live的ing形式）；度过 n. (Living)人名；(英)利","en":"living","type":"word"},{"cn":"地方；住所 放置","en":"place","type":"word"},{"cn":"空间；太空","en":"space","type":"word"},{"cn":"世界","en":"world","type":"word"},{"cn":"绘画；绘制；拉，拖","en":"draw","type":"word"},{"cn":"岩石；摇滚乐","en":"rock","type":"word"},{"cn":"工作；劳动","en":"work","type":"word"},{"cn":"拿;抱;握住;举行;进行;保持;容纳","en":"hold","type":"word"},{"cn":"生命；生活；人生","en":"life","type":"word"},{"cn":"艺术","en":"art","type":"word"},{"cn":"/ pron.","en":"one","type":"word"}],"passage":{"title":"Chinese Garden Art","html":"<p>The classical <b>Chinese</b> <b>garden</b> stands as <b>one</b> of the most distinctive achievements in <b>landscape</b> <b>design</b>, a <b>living</b> <b>work</b> of <b>art</b> that seeks to capture the essence of <b>nature</b> in a bounded <b>space</b>. Unlike the formal gardens of <b>Europe</b>, the <b>Chinese</b> <b>garden</b> aspires to recreate <b>natural</b> landscapes in miniature. The philosophical foundations <b>draw</b> deeply from Daoism, with its reverence for the <b>natural</b> <b>world</b>. The <b>garden</b> is conceived as a collaboration <b>between</b> the designer and the inherent qualities of the site. Rocks <b>hold</b> a <b>place</b> of <b>special</b> <b>importance</b>, functioning as sculptural objects, symbolic mountains, and microcosmic representations of the broader <b>landscape</b>. The most prized <b>garden</b> rocks are limestone formations sculpted by centuries of <b>water</b> erosion. <b>Water</b> is the <b>garden</b>'s vital counterpart to <b>rock</b>, representing the fluid, receptive principle. Pavilions, bridges, and <b>covered</b> walkways are placed as frames for the <b>landscape</b>. Beyond aesthetics, the <b>Chinese</b> <b>garden</b> served as a retreat from <b>public</b> <b>life</b>. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p>"}},{"name":"中国皮影戏","entries":[{"cn":"传统的","en":"traditional","type":"word"},{"cn":"表演；演出；行动","en":"performance","type":"word"},{"cn":"光；灯光","en":"light","type":"word"},{"cn":"历史的,历史上的","en":"historical","type":"word"},{"cn":"对话","en":"dialogue","type":"word"},{"cn":"千","en":"thousand","type":"word"},{"cn":"中国的；中国人的；汉语的  中国人；汉语","en":"chinese","type":"word"},{"cn":"古代的；古老的","en":"ancient","type":"word"},{"cn":"流行的；大众的；受欢迎的","en":"popular","type":"word"},{"cn":"跳舞；舞蹈 v. 跳舞；摇晃（dance的ing形式）","en":"dancing","type":"word"},{"cn":"横过，穿过","en":"across","type":"word"},{"cn":"在……后面；在后面；向后","en":"behind","type":"word"},{"cn":"艺术","en":"art","type":"word"},{"cn":"动物","en":"animal","type":"word"},{"cn":"明亮的；聪明的；灿烂的","en":"bright","type":"word"},{"cn":"艺术家；画家","en":"artist","type":"word"},{"cn":"屏幕；银幕","en":"screen","type":"word"},{"cn":"行动；活动；功能；战斗；情节 n. (Action)人名；(英)埃克申","en":"action","type":"word"},{"cn":"瓷器","en":"china","type":"word"},{"cn":"今天；当今","en":"today","type":"word"},{"cn":"魔术；魔法","en":"magic","type":"word"},{"cn":"小的；少的","en":"small","type":"word"},{"cn":"电源；能源；动力；电力","en":"power","type":"word"},{"cn":"技能；技巧","en":"skill","type":"word"},{"cn":"年；年龄；岁月；年代","en":"years","type":"word"},{"cn":"使用（use的现在分词）","en":"using","type":"word"},{"cn":"在……上方；越过；遍及；超过 结束；越过；翻转","en":"over","type":"word"},{"cn":"然后；那时；那么","en":"then","type":"word"},{"cn":"工作；劳动","en":"work","type":"word"},{"cn":"把……藏起来,隐藏","en":"hide","type":"word"}],"passage":{"title":"Chinese Shadow Puppetry","html":"<p><b>Chinese</b> shadow puppetry is an <b>ancient</b> theatrical <b>art</b> in which intricately cut leather figures are manipulated <b>behind</b> a translucent <b>screen</b> while a <b>bright</b> <b>light</b> casts their silhouettes into vivid, <b>dancing</b> shadows. For <b>over</b> two <b>thousand</b> <b>years</b>, this captivating form of storytelling has entertained audiences <b>across</b> <b>China</b>. The creation of shadow puppets is itself an <b>art</b> of extraordinary <b>skill</b>. <b>Traditional</b> puppets are made from <b>animal</b> <b>hide</b> which is scraped, stretched, and polished until thin and translucent. The <b>artist</b> <b>then</b> carves intricate designs <b>using</b> specialized knives. A shadow puppet <b>performance</b> involves multiple artists in tight coordination. The lead puppeteer manipulates the main characters while delivering <b>dialogue</b> in stylized voices. A <b>small</b> orchestra accompanies the <b>action</b>. The repertoire draws from classical literature, <b>historical</b> chronicles, and <b>popular</b> legends. <b>Today</b>, dedicated artists <b>work</b> to preserve and revitalize this heritage. The enduring <b>power</b> of shadow puppetry lies in the elemental <b>magic</b> of <b>light</b> and shadow. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p>"}},{"name":"清晨的日常","entries":[{"cn":"通常；经常","en":"usually","type":"word"},{"cn":"报纸","en":"newspaper","type":"word"},{"cn":"厨房","en":"kitchen","type":"word"},{"cn":"装饰；给…穿衣；布置（dress的过去分词） adj. 穿好衣服的；打扮好的；去内脏及分割加工好的（特指动物，如鱼，禽类等）","en":"dressed","type":"word"},{"cn":"歌唱；歌声；耳鸣；振鸣 v. 唱歌（sing的ing形式） adj. 唱歌的；音乐般的","en":"singing","type":"word"},{"cn":"瓶子","en":"bottle","type":"word"},{"cn":"成为；变得；得到；到达；具有","en":"get","type":"word"},{"cn":"房子;住宅;家","en":"house","type":"word"},{"cn":"检查；批改；支票；核对；检查","en":"check","type":"word"},{"cn":"警报","en":"alarm","type":"word"},{"cn":"油煎的","en":"fried","type":"word"},{"cn":"赶快;急忙；赶紧;急忙","en":"hurry","type":"word"},{"cn":"七","en":"seven","type":"word"},{"cn":"碗﹔钵；一碗之量","en":"bowl","type":"word"},{"cn":"令人愉快的；好的；漂亮的","en":"nice","type":"word"},{"cn":"谈话；交谈","en":"talk","type":"word"},{"cn":"洗；洗涤","en":"wash","type":"word"},{"cn":"确信的；肯定的","en":"sure","type":"word"},{"cn":"放，摆","en":"put","type":"word"},{"cn":"说；讲","en":"say","type":"word"},{"cn":"书包；提包；袋子","en":"bag","type":"word"},{"cn":"教育学学士","en":"bed","type":"word"},{"cn":"盒子；箱子","en":"box","type":"word"}],"passage":{"title":"A Morning Routine","html":"<p>Every morning, my <b>alarm</b> clock rings at six thirty. I slowly open my eyes and stretch my arms. Then I <b>get</b> <b class=\"gs\">out of</b> <b>bed</b>, <b>wash</b> my face, and brush my teeth. The cold water helps me <b class=\"gs\">wake up</b>. After that, I <b>get</b> <b>dressed</b> in my school uniform. My mother <b>usually</b> calls me from the <b>kitchen</b> to <b>hurry</b> up. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>Breakfast is always simple but <b>nice</b>. I <b>usually</b> have a <b>bowl</b> of rice porridge, a boiled egg, and a glass of warm milk. Sometimes my mother makes steamed buns or <b>fried</b> bread sticks. We sit together and <b>talk</b> a little while eating. My father reads the <b>newspaper</b> and drinks his tea. I try to eat quickly because the school bus comes at <b>seven</b> fifteen. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>Before I leave the <b>house</b>, I <b>check</b> my school <b>bag</b>. I <b class=\"gs\">make sure</b> I have all my books, notebooks, and pencils. My mother always reminds me to bring my water <b>bottle</b> and <b class=\"gs\">lunch</b> <b>box</b>. Then I <b class=\"gs\">put on</b> my shoes, <b>say</b> goodbye to my parents, and walk to the bus stop. The air is fresh and the birds are <b>singing</b>. It is the start of another school day. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p>"}},{"name":"放学后的时光","entries":[{"cn":"家庭作业","en":"homework","type":"word"},{"cn":"祖母﹔外祖母","en":"grandmother","type":"word"},{"cn":"篮球","en":"basketball","type":"word"},{"cn":"抱怨；投诉","en":"complain","type":"word"},{"cn":"傍晚;晚上","en":"evening","type":"word"},{"cn":"公司","en":"company","type":"word"},{"cn":"等待；服侍 v. 等待；伺候（wait的ing形式）；延缓 adj. 等待的；服侍的 n. (Waiting)人名；(英)韦廷","en":"waiting","type":"word"},{"cn":"在……旁边；靠近","en":"beside","type":"word"},{"cn":"奶油，乳脂","en":"cream","type":"word"},{"cn":"滑稽的；可笑的","en":"funny","type":"word"},{"cn":"(使)放松，轻松","en":"relax","type":"word"},{"cn":"班级；课；等级","en":"class","type":"word"},{"cn":"嘈杂的，喧闹的","en":"noisy","type":"word"},{"cn":"一块(片、张、件、段)；碎片；部件","en":"piece","type":"word"},{"cn":"卖；背叛，经营（sell第三人称形式） n. (Sells)人名；(英)塞尔斯","en":"sells","type":"word"},{"cn":"大门","en":"gate","type":"word"},{"cn":"钟；铃","en":"bell","type":"word"},{"cn":"包 打包","en":"pack","type":"word"},{"cn":"冲；奔跑","en":"rush","type":"word"},{"cn":"玩﹐玩耍","en":"play","type":"word"}],"passage":{"title":"After School","html":"<p>The <b <b>class</b>=\"gs\">last</b> <b>bell</b> rings at four thirty in the afternoon. Everyone stands up and says goodbye to the teacher. We <b>pack</b> our bags quickly and <b>rush</b> <b <b>class</b>=\"gs\">out of</b> the classroom. Some students run to the playground to <b>play</b> <b>basketball</b>. Others walk to the school <b>gate</b> where their parents are <b>waiting</b>. The school becomes <b>noisy</b> and full of energy. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>I usually walk home <b <b>class</b>=\"gs\">with</b> my best friend, Li Ming. We live in the same neighborhood. <b <b>class</b>=\"gs\">On the</b> way, we <b <b>class</b>=\"gs\">talk about</b> our day. We share <b>funny</b> stories from <b>class</b> and <b <b>class</b>=\"gs\">complain about</b> <b>homework</b>. Sometimes we stop at a small shop to buy snacks. The shop <b>sells</b> ice <b>cream</b>, candy, and cold drinks. We sit on a bench and enjoy our treats together. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>When I get home, my <b>grandmother</b> is usually there. She asks me about my day and gives me <b <b>class</b>=\"gs\">a <b>piece</b> of</b> fruit. I wash my hands and change <b <b>class</b>=\"gs\">out of</b> my school uniform. Then I sit at my desk and start my <b>homework</b>. I like to finish it before dinner so I can <b>relax</b> in the <b>evening</b>. My little dog sits <b>beside</b> me and keeps me <b>company</b>. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p>"}},{"name":"周末生活","entries":[{"cn":"周末（weekend的复数） adv. 在每周末","en":"weekends","type":"word"},{"cn":"家务活","en":"housework","type":"word"},{"cn":"星期六","en":"saturday","type":"word"},{"cn":"/ **bike** /baɪk/ 自行车","en":"bicycle","type":"word"},{"cn":"……点钟","en":"o'clock","type":"word"},{"cn":"朋友（friend的复数）","en":"friends","type":"word"},{"cn":"窗户","en":"window","type":"word"},{"cn":"电影","en":"movie","type":"word"},{"cn":"钢琴","en":"piano","type":"word"},{"cn":"手表；观看 观看；注视","en":"watch","type":"word"},{"cn":"行为；离去；工作情况；地面状况 v. 前进；出发；运转（go的ing形式） adj. 流行的；进行中的；现存的 n. (Going)人名；(英)戈因","en":"going","type":"word"},{"cn":"八字形","en":"eight","type":"word"},{"cn":"在……附近","en":"near","type":"word"},{"cn":"星期；周","en":"week","type":"word"},{"cn":"自行车﹐脚踏车﹐单车","en":"bike","type":"word"}],"passage":{"title":"A Weekend Day","html":"<p>On <b>Saturday</b> mornings, I do not need to <b class=\"gs\">wake up</b> early. I stay in bed until <b>eight</b> or even nine <b>o'clock</b>. The sunlight comes through the <b>window</b> and warms my room. I can hear my mother cooking breakfast and the sound of the television from the living room. It feels so good to have no rush and no school bell. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>After a late breakfast, I help my mother <b class=\"gs\">with</b> some <b>housework</b>. Then I ride my <b>bicycle</b> to the park <b>near</b> our home. Many people are there <b class=\"gs\">on weekends</b>. Old people do morning exercises and practice tai chi. Children run around and play games. I ride my <b>bike</b> along the paths and enjoy the fresh air and green trees. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>In the afternoon, I often meet my <b>friends</b>. We play football <b class=\"gs\">on the</b> sports field or go to the bookstore together. Sometimes we <b>watch</b> a <b class=\"gs\">movie</b> at my house. My mother makes popcorn for us. We laugh and have a great time. In the evening, I read a book or play the <b>piano</b> for a while before <b>going</b> to bed. <b>Weekends</b> are truly the best days of the <b>week</b>. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p>"}},{"name":"帮妈妈做家务","entries":[{"cn":"舒服的","en":"comfortable","type":"word"},{"cn":"卧室","en":"bedroom","type":"word"},{"cn":"洗涤；洗涤剂；要洗的衣物 v. 洗；使受洗礼（wash的ing形式） adj. 洗涤用的，清洗用的","en":"washing","type":"word"},{"cn":"自豪的；骄傲的","en":"proud","type":"word"},{"cn":"感谢；谢谢","en":"thank","type":"word"},{"cn":"脏的","en":"dirty","type":"word"},{"cn":"相貌 n. (Looks)人名；(英)卢克斯","en":"looks","type":"word"},{"cn":"整洁的 整理；收拾","en":"tidy","type":"word"},{"cn":"处绞刑;上吊","en":"hang","type":"word"},{"cn":"肥皂","en":"soap","type":"word"},{"cn":"任务","en":"task","type":"word"},{"cn":"努力地;使劲;猛烈地；硬的;困难的;艰难的","en":"hard","type":"word"},{"cn":"西、罗","en":"done","type":"word"},{"cn":"干的;干燥的","en":"dry","type":"word"}],"passage":{"title":"Helping with Housework","html":"<p>My parents both work very <b>hard</b>. I think it is important for me to help <b class=\"gs\">with</b> housework <b class=\"gs\">at home</b>. I am not a little child anymore. I can do many things to make our home clean and <b>comfortable</b>. It also makes me feel <b>proud</b> when I finish a <b>task</b>. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>On Sundays, I have a list of chores to do. First, I make my bed and <b>tidy</b> up my desk. Then I sweep the floor in my <b>bedroom</b> and the living room. After sweeping, I use the mop to clean the floor. The floor <b>looks</b> bright and shiny when I am <b>done</b>. My mother always smiles and says <b>thank</b> you. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>Sometimes I also help <b class=\"gs\">with</b> the laundry. I put the <b>dirty</b> clothes into the <b>washing</b> machine and pour in the <b>soap</b>. When the machine finishes, I <b>hang</b> the clothes <b class=\"gs\">on the</b> balcony to <b>dry</b>. The clothes smell fresh and clean in the sun. Helping my family makes me feel closer to them. I believe every child should help <b class=\"gs\">at home</b>. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p>"}},{"name":"一次生日聚会","entries":[{"cn":"巧克力","en":"chocolate","type":"word"},{"cn":"蛋糕；糕点；饼","en":"cake","type":"word"},{"cn":"铅笔","en":"pencil","type":"word"},{"cn":"美好的；可爱的","en":"lovely","type":"word"},{"cn":"来到；到达 v. 来（come的ing形式） adj. 即将到来的；接着的；前途有望的","en":"coming","type":"word"},{"cn":"照片，图片；相册（photo的复数形式） v. 为…拍照（photo的第三人称单数形式）","en":"photos","type":"word"},{"cn":"看，瞧( look的过去式和过去分词 )；注意；面向；寻找","en":"looked","type":"word"},{"cn":"果汁","en":"juice","type":"word"},{"cn":"情况；案件；箱；盒","en":"case","type":"word"},{"cn":"毡；毡制品 v. 感觉（feel的过去式） vi. 粘结 vt. 使粘结；把…制成毡 n. (Felt)人名；(英、罗、芬、捷、瑞典)费尔特","en":"felt","type":"word"},{"cn":"给予（give的过去式） n. (Gave)人名；(塞内)加韦；(法)加夫","en":"gave","type":"word"},{"cn":"希望；祝福；心愿 vt. 祝愿；渴望；向…致问候语 v","en":"wish","type":"word"},{"cn":"大的","en":"big","type":"word"}],"passage":{"title":"A Birthday Party","html":"<p><b class=\"gs\">Last</b> Saturday was my fourteenth birthday. My parents planned a small party for me at our home. We decorated the living room <b class=\"gs\">with</b> colorful balloons and ribbons. A <b>big</b> birthday banner hung <b class=\"gs\">on the</b> wall. My mother baked a <b>chocolate</b> <b>cake</b> and put fourteen candles on it. Everything <b>looked</b> beautiful and festive. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>My friends arrived in the afternoon. They brought me <b class=\"gs\">love</b>ly gifts: books, a new <b>pencil</b> <b>case</b>, and a cool water bottle. We played games together and listened to music. My father took many <b>photos</b> of us laughing and dancing. The best moment was when they all sang \"Happy Birthday\" to me. I <b>felt</b> so happy and <b class=\"gs\">love</b>d. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>After the song, I made a <b>wish</b> and blew out the candles. Everyone clapped and cheered. Then my mother cut the <b>cake</b> and <b>gave</b> a piece to each friend. We also had <b>juice</b>, fruit, and snacks. The party <b class=\"gs\">last</b>ed until evening. When my friends left, I thanked them for <b>coming</b>. It was a day I will always remember. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p>"}},{"name":"逛超市","entries":[{"cn":"超市","en":"supermarket","type":"word"},{"cn":"买东西﹐购物","en":"shopping","type":"word"},{"cn":"走路；散步（walk的过去分词）","en":"walked","type":"word"},{"cn":"蔬菜","en":"vegetable","type":"word"},{"cn":"鸡；鸡肉","en":"chicken","type":"word"},{"cn":"篮子","en":"basket","type":"word"},{"cn":"星期日","en":"sunday","type":"word"},{"cn":"帮助（help的过去分词）","en":"helped","type":"word"},{"cn":"挑选；采摘（pick的过去式） adj. 采摘的；精选的","en":"picked","type":"word"},{"cn":"灯光（light的复数）；（供食用的）家畜的肺脏 v. 点亮（light的三单形式）","en":"lights","type":"word"},{"cn":"卖方要价 v. 问（ask的过去式）","en":"asked","type":"word"},{"cn":"肉","en":"meat","type":"word"},{"cn":"面积；范围；地区","en":"area","type":"word"},{"cn":"忙(碌)的","en":"busy","type":"word"},{"cn":"说（say的过去式和过去分词） adj. 上述的，该 n. (Said)人名；(西、塞、哈萨、乌兹、吉尔、塔吉、土库、阿塞、阿拉伯)赛义德","en":"said","type":"word"},{"cn":"得到，明白（get的过去式和过去分词） n. (Got)人名；(法)戈；(西、匈、瑞典)戈特","en":"got","type":"word"}],"passage":{"title":"Shopping at the Supermarket","html":"<p>On <b>Sunday</b> afternoon, my mother and I went to the <b>supermarket</b>. It is a big store not far from our home. We took a <b>shopping</b> <b>basket</b> and <b>walked</b> inside. The <b>supermarket</b> was <b>busy</b> <b class=\"gs\">with</b> many families doing their weekly <b>shopping</b>. Colorful signs and bright <b>lights</b> made everything look fresh and inviting. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>We first went to the fruit and <b>vegetable</b> section. My mother <b>picked</b> out fresh apples, bananas, and tomatoes. She taught me how to choose good vegetables by looking at their color and feeling their firmness. Then we moved to the <b>meat</b> and dairy <b>area</b>. We bought some <b>chicken</b>, eggs, and two bottles of milk. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>Next, we <b>walked</b> through the snack aisles. I <b>asked</b> my mother if we could buy some chips and cookies. She <b>said</b> yes but told me not to eat too many snacks. She also reminded me to read the price tags and compare different brands. Finally, we waited in a long line to pay. When we <b>got</b> home, I <b>helped</b> my mother put everything away in the cupboards and refrigerator. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p>"}},{"name":"整理房间","entries":[{"cn":"完全地，完整地","en":"completely","type":"word"},{"cn":"完成；结束；毁掉（finish的过去分词形式） adj. 完结的，完成的；精巧的","en":"finished","type":"word"},{"cn":"周末","en":"weekend","type":"word"},{"cn":"毯子﹐毛毯；厚（的覆盖）层","en":"blanket","type":"word"},{"cn":"的过去式和过去分词","en":"started","type":"word"},{"cn":"明确的；显然的；坚决的，果断的","en":"decided","type":"word"},{"cn":"容易地","en":"easily","type":"word"},{"cn":"架子；搁板","en":"shelf","type":"word"},{"cn":"镇静的；沉着的；使平静","en":"calm","type":"word"},{"cn":"去（go的过去分词） adj. 离去的；死去的；用光的","en":"gone","type":"word"},{"cn":"放，搁；下(蛋)","en":"lay","type":"word"},{"cn":"湿的；潮湿的","en":"wet","type":"word"},{"cn":"sit的过去式","en":"sat","type":"word"}],"passage":{"title":"Cleaning My Room","html":"<p>My room was very messy <b class=\"gs\">last</b> week. Books were <b class=\"gs\">all over</b> my desk. Dirty clothes <b>lay</b> <b class=\"gs\">on the</b> floor. My bed was not made and the window was dusty. I could not find my things <b>easily</b>. My mother asked me to clean it up. I knew she was right and it was time to <b class=\"gs\">take action</b>. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>I <b>started</b> by opening the curtains and the window. Fresh air came in right away. Then I took all the dirty clothes to the laundry basket. I made my bed and smoothed the <b>blanket</b>. Next, I put all the books back <b class=\"gs\">on the</b> <b>shelf</b> in order. I used a <b>wet</b> cloth to wipe my desk and the window sill. It took some time but the dust was <b>gone</b>. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>After organizing everything, I swept the floor and then mopped it carefully. When I <b>finished</b>, my room looked <b>completely</b> different. It was clean, bright, and comfortable. I <b>sat</b> on my bed and felt very happy. A clean room makes me feel <b>calm</b> and focused. From that day on, I <b>decided</b> to tidy my room every <b>weekend</b>. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p>"}},{"name":"停电的夜晚","entries":[{"cn":"姐；妹","en":"sister","type":"word"},{"cn":"星期四","en":"thursday","type":"word"},{"cn":"没有东西；没有什么","en":"nothing","type":"word"},{"cn":"沉默的；寂静的","en":"silent","type":"word"},{"cn":"，阐述","en":"talked","type":"word"},{"cn":"通常的；平常的","en":"usual","type":"word"},{"cn":"黑暗；暗处；深色","en":"dark","type":"word"},{"cn":"不久；很快","en":"soon","type":"word"},{"cn":"喊叫；哭","en":"cry","type":"word"},{"cn":"难过的；悲哀的；令人悲痛的","en":"sad","type":"word"}],"passage":{"title":"A Night Without Power","html":"<p>One <b>Thursday</b> evening, while I was doing my homework, the lights suddenly went out. The whole house became <b>dark</b> and <b>silent</b>. <b class=\"gs\">At first</b>, I was a little scared. My little <b>sister</b> started to <b>cry</b>. My father quickly found a flashlight and told us to stay calm. He said it was just a power cut and the electricity would come back <b>soon</b>. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>My mother lit some candles and placed them <b class=\"gs\">on the</b> dinner table. The soft candlelight made the room look warm and cozy. <b class=\"gs\">With</b>out the television and computer, we had <b>nothing</b> to do. So my father suggested we tell stories. He told us a funny story from his childhood. My mother shared a traditional folk tale. My <b>sister</b> and I listened <b class=\"gs\">with</b> great interest. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p><b class=\"gs\">With</b>out electricity, we could not use any appliances. We could not charge our phones or use the internet. But that night, we <b>talked</b> <b class=\"gs\">more than</b> <b>usual</b>. We laughed and shared our thoughts. It was actually a very special evening. When the power came back two hours later, I al<b class=\"gs\">most</b> felt a little <b>sad</b>. I learned that sometimes, simple moments <b class=\"gs\">with</b> family are the best. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p>"}},{"name":"我的教室","entries":[{"cn":"黑板","en":"blackboard","type":"word"},{"cn":"第三","en":"third","type":"word"},{"cn":"杂志（magazine的复数）","en":"magazines","type":"word"},{"cn":"角；角落；拐角","en":"corner","type":"word"},{"cn":"向别人）借用；借","en":"borrow","type":"word"},{"cn":"丰富，大量；充足 adj. 足够的，很多的 ad","en":"plenty","type":"word"},{"cn":"前面的；前部的 前面；前部；前线","en":"front","type":"word"},{"cn":"局﹐部﹐委员会〔用于机构名称〕","en":"board","type":"word"},{"cn":"月，月份","en":"month","type":"word"},{"cn":"转弯；匝数；圈数（turn的复数形式）；[机] 手动车床 v. 转弯；转动；倒置（turn的三单形式）","en":"turns","type":"word"},{"cn":"旗﹐旗帜；〔某些体育运动中的〕信号旗","en":"flag","type":"word"},{"cn":"让","en":"let","type":"word"}],"passage":{"title":"My Classroom","html":"<p>My classroom is <b class=\"gs\">on the</b> <b>third</b> floor of our school building. It is a bright and spacious room. There are two large windows that <b>let</b> in <b class=\"gs\">plenty of</b> sunlight. The walls are painted white and there is a big <b>blackboard</b> at the <b>front</b>. Above the <b>blackboard</b>, a Chinese national <b>flag</b> hangs proudly <b class=\"gs\">on the</b> wall. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>There are thirty-two desks and chairs in the classroom. They are arranged in four rows. My seat is in the <b>third</b> row near the window. I like this seat because I can see the trees outside. <b class=\"gs\">On the</b> back wall, there is a display <b>board</b>. We put our best drawings and writings there. It changes every <b>month</b> and always looks colorful and interesting. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>The classroom also has a small bookshelf in the <b>corner</b>. It contains storybooks, dictionaries, and <b>magazines</b>. Students can <b>borrow</b> them during the break. We take <b>turns</b> cleaning the classroom every day. We sweep the floor, wipe the <b>blackboard</b>, and water the plants. I like my classroom because it feels like a second home. It is a place where I learn and grow every day. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p>"}},{"name":"一堂有趣的课","entries":[{"cn":"气球","en":"balloon","type":"word"},{"cn":"极好的，精彩的，绝妙的；奇妙的；美妙；胜；神妙","en":"wonderful","type":"word"},{"cn":"令人惊讶的；令人赞叹的","en":"amazing","type":"word"},{"cn":"兴奋的","en":"excited","type":"word"},{"cn":"奇怪的；陌生的","en":"strange","type":"word"},{"cn":"课；功课；教训","en":"lesson","type":"word"}],"passage":{"title":"An Interesting Class","html":"<p>The <b class=\"gs\">most</b> interesting class I ever had was a science <b class=\"gs\"><b class=\"gs\">less</b>on</b> <b class=\"gs\">last</b> month. Our teacher, Mr. Wang, walked into the classroom carrying a big box. We all wondered what was inside. He put the box on his desk and smiled at us mysteriously. Everyone became curious and <b>excited</b> to see what would happen next. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>Mr. Wang opened the box and took out some <b>strange</b> things: a glass jar, <b class=\"gs\">a piece of</b> paper, a <b>balloon</b>, and some vinegar and baking soda. He told us we were going to do an experiment. First, he poured vinegar into the jar. Then he put baking soda <b class=\"gs\">on the</b> paper. He quickly poured the baking soda into the jar and covered it <b class=\"gs\">with</b> the <b>balloon</b>. Suddenly, white bubbles appeared inside the jar, and the <b>balloon</b> began to inflate all by itself. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>We all gasped and clapped. It felt like magic. Then Mr. Wang explained the science behind it. The vinegar and baking soda mixed together and made a gas called carbon dioxide. The gas had nowhere to go, so it filled the <b>balloon</b>. I thought it was <b>amazing</b>. That class made me <b class=\"gs\">love</b> science even more. I will never forget that <b>wonderful</b> experiment. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p>"}},{"name":"考试前后","entries":[{"cn":"考试,测试;检查","en":"exam","type":"word"},{"cn":"写（write的过去式）","en":"wrote","type":"word"},{"cn":"研究（study的ing形式）；学习","en":"studying","type":"word"},{"cn":"离开；残余；渣滓 v. 离开；留下；舍弃（leave的ing形式）","en":"leaving","type":"word"},{"cn":"复习；评论","en":"review","type":"word"},{"cn":"呼吸；一口气；气息","en":"breath","type":"word"},{"cn":"真正地；到底","en":"really","type":"word"},{"cn":"得分；分数","en":"score","type":"word"},{"cn":"最后的；终极的","en":"final","type":"word"}],"passage":{"title":"Before and After an Exam","html":"<p>A week before the <b>final</b> English <b>exam</b>, I was very nervous. I had so much to <b>review</b>: vocabulary, grammar rules, reading passages, and writing. Every day after school, I spent three hours <b>studying</b>. I <b>wrote</b> new words many times to remember them. I practiced listening by watching short English videos online. My mother encouraged me and brought me warm milk at night. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>The <b>exam</b> day arrived. I woke up early and had a good breakfast. I checked my pencils and eraser before <b>leaving</b> home. When I sat down in the <b>exam</b> room, my heart was beating fast. But when I read the first question, I calmed down. I knew the answers. I tried my best and <b>wrote</b> carefully. When the time was up, I handed in my paper and took a deep <b>breath</b>. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>After the <b>exam</b>, I felt both tired and relieved. My friends and I talked about the questions outside the classroom. Some were harder than others, but we all tried our best. Two weeks later, the results came out. I got a good <b>score</b>, and my parents were very proud. I learned that hard work <b>really</b> does pay off <b class=\"gs\">in the end</b>. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p>"}},{"name":"新同学","entries":[{"cn":"同班同学（classmate的复数）","en":"classmates","type":"word"},{"cn":"图书馆；图书室","en":"library","type":"word"},{"cn":"学生","en":"student","type":"word"},{"cn":"热情地；温暖地；亲切地","en":"warmly","type":"word"},{"cn":"加入；参加（join的过去式，过去分词）；[计] 连接","en":"joined","type":"word"},{"cn":"刘（姓氏）","en":"liu","type":"word"},{"cn":"喂;你好","en":"hello","type":"word"},{"cn":"旅行；旅游","en":"tour","type":"word"},{"cn":"高兴的；乐意的","en":"glad","type":"word"},{"cn":"(使)适合；与……相配 健康的；合适的","en":"fit","type":"word"}],"passage":{"title":"A New Classmate","html":"<p>At the start of this term, a new <b>student</b> <b>joined</b> our class. Her name is <b>Liu</b> Fang. She came from another city, so she did not know anyone. On her first day, she stood at the front of the classroom and introduced herself. She spoke in a soft voice and looked a little shy. Our teacher asked us to be kind and help her <b>fit</b> in. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>During the first break, I walked over to her desk and said <b>hello</b>. She smiled at me <b>warmly</b>. I asked her where she came from and what she liked to do. We found out that we both enjoy reading and drawing. I showed her around the school: the <b>library</b>, the playground, and the cafeteria. She seemed to feel more relaxed and happy after the <b>tour</b>. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>Soon, <b>Liu</b> Fang became good friends <b class=\"gs\">with</b> me and several other <b>classmates</b>. She is actually very funny and smart. In math class, she is one of the best students. She also draws beautiful pictures for the classroom display board. I am <b>glad</b> I talked to her on th<b class=\"gs\">at first</b> day. Making a new friend is always a wonderful and special thing. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p>"}},{"name":"图书馆的一天","entries":[{"cn":"小说","en":"novel","type":"word"},{"cn":"图书馆管理员","en":"librarian","type":"word"},{"cn":"使惊奇（surprise的过去分词形式） adj. 感到惊讶的，出人意料的","en":"surprised","type":"word"},{"cn":"入口;入场","en":"entrance","type":"word"},{"cn":"工程；课程；作业；项目；规划","en":"project","type":"word"},{"cn":"有用的；有益的","en":"useful","type":"word"},{"cn":"工作（work的过去式和过去分词） adj. 处理过的；制造好的；耕种过的","en":"worked","type":"word"},{"cn":"忘记；轻忽；遗漏（forget的过去式）","en":"forgot","type":"word"},{"cn":"注释，说明，笔记（note复数）；[金融] 票据 n. (Notes)人名；(意)诺泰斯","en":"notes","type":"word"},{"cn":"女孩","en":"girl","type":"word"},{"cn":"卡片","en":"card","type":"word"},{"cn":"乐趣；有趣的事；娱乐；玩笑","en":"fun","type":"word"},{"cn":"许多","en":"lot","type":"word"}],"passage":{"title":"A Day at the Library","html":"<p><b class=\"gs\">Last</b> Sunday, I spent the whole day at the city library. It is a large building <b class=\"gs\">with</b> three floors. The first floor has books for children and young people. The second floor is for adults. The third floor has computers and study rooms. I like the library because it is quiet and full of knowledge waiting to be discovered. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>I arrived at nine in the morning. I found a seat near the window where the light was good. First, I <b>worked</b> on my school <b>project</b> about animals. I found several <b>useful</b> books and took <b>notes</b> in my notebook. The library has many encyclopedias and science books that helped me a <b>lot</b>. Around noon, I ate my packed <b class=\"gs\">lunch</b> in the small café outside the main <b>entrance</b>. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>In the afternoon, I read a <b>novel</b> for <b>fun</b>. It was a story about a brave <b>girl</b> who travels around the world. I got so lost in the story that I <b>forgot</b> the time. When a <b>librarian</b> told me the library was closing soon, I was <b class=\"gs\">surprise</b>d. I borrowed the <b>novel</b> <b class=\"gs\">with</b> my library <b>card</b> so I could finish it <b class=\"gs\">at home</b>. I walked out feeling happy and proud of the work I had done. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p>"}},{"name":"英语演讲比赛","entries":[{"cn":"观众；听众","en":"audience","type":"word"},{"cn":"竞赛","en":"contest","type":"word"},{"cn":"小姐，女士(称呼未婚妇女)","en":"miss","type":"word"},{"cn":"自信的","en":"confident","type":"word"},{"cn":"准备，预备","en":"prepare","type":"word"},{"cn":"有帮助的;有益的","en":"helpful","type":"word"},{"cn":"接触；联系  与……来往，联系","en":"contact","type":"word"},{"cn":"害怕的；担心的","en":"afraid","type":"word"},{"cn":"忠告；劝告；建议","en":"advice","type":"word"},{"cn":"大声地","en":"loudly","type":"word"},{"cn":"奖赏；奖品","en":"prize","type":"word"},{"cn":"电话；电话机 打电话","en":"phone","type":"word"},{"cn":"大厅,会堂,礼堂","en":"hall","type":"word"}],"passage":{"title":"An English Speech Contest","html":"<p><b class=\"gs\">Last</b> month, our school held an English speech <b>contest</b>. My English teacher, <b>Miss</b> Li, encouraged me to take part. <b class=\"gs\">At first</b>, I was <b>afraid</b>. Speaking English <b class=\"gs\">in front of</b> many people seemed very difficult. But <b>Miss</b> Li said I had good pronunciation and should try my best. So I began to <b>prepare</b> a speech about protecting the environment. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>I practiced my speech every evening <b class=\"gs\">at home</b>. I spoke <b class=\"gs\">in front of</b> a mirror and recorded my voice on my <b>phone</b>. My father listened to me and gave me <b>helpful</b> <b>advice</b>. I learned to speak slowly and clearly, and to make eye <b>contact</b> <b class=\"gs\">with</b> the <b>audience</b>. <b>Miss</b> Li also helped me correct some grammar mistakes. Slowly, I became more <b>confident</b> and <b class=\"gs\">less</b> nervous. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p><b class=\"gs\">On the</b> day of the <b>contest</b>, the school <b>hall</b> was full of students. When my turn came, I took a deep breath and walked onto the stage. I began to speak, and after the first few sentences, my fear went away. I finished my speech and the <b>audience</b> clapped <b>loudly</b>. I did not win first <b>prize</b>, but I got third place. I was so proud of myself. That experience taught me that courage is more important than winning. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p>"}},{"name":"最喜欢的老师","entries":[{"cn":"有人，某人","en":"someone","type":"word"},{"cn":"乏味的；无聊的；令人厌烦的","en":"boring","type":"word"},{"cn":"失败，不成功（fail的过去式和过去分词） adj. 已失败的，不成功的","en":"failed","type":"word"},{"cn":"微笑","en":"smile","type":"word"},{"cn":"教；教授","en":"teach","type":"word"},{"cn":"停留；依靠；妇女胸衣（stay的复数） v. 停留；保持（stay的三单形式）；居住","en":"stays","type":"word"},{"cn":"散步，行走，跳板","en":"walks","type":"word"}],"passage":{"title":"My Favorite Teacher","html":"<p>Among all my teachers, my favorite is Miss Li, our English teacher. She is in her early thirties and always dresses neatly. She has a warm <b>smile</b> and kind eyes. When she <b>walks</b> into the classroom, everyone feels happy. Her classes are never <b>boring</b>. She always finds interesting ways to <b>teach</b> us new things. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>Miss Li does not just read from the textbook. She tells us stories <b class=\"gs\">in English</b> and plays English songs for us. Sometimes she organizes group activities and games. We act out dialogues, sing songs, and even perform short plays together. Learning English <b class=\"gs\">with</b> her is always fun. She also encourages us to speak English as much as possible, even if we make mistakes. She says mistakes are a natural part of learning. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>What I like <b class=\"gs\">most</b> about Miss Li is that she truly cares about every student. If <b>someone</b> is struggling <b class=\"gs\">with</b> a <b class=\"gs\"><b class=\"gs\">less</b>on</b>, she <b>stays</b> after class to help. She listens to our problems and gives us kind advice. Once, I <b>failed</b> a test and felt very sad. She talked to me and told me not to <b class=\"gs\">give up</b>. <b class=\"gs\">With</b> her help, my English improved a lot. She is not just a teacher to me, but also a good friend. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p>"}},{"name":"我的家庭","entries":[{"cn":"等级;(中小学的)学年;成绩,分数","en":"grade","type":"word"},{"cn":"最喜爱的","en":"favourite","type":"word"},{"cn":"科目；主题","en":"subject","type":"word"},{"cn":"办公室","en":"office","type":"word"},{"cn":"温柔的；轻轻的","en":"gentle","type":"word"},{"cn":"幸运的","en":"lucky","type":"word"},{"cn":"快的；敏捷的；迅速的","en":"quick","type":"word"},{"cn":"好恶；爱好的事物 v. 喜欢；愿意（like的第三人称单数形式） n. (Likes)人名；(英)莱克斯","en":"likes","type":"word"},{"cn":"照料；小心；介意；关心","en":"care","type":"word"},{"cn":"高的","en":"tall","type":"word"},{"cn":"成年男人；人；人类","en":"man","type":"word"}],"passage":{"title":"My Family","html":"<p>There are four people in my family. They are my father, my mother, my younger sister and me. We live in a small but warm apartment. My father is a <b>tall</b> <b>man</b>. He works in an <b>office</b>. My mother is kind and <b>gentle</b>. She stays <b class=\"gs\">at home</b> and takes <b>care</b> of all of us. She cooks very well. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>My sister is ten years old. She is in the fifth <b>grade</b>. She <b>likes</b> drawing and playing <b class=\"gs\">with</b> her dolls. Sometimes she is noisy, but I still <b class=\"gs\">love</b> her. She often asks me for help <b class=\"gs\">with</b> her homework. When I have time, I sit <b class=\"gs\">with</b> her and explain the problems. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>I am fourteen years old and I study in <b>Grade</b> Eight. Every morning I <b class=\"gs\">get up</b> at six thirty. After a <b>quick</b> breakfast, I ride my bicycle to school. The ride takes about fifteen minutes. School starts at eight and ends at four thirty. My <b>favourite</b> <b>subject</b> is English. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>In the evening, our family sits around the dinner table. We share stories about our day. My father tells us about his work. My sister talks about school. My mother listens and smiles. These are the happiest moments of my day. I feel <b>lucky</b> to have such a loving family. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p>"}},{"name":"最好的朋友","entries":[{"cn":"邻近地区；街坊","en":"neighbourhood","type":"word"},{"cn":"math /mæθ/) (通常作单数用)数学","en":"maths","type":"word"},{"cn":"草;草场;牧草","en":"grass","type":"word"},{"cn":"麻烦；烦恼","en":"trouble","type":"word"},{"cn":"眼镜","en":"glasses","type":"word"},{"cn":"回来；返回；归还","en":"return","type":"word"},{"cn":"一双，一对","en":"pair","type":"word"},{"cn":"跑（run的过去式） n. (Ran)人名；(俄、瑞典、塞)拉恩；(柬)兰","en":"ran","type":"word"}],"passage":{"title":"My Best Friend","html":"<p>My best friend is Li Wei. We have known <b class=\"gs\">each other</b> since we were very young. We live in the same <b>neighbourhood</b>. When we were little, we played in the park behind our building. We <b>ran</b> <b class=\"gs\">on the</b> <b>grass</b> and climbed the old trees. Now we are both in middle school. We are in different classes. Still, we meet every day after school. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>Li Wei is not very tall. He wears <b>glasses</b> and has a bright smile. He is good at <b>maths</b> and science. When I have <b>trouble</b> <b class=\"gs\">with</b> a <b>maths</b> problem, he explains it patiently. <b class=\"gs\">In return</b>, I help him <b class=\"gs\">with</b> his English homework. We work together as a team. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>We both <b class=\"gs\">love</b> sports. After school, we go to the basketball court. Li Wei is a fast runner and shoots well. I am better at passing. Together we make a good <b>pair</b>. When tired, we sit <b class=\"gs\">on the</b> <b>grass</b> and <b class=\"gs\">talk about</b> our dreams and funny things. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>Li Wei is a true friend. He never laughs at my mistakes. He listens when I am sad and cheers me up. I can share my secrets <b class=\"gs\">with</b> him. I know he will keep them safe. I hope we will stay friends forever. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p>"}},{"name":"祖父母家","entries":[{"cn":"美味的，可口的","en":"delicious","type":"word"},{"cn":"假日;假期","en":"holiday","type":"word"},{"cn":"味道；品味；审美 vt. 尝；体验 vi. 尝起来；有…的味道 n. (Taste)人名；(法)塔斯特","en":"tasted","type":"word"},{"cn":"青春；青年","en":"youth","type":"word"},{"cn":"的复数","en":"exams","type":"word"}],"passage":{"title":"At My Grandparents' House","html":"<p>My grandparents live in the countryside. Their house is two hours away <b class=\"gs\">by bus</b>. Every summer <b>holiday</b>, my family goes to visit them. I always <b class=\"gs\"><b class=\"gs\">look for</b>ward to</b> these trips. The countryside is so different from the busy city. I can see green fields, tall trees, and a clear blue sky. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>Their house is old but comfortable. It has a large yard <b class=\"gs\">with</b> flowers. My grandmother waters them every morning. There is a big old tree in the yard. Under it is a stone table and stools. On hot afternoons, we sit there in the cool shade. Sometimes I read or <b class=\"gs\">listen to</b> the birds. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>My grandfather is a quiet man. He likes reading newspapers and listening to the radio. He tells me stories about his <b>youth</b>. My grandmother is very kind. She cooks <b>delicious</b> meals. Her dumplings are the best I have <b>tasted</b>. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>Life in the countryside is slow and peaceful. I <b class=\"gs\">wake up</b> late and walk in the fields. There is no hurry, no homework, and no <b>exams</b>. When I go back to the city, I feel a little sad. But I know I will return soon. These days are among my <b class=\"gs\">most</b> treasured memories. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p>"}},{"name":"邻居","entries":[{"cn":"吉他","en":"guitar","type":"word"},{"cn":"关系","en":"relationship","type":"word"},{"cn":"夫人﹐太太〔对已婚妇女的礼貌称呼〕","en":"mrs","type":"word"},{"cn":"病人 耐心的","en":"patient","type":"word"},{"cn":"准备好的","en":"ready","type":"word"},{"cn":"甜的；甜蜜的","en":"sweet","type":"word"},{"cn":"的复数","en":"cakes","type":"word"},{"cn":"生病的；恶心的","en":"sick","type":"word"},{"cn":"儿子","en":"son","type":"word"}],"passage":{"title":"Our Neighbors","html":"<p>We have lived in this apartment building for six years. Next door lives the Wang family. They are very nice people. Mr Wang works as a doctor. <b>Mrs</b> Wang is a music teacher. They have a <b>son</b> named Wang Tao. He is two years older than me. He is tall, friendly, and good at playing the <b>guitar</b>. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>Our two families have a good <b>relationship</b>. <b>Mrs</b> Wang often brings us food that she has cooked. <b class=\"gs\">Last</b> week she made <b>sweet</b> rice <b>cakes</b>. My mother gives them fruits and vegetables. When there is a holiday, we sometimes eat dinner together. It feels like having a bigger family. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>Wang Tao and I are good friends. Sometimes in the evening, I can hear him playing his <b>guitar</b> through the wall. The music is soft and pleasant. He has taught me a few simple chords. I am not very good yet, but I am learning slowly. He is a <b>patient</b> teacher. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>Living <b class=\"gs\">next to</b> good neighbours is wonderful. If we need help, they are always <b>ready</b>. Once my mother was <b>sick</b>, and <b>Mrs</b> Wang brought her medicine. Another time, Mr Wang helped my father carry a heavy box up the stairs. Small acts of kindness like these make our building feel like a real community. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p>"}},{"name":"宠物狗","entries":[{"cn":"惊奇；惊讶","en":"surprise","type":"word"},{"cn":"成员；会员","en":"member","type":"word"},{"cn":"尺寸；大小","en":"size","type":"word"},{"cn":"尾巴","en":"tail","type":"word"},{"cn":"猫","en":"cat","type":"word"},{"cn":"问，询问；请求，要求","en":"ask","type":"word"},{"cn":"宠物","en":"pet","type":"word"}],"passage":{"title":"Our Pet Dog","html":"<p>Two years ago, my parents gave me a wonderful <b class=\"gs\">surprise</b>. It was a little puppy. He was white <b class=\"gs\">with</b> a brown spot on his right ear. I named him Dou Dou. When I first held him, he was so small that he fit in both my hands. He looked at me <b class=\"gs\">with</b> big round eyes. I <b class=\"gs\">love</b>d him right away. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>Now Dou Dou is a grown dog. He is not very big, about the <b>size</b> of a <b>cat</b>. He is full of energy. Every evening when I come back from school, he runs to the door. His <b>tail</b> wags so hard that his body shakes. He jumps up to lick my hands. It is the best welcome I could <b class=\"gs\">ask for</b>. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>Dou Dou is very smart. He can sit, roll over, and shake hands. I taught him these tricks <b class=\"gs\">with</b> snacks. Every morning at seven, he brings his leash to my father and waits by the door. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>Taking care of a <b>pet</b> is a big responsibility. I need to feed Dou Dou, give him water, and walk him. But it is worth it. Dou Dou is a <b>member</b> of our family. When I feel sad, he sits beside me and puts his head on my knee. It is his way of saying everything will be <b class=\"gs\">all right</b>. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p>"}},{"name":"表妹来做客","entries":[{"cn":"科学家","en":"scientist","type":"word"},{"cn":"林（姓氏）","en":"lin","type":"word"},{"cn":"动画片；卡通；漫画","en":"cartoon","type":"word"},{"cn":"堂(表)兄弟；堂(表)姐妹","en":"cousin","type":"word"},{"cn":"电影院；电影","en":"cinema","type":"word"},{"cn":"中心；中央","en":"centre","type":"word"},{"cn":"需求；欲望；必需品 v. 想要（want的第三人称单数）；渴望","en":"wants","type":"word"}],"passage":{"title":"My Cousin Visits","html":"<p><b class=\"gs\">Last</b> month, my <b>cousin</b> Chen <b>Lin</b> came to visit. She lives in another city about five hundred kilometres away. We do not see <b class=\"gs\">each other</b> often, usually only during the Spring Festival. I was very excited when my mother told me she was coming for a week. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>Chen <b>Lin</b> is the same age as me. We were born in the same year, just one month apart. <b class=\"gs\">On the</b> first day, we talked for hours. She told me about her school and her friends. I showed her around our neighbourhood. It felt like we had never been apart. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>During the week, we did many things together. We went to the new shopping <b>centre</b>. We watched a <b>cartoon</b> <b class=\"gs\">movie</b> at the <b>cinema</b>. We even cooked a simple <b class=\"gs\">lunch</b> by ourselves. It was only noodles <b class=\"gs\">with</b> eggs and vegetables, but we were very proud of it. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>The best part was the evening talks. At night, we lay in our beds and talked about everything. Chen <b>Lin</b> <b>wants</b> to become a <b>scientist</b>. I told her about my <b class=\"gs\">dream of</b> becoming a teacher. We promised to support <b class=\"gs\">each other</b>. When she left, I felt sad. But I know we will meet <b class=\"gs\">again</b>. Our friendship grows stronger every time. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p>"}},{"name":"做一顿饭","entries":[{"cn":"盘，碟；盘装菜；盘形物","en":"dish","type":"word"},{"cn":"小心的；仔细的","en":"careful","type":"word"},{"cn":"使变成（turn的过去式）；转动 adj. 被转动的；变质的；车削的","en":"turned","type":"word"},{"cn":"小刀","en":"knife","type":"word"},{"cn":"厨师  烹调；做饭","en":"cook","type":"word"}],"passage":{"title":"Cooking a Meal","html":"<p><b class=\"gs\">Last</b> Saturday, my mother had to <b class=\"gs\">go out</b> for the whole day. She asked me to <b>cook</b> <b class=\"gs\">lunch</b> for my father and sister. I was nervous because I had never cooked a full meal by myself. My mother left me some simple instructions. She told me to <b class=\"gs\">be <b>careful</b> <b class=\"gs\">with</b></b> the fire and the <b>knife</b>. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>I decided to make three dishes. The first was fried eggs <b class=\"gs\">with</b> tomatoes. I cut the tomatoes and beat three eggs. Then I heated the pan, added oil, and poured in the eggs. After they cooked, I added the tomatoes. The kitchen filled <b class=\"gs\">with</b> a wonderful smell. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>The second <b>dish</b> was stir-fried green beans. This was harder. I washed the beans and cut the ends. When I put them into the hot pan, the oil sizzled loudly. I kept stirring and so<b class=\"gs\">on the</b> beans <b>turned</b> bright green. I added salt and soy sauce. The third <b>dish</b> was a simple tofu and seaweed soup. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>When I put the dishes <b class=\"gs\">on the</b> table, my father and sister looked <b class=\"gs\">surprise</b>d. They said the food looked great. When they tasted it, they smiled and said it was delicious. My sister even asked for a second bowl of rice. I felt so proud. I learned that cooking just needs patience and care. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p>"}},{"name":"健康饮食","entries":[{"cn":"头痛","en":"headache","type":"word"},{"cn":"土豆，马铃薯","en":"potato","type":"word"},{"cn":"星期一","en":"monday","type":"word"},{"cn":"护士；保育员","en":"nurse","type":"word"},{"cn":"种类（kind的复数形式）","en":"kinds","type":"word"}],"passage":{"title":"Healthy Eating","html":"<p>When I started middle school, I did not think much about my diet. I liked fried chicken, <b>potato</b> chips, and sweet drinks. I often bought snacks from the shop near school. My mother told me to eat more vegetables and fruit. But I did not really listen. I thought <b class=\"gs\">as long as</b> food tasted good, it was fine. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>Then something made me change my mind. One <b>Monday</b> morning, I felt very sick. My stomach hurt and I had a <b>headache</b>. I went to see the school <b>nurse</b>. She asked what I had eaten for breakfast. I told her I had only drunk sweet milk tea. She said my body needed real food. A good breakfast should have bread, eggs, or noodles. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>After that day, I paid more attention to my meals. A healthy diet needs different <b>kinds</b> of food. Grains, like rice and noodles, give us energy. Proteins, like meat, eggs, and beans, build our muscles. Vegetables and fruit give us vitamins. We need water <b class=\"gs\">instead of</b> sugary drinks. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>Now I eat a good breakfast every morning. I take fruit as a snack. I have more energy. I focus better <b class=\"gs\">in class</b>. I do not get sick as often. Taking care of what you eat is one of the best things you can do. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p>"}},{"name":"看医生","entries":[{"cn":"诊所；医务室","en":"clinic","type":"word"},{"cn":"可怕的；糟糕的","en":"terrible","type":"word"},{"cn":"星期二","en":"tuesday","type":"word"},{"cn":"拥挤的","en":"crowded","type":"word"},{"cn":"星期五","en":"friday","type":"word"},{"cn":"担心；烦恼","en":"worry","type":"word"},{"cn":"等；等待","en":"wait","type":"word"},{"cn":"能够；有能力的","en":"able","type":"word"}],"passage":{"title":"Seeing the Doctor","html":"<p><b class=\"gs\">Last</b> <b>Tuesday</b>, I woke up feeling <b>terrible</b>. My head was hot and my throat sore. I tried to get <b class=\"gs\">out of</b> bed, but my body felt weak. My mother took my temperature. It was thirty-eight degrees. She took me to the community <b>clinic</b>. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>The <b>clinic</b> was not <b>crowded</b>. We waited about ten minutes before a nurse called my name. She led us to a small room and asked about my symptoms. Then the doctor came in. He was an older man <b class=\"gs\">with</b> a gentle voice. He looked at my throat and listened to my breathing. He said I had a cold and told me not to <b>worry</b>. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>The doctor gave me medicine. He told me to take it three times a day after meals. He said to drink warm water and rest. He smiled and said I would feel better in a few days. I asked if I could eat ice cream. He laughed and said I should <b>wait</b>. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>For the next two days, I stayed home. I drank warm water, took my medicine, and slept a lot. My mother made me a blanket and warm soup. By Thursday, I felt much better. I was even <b>able</b> to do some homework. I was happy to go back to school on <b>Friday</b>. I learned to see a doctor when sick. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p>"}},{"name":"运动会","entries":[{"cn":"使人兴奋的","en":"exciting","type":"word"},{"cn":"已经","en":"already","type":"word"},{"cn":"米，公尺","en":"metre","type":"word"},{"cn":"轨道；跑道；踪迹","en":"track","type":"word"},{"cn":"hear的过去式","en":"heard","type":"word"},{"cn":"男孩","en":"boy","type":"word"},{"cn":"枪;炮","en":"gun","type":"word"}],"passage":{"title":"Sports Day","html":"<p>The school Sports Day is one of the <b class=\"gs\">most</b> <b>exciting</b> events of the year. It is held in spring when the weather is warm. The whole school gathers <b class=\"gs\">on the</b> big sports field. Colourful flags hang along the <b>track</b>. Music plays from the loudspeakers. Everyone is full of energy. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>This year, I took part in two events. The first was the one-hundred-<b>metre</b> race. I was nervous because I am not the fastest runner. When the <b>gun</b> fired, I ran as fast as I could. I <b>heard</b> my classmates shouting my name. I finished fourth. I did not get a medal, but my friends cheered for me. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>The second event was the class relay race. I was the third runner. I took the baton and ran <b class=\"gs\">with</b> all my strength. I passed one runner from another class. Then I handed the baton to our <b class=\"gs\">last</b> runner. He was very fast and brought us to second place. Our whole class jumped <b class=\"gs\">with</b> joy. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>Sports Day is not just about winning. It is about trying your best and helping <b class=\"gs\">each other</b>. I saw a <b>boy</b> fall during a race. Students from different classes ran to help him. I saw teachers clapping for every runner. At the end, everyone was tired but happy. I am <b>already</b> looking forward to next year. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p>"}},{"name":"季节与穿衣","entries":[{"cn":"的复数形式","en":"shirts","type":"word"},{"cn":"呼吸","en":"breathe","type":"word"},{"cn":"毛衣","en":"sweater","type":"word"},{"cn":"棉布﹔棉纱；棉株〔植物〕","en":"cotton","type":"word"},{"cn":"短上衣，茄克衫","en":"jacket","type":"word"},{"cn":"牛仔裤","en":"jeans","type":"word"},{"cn":"围巾；头巾","en":"scarf","type":"word"},{"cn":"厚的；浓的","en":"thick","type":"word"},{"cn":"帽子","en":"hat","type":"word"}],"passage":{"title":"Seasons and Clothing","html":"<p>The city where I live has four different seasons. Spring is warm and windy. Summer is hot and wet. Autumn is cool and dry. Winter is cold <b class=\"gs\">with</b> some snow. Because the weather changes so much, people wear different clothes in different seasons. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>In spring, I usually wear a light <b>jacket</b> or a thin <b>sweater</b>. The mornings are chilly, but by noon it gets warm. I like bright colours in spring because flowers are blooming and everything feels fresh. I carry a small umbrella in my schoolbag. Spring rain can come suddenly. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>Summer is very hot here. The temperature often goes above thirty-five degrees. I wear T-<b>shirts</b> and shorts <b class=\"gs\">most</b> of the time. <b>Cotton</b> clothes are best because they let the skin <b>breathe</b>. I wear a <b>hat</b> outside to protect myself from the sun. I change my clothes every day because I sweat a lot. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>Autumn is my favourite season for clothing. I wear long-sleeved <b>shirts</b> and <b>jeans</b>. I like clothes in brown, orange, and dark red. In winter, I <b class=\"gs\">put on</b> my <b>thick</b> coat, <b>scarf</b>, and g<b class=\"gs\">love</b>s. My grandmother makes me wear long underwear too. I <b class=\"gs\">used to</b> think it was old-fashioned. Now I understand why. Dressing right for the season keeps us healthy. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p>"}},{"name":"买新衣服","entries":[{"cn":"昂贵的","en":"expensive","type":"word"}],"passage":{"title":"Buying New Clothes","html":"<p>A few weeks ago, my mother noticed that my trousers had become too short. During the <b class=\"gs\">last</b> few months, I had grown a lot taller. My school uniform still fit, but my casual clothes looked funny. <b class=\"gs\">Last</b> Sunday afternoon, my mother and I went to buy some new clothes. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>The store is <b class=\"gs\">on the</b> third floor of a big shopping centre. There were racks of shirts, trousers, and jackets everywhere. I felt a little lost <b class=\"gs\">at first</b>. There were so many choices. My mother told me to <b class=\"gs\">focus on</b> what I really needed. She said not to buy something just because it looks nice. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>I tried on several pairs of trousers. The first was too tight. The second was too long. The third fit perfectly. They were dark blue jeans. I also chose two T-shirts. One was plain white and the other had a blue stripe. My mother suggested a light jacket for cooler evenings. We found a grey one that matched everything. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>Shopping took al<b class=\"gs\">most</b> two hours. When we finished, we had juice at a café. I was happy <b class=\"gs\">with</b> our choices. The new clothes were simple, comfortable, and not <b>expensive</b>. My mother was happy I did not <b class=\"gs\">ask for</b> <b>expensive</b> brands. She said I was becoming a sensible young person. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p>"}},{"name":"文具店","entries":[{"cn":"图片，画片，照片；影片","en":"picture","type":"word"},{"cn":"兴趣,嗜好","en":"hobby","type":"word"},{"cn":"拥有者；物主","en":"owner","type":"word"},{"cn":"生气的，愤怒的","en":"angry","type":"word"},{"cn":"进入;参加","en":"enter","type":"word"},{"cn":"女士；夫人","en":"lady","type":"word"},{"cn":"钢笔；笔","en":"pen","type":"word"}],"passage":{"title":"At the Stationery Shop","html":"<p>Not far from my school, there is a small stationery shop named Morning Star. It is my favourite place to go after school. The shop looks small from outside, but inside it is full of wonderful things. The shelves go up to the ceiling. They are packed <b class=\"gs\">with</b> notebooks, pens, pencils, rulers, and stickers. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>I visit the shop <b class=\"gs\">at least</b> twice a week. Sometimes I need something useful, like a notebook or tape. But often, I just look around. The <b>owner</b> is a kind old <b>lady</b>. She knows <b class=\"gs\">most</b> young customers by name. When I <b>enter</b>, she smiles. She never gets <b>angry</b> when students browse. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>The best part is the wall of pens. There are pens of every colour. Some are gel pens, some are ballpoint pens. I collect pens as a small <b>hobby</b>. Over the past year, I have collected eighteen of them. My newest one is a green <b>pen</b> that writes smoothly. I use it <b class=\"gs\">in English</b> class. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>The shop also sells water bottles, <b class=\"gs\">lunch</b> boxes, and small gifts. <b class=\"gs\">Last</b> month, I bought a birthday card for my mother there. It had a <b>picture</b> of a cat. She <b class=\"gs\">love</b>d it. For me, the stationery shop is <b class=\"gs\">more than</b> a place to buy things. It is a warm and friendly part of my daily life. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p>"}},{"name":"网上购物","entries":[{"cn":"确切地;(表示赞同的回答)确实如此","en":"exactly","type":"word"},{"cn":"高兴的；喜欢的；乐意做某事 v. 满意；愿意（please的过去分词形式）","en":"pleased","type":"word"},{"cn":"保护（save的过去分词）；救助 adj. 获救的；已保存的","en":"saved","type":"word"}],"passage":{"title":"Shopping Online","html":"<p>These days, many people shop online. My mother uses her phone to buy things <b class=\"gs\">with</b>out leaving home. <b class=\"gs\">At first</b>, I did not understand why it was popular. I thought real shops were more fun. But <b class=\"gs\">last</b> month, my mother showed me how it worked. Now I see it can be useful. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>A week ago, I needed a new schoolbag. My old one had a broken strap. We opened a shopping application and typed in the search. In seconds, hundreds of schoolbags appeared. There were bags of many colours, sizes, and styles. It would have taken hours to see so many in a real shop. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>We looked at several bags carefully. We read the descriptions and buyer reviews. Some buyers said a bag's colour was different from the picture. Others said a bag was strong and <b class=\"gs\">last</b>ed a long time. The reviews helped us choose. <b class=\"gs\">In the end</b>, we chose a dark blue bag <b class=\"gs\">with</b> a padded back. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>The bag arrived three days later in a box. I was <b>pleased</b> when I opened it. It was <b>exactly</b> as pictured. It felt strong and comfortable. The price was lower than in a store. Online shopping <b>saved</b> us time and money. I still like real shops. But now I know online shopping is a good choice too. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p>"}},{"name":"跳蚤市场","entries":[{"cn":"卖，销售（sell的过去式和过去分词） n. (Sold)人名；(瑞典)索尔德","en":"sold","type":"word"},{"cn":"机器人","en":"robot","type":"word"},{"cn":"同班同学","en":"classmate","type":"word"},{"cn":"玩具","en":"toy","type":"word"},{"cn":"机会","en":"chance","type":"word"},{"cn":"卖；出售","en":"sell","type":"word"}],"passage":{"title":"A Flea Market","html":"<p><b class=\"gs\">Last</b> Saturday, our school held a flea market in the playground. Students brought things they <b class=\"gs\">no longer</b> needed to <b>sell</b>. The school wanted us to learn about reusing things. It was also a <b>chance</b> to learn about buying and selling. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>On Saturday morning, the playground was full of colour and noise. Students set up tables or laid blankets <b class=\"gs\">on the</b> ground. Each seller had a different collection. Some <b>sold</b> old books. Others <b>sold</b> toys, sports gear, or handmade items. I brought ten books I had already read and a <b>toy</b> <b>robot</b>. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p><b class=\"gs\">At first</b>, I was shy to call out to passing students. But soon I saw everyone was having fun. I started calling out like the others. Before noon, I <b>sold</b> seven of my ten books. A younger student bought three for twenty yuan. The <b>toy</b> <b>robot</b> was bought by a boy who collected robots. He paid me fifteen yuan. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p><b class=\"gs\">With</b> the money, I walked around. I bought two second-hand novels for ten yuan. They looked al<b class=\"gs\">most</b> new. I also bought a wooden puzzle box from a <b>classmate</b>. The flea market was a great experience. I learned that things I <b class=\"gs\">no longer</b> need can be useful to others. I also learned that selling takes courage and a friendly smile. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p>"}},{"name":"坐公交上学","entries":[{"cn":"医院","en":"hospital","type":"word"},{"cn":"司机,驾驶员","en":"driver","type":"word"}],"passage":{"title":"Taking the Bus to School","html":"<p>Every morning I take the No. 5 bus to school. I <b class=\"gs\">get up</b> at six thirty, wash my face, e<b class=\"gs\">at breakfast</b>, and then walk to the bus stop. The bus stop is only five minutes from my home. I usually wait there with some other students. We all know <b class=\"gs\">each other</b> because we take the same bus every day. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>The bus comes at about seven o'clock. It is often crowded in the morning. Many people are going to work and many students are going to school. I try to find a seat near the window. If there is no seat, I stand and hold the handrail. The ride takes about twenty minutes. I like to <b class=\"gs\">look out</b> the window and watch the city <b class=\"gs\">wake up</b>. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p><b class=\"gs\">On the</b> way, the bus passes a park, a big supermarket, and a <b>hospital</b>. I see people walking their dogs, shop owners opening their stores, and children riding bikes. Sometimes my friend Li Wei gets <b class=\"gs\">on the</b> bus at the third stop. We <b class=\"gs\">talk about</b> homework, sports, and our favorite movies. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>The bus drops me off right <b class=\"gs\">in front of</b> my school. I <b class=\"gs\">get off</b>, say goodbye to the <b>driver</b>, and walk through the school gate. Taking the bus is a simple part of my day, but I enjoy it. It gives me time to relax and <b class=\"gs\">get ready for</b> my classes. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p>"}},{"name":"一次旅行","entries":[{"cn":"旅行；旅程","en":"trip","type":"word"},{"cn":"停止；停下来（stop的过去式和过去分词） adj. 停止的；停顿的","en":"stopped","type":"word"},{"cn":"拜访，访问（visit的过去式）","en":"visited","type":"word"},{"cn":"野餐","en":"picnic","type":"word"},{"cn":"旅馆,宾馆","en":"hotel","type":"word"},{"cn":"小山","en":"hill","type":"word"},{"cn":"湖","en":"lake","type":"word"},{"cn":"小汽车","en":"car","type":"word"}],"passage":{"title":"A Trip","html":"<p><b class=\"gs\">Last</b> summer my family went on a <b>trip</b> to a mountain town. It was the first time I had traveled <b class=\"gs\">so far</b> from home. We packed our bags the night before and left early in the morning. My father drove the <b>car</b> and my mother sat in the front seat. I sat in the back <b class=\"gs\">with</b> my little sister. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>The drive took about four hours. <b class=\"gs\">On the</b> way we saw green fields, tall trees, and blue rivers. We <b>stopped</b> once at a small shop to buy water and snacks. My sister and I played word games to pass the time. The road went higher and higher into the mountains. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>When we arrived, the air felt cool and fresh. We stayed in a small <b>hotel</b> near a <b>lake</b>. <b class=\"gs\">On the</b> first day we went for a walk by the water. <b class=\"gs\">On the</b> second day we climbed a <b>hill</b> and had a <b>picnic</b> at the top. The view was wonderful. <b class=\"gs\">On the</b> third day we <b>visited</b> an old temple and learned about its history. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>It was a short <b>trip</b> but a very happy one. I took many photos <b class=\"gs\">with</b> my phone. At night we sat outside and looked at the stars. There were so many more stars than I could see in the city. I will never forget that <b>trip</b>. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p>"}},{"name":"在机场","entries":[{"cn":"机场","en":"airport","type":"word"},{"cn":"飞机","en":"plane","type":"word"},{"cn":"上海（中国东部港市）","en":"shanghai","type":"word"},{"cn":"巨大的;庞大的","en":"huge","type":"word"},{"cn":"拥抱","en":"hug","type":"word"}],"passage":{"title":"At the Airport","html":"<p>My uncle was flying in from <b>Shanghai</b>, and I went to the <b>airport</b> <b class=\"gs\">with</b> my parents to meet him. It was my first time at the <b>airport</b>. The building was <b>huge</b> and full of people. I felt a little lost <b class=\"gs\">at first</b>, but my father held my hand and led the way. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>We first checked the big screen to <b class=\"gs\">find out</b> when my uncle's <b class=\"gs\">plane</b> would land. It said the <b class=\"gs\">plane</b> was <b class=\"gs\">on time</b>. We had about forty minutes to wait. We walked around the shops and looked at books, snacks, and gifts. I sat near the window and watched the <b class=\"gs\">plane</b>s <b class=\"gs\">take off</b> and land. It was amazing how such big machines could fly in the sky. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>Soon it was time to go to the arrival gate. Many people were standing there, waiting for their family and friends. Some held flowers. Others held signs <b class=\"gs\">with</b> names <b class=\"gs\">on the</b>m. I felt excited and kept looking at the door, hoping to see my uncle. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>Finally, my uncle walked out <b class=\"gs\">with</b> a big smile on his face. He waved at us, and I ran to give him a <b>hug</b>. He looked tired but happy. He said he had brought gifts for me and my sister. We walked to the car together. I was so glad to see him <b class=\"gs\">again</b>. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p>"}},{"name":"问路","entries":[{"cn":"街道","en":"street","type":"word"},{"cn":"指出；瞄准（point的过去式） adj. 尖的；突出的；锐利的；率直的","en":"pointed","type":"word"},{"cn":"原谅；宽恕","en":"excuse","type":"word"},{"cn":"妇女；女人","en":"woman","type":"word"},{"cn":"邮政；邮寄；邮件","en":"post","type":"word"}],"passage":{"title":"Asking for Directions","html":"<p>One Sunday afternoon my friend and I wanted to visit a new bookstore in town. We knew it was on Park <b>Street</b>, but we were not sure how to get there. We did not have a phone <b class=\"gs\">with</b> a map, so we had to <b class=\"gs\">ask for</b> directions. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>We first stopped an old <b>woman</b> who was walking her dog. We said, \"<b>Excuse</b> me, can you tell us how to <b class=\"gs\">get to</b> Park <b>Street</b>?\" She smiled and <b>pointed</b> to the right. \"Go straight down this road,\" she said. \"Then turn left at the second crossing. Park <b>Street</b> is the third <b>street</b> on your right.\" We thanked her and followed her directions. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>We walked for about ten minutes but still could not find the bookstore. The <b>street</b> names were hard to see. We decided to ask <b class=\"gs\">again</b>. This time we asked a young man carrying a shopping bag. He told us we had missed the turn. \"Go back one block and you will see a red <b>post</b> office. The bookstore is right <b class=\"gs\">next to</b> it.\" <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>Following his clear directions, we quickly found the place. It was a small, cozy bookstore <b class=\"gs\">with</b> many books in the window. We thanked the man and went inside. I learned that it is okay to <b class=\"gs\">ask for</b> help when you are lost. <b class=\"gs\">Most</b> people are kind and happy to give directions. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p>"}},{"name":"参观博物馆","entries":[{"cn":"博物馆","en":"museum","type":"word"},{"cn":"什么事(物)；任何事(物)","en":"anything","type":"word"},{"cn":"士兵；军人","en":"soldier","type":"word"},{"cn":"油漆；粉刷；绘画 油漆；涂料；颜料","en":"paint","type":"word"},{"cn":"触摸；接触","en":"touch","type":"word"},{"cn":"海；海洋","en":"sea","type":"word"}],"passage":{"title":"Visiting a Museum","html":"<p><b class=\"gs\">Last</b> Friday our school took us to the city <b>museum</b>. We went there on a big yellow school bus. Everyone was excited because we do not <b class=\"gs\">go on</b> field trips very often. Our teacher told us to stay together and not to <b>touch</b> <b>anything</b> in the <b>museum</b>. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>The <b>museum</b> was a large old building <b class=\"gs\">with</b> tall stone pillars at the front. Inside, it was quiet and cool. We first went to the history hall. There were old pots, tools, and clothes from hundreds of years ago. I saw a real sword that a <b>soldier</b> once used. Our guide told us stories about how people lived long ago. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>Next we visited the art hall. There were beautiful paintings <b class=\"gs\">on the</b> walls. Some showed mountains and rivers. Others showed people and animals. My favorite painting was of a golden sunset over the <b>sea</b>. I stood <b class=\"gs\">in front of</b> it for a long time, wishing I could <b>paint</b> like that someday. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>Finally we went to the science hall. There we saw dinosaur bones, rocks from space, and machines that showed how electricity works. We could press buttons and turn wheels. When the trip ended, I did not want to leave. I hope we can visit <b class=\"gs\">again</b> sometime. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p>"}},{"name":"春节","entries":[{"cn":"运气；好运","en":"luck","type":"word"},{"cn":"子夜﹐午夜","en":"midnight","type":"word"},{"cn":"(节日的)前夜,前夕","en":"eve","type":"word"}],"passage":{"title":"Spring Festival","html":"<p>Spring Festival is the <b class=\"gs\">most</b> important holiday in China. My whole family looks forward to it every year. A few days before the festival, we clean the house from top to bottom. My mother says cleaning sweeps away bad <b>luck</b> and makes room for good <b>luck</b> in the new year. We also <b class=\"gs\">put up</b> red paper cuttings and spring couplets <b class=\"gs\">on the</b> doors. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>On New Year's <b>Eve</b>, the whole family gathers for a big dinner. My grandmother cooks many delicious dishes, including fish, dumplings, and rice cakes. Fish is a must because it means having plenty every year. After dinner we watch the Spring Festival Gala on television. We talk, laugh, and eat snacks until <b>midnight</b>. When the clock strikes twelve, we hear firecrackers and see fireworks light up the sky. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>On New Year's Day, I <b class=\"gs\">wake up</b> early and <b class=\"gs\">put on</b> my new clothes. I say \"Happy New Year\" to my parents and grandparents. They give me red envelopes <b class=\"gs\">with</b> lucky money inside. This is my favorite part of the festival. Then we visit our relatives and friends to share good wishes. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>The celebration <b class=\"gs\">last</b>s for many days. We eat and play and enjoy the holiday break from school. Spring Festival is about family, <b class=\"gs\">love</b>, and hope. I always feel warm and happy during this special time of year. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p>"}},{"name":"中秋节","entries":[{"cn":"九月","en":"september","type":"word"},{"cn":"感谢的；欣慰的","en":"thankful","type":"word"},{"cn":"十月","en":"october","type":"word"}],"passage":{"title":"Mid-Autumn Festival","html":"<p>Mid-Autumn Festival comes in <b>September</b> or <b>October</b> when the moon is at its fullest and brightest. It is a time for family reunions. On this day, my family and I always <b class=\"gs\">get to</b>gether at my grandparents' home. My aunts, uncles, and cousins come too. The house is full of laughter and happy voices. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>In the evening, we have a special dinner together. We eat dishes made <b class=\"gs\">with</b> seasonal foods like crab, pumpkin, and lotus root. After dinner, we <b class=\"gs\">go out</b>side to <b class=\"gs\">look at</b> the moon. My grandfather tells us the story of Chang'e, the lady who lives <b class=\"gs\">on the</b> moon, and her rabbit companion. I have heard the story many times, but I still enjoy it every year. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>Then we eat mooncakes. Mooncakes are round and sweet, just like the full moon. Some have red bean paste inside, and others have egg yolk. My favorite is the one <b class=\"gs\">with</b> lotus seed paste. My grandmother always buys a big box <b class=\"gs\">with</b> different flavors so everyone can choose what they like. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>Looking at the bright moon, I <b class=\"gs\">think about</b> people who cannot be <b class=\"gs\">with</b> their families on this day. The festival reminds me to be <b>thankful</b> for the people I <b class=\"gs\">love</b>. The round moon and round mooncakes <b class=\"gs\">stand for</b> togetherness and completeness. It is a beautiful tradition. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p>"}},{"name":"圣诞节","entries":[{"cn":"圣诞节","en":"christmas","type":"word"},{"cn":"赠品；礼物","en":"gift","type":"word"},{"cn":"塑料的","en":"plastic","type":"word"},{"cn":"覆盖；遮盖  盖子；罩；封面","en":"cover","type":"word"}],"passage":{"title":"Christmas","html":"<p><b>Christmas</b> is not a traditional Chinese holiday, but many young people enjoy celebrating it. <b class=\"gs\">Last</b> year my friends and I decided to have a small <b>Christmas</b> party at my house. We spent a whole afternoon decorating. We <b class=\"gs\">put up</b> a small p<b class=\"gs\">last</b>ic tree and hung colorful lights around the living room. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>On <b>Christmas</b> Eve, my friends arrived one by one. Each person brought a small <b>gift</b> wrapped in bright paper. We put all the gifts under the tree. We played <b>Christmas</b> songs <b class=\"gs\">on the</b> speaker and sang along. Some of us knew the English words, and some just hummed the tune. We also watched a funny <b>Christmas</b> <b class=\"gs\">movie</b> and ate popcorn. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>The best part was the <b>gift</b> exchange. We wrote numbers on pieces of paper and put them in a hat. Each person picked a number and took the matching <b>gift</b>. I got a soft green scarf from my best friend Mei. I gave a small notebook <b class=\"gs\">with</b> a cat <b class=\"gs\">on the</b> <b>cover</b> to another friend. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>Although <b>Christmas</b> is a Western holiday, the spirit of giving and sharing <b class=\"gs\">with</b> friends is something anyone can enjoy. That evening I felt close to my friends. We promised to do it <b class=\"gs\">again</b> next year. For me, <b>Christmas</b> has become a time to show my friends I care. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p>"}},{"name":"儿童节","entries":[{"cn":"人群","en":"crowd","type":"word"},{"cn":"六月","en":"june","type":"word"},{"cn":"可爱的；漂亮迷人的","en":"cute","type":"word"},{"cn":"(铃)响；打电话 戒指；铃声","en":"ring","type":"word"},{"cn":"的过去式和过去分词","en":"won","type":"word"}],"passage":{"title":"Children's Day","html":"<p>Children's Day is on <b>June</b> the first, and it is one of my favorite days of the year. On that day, there is no school. Instead, my school holds a big celebration. The whole campus is decorated <b class=\"gs\">with</b> balloons and colorful flags. Everyone comes in their best clothes, and there is an exciting feeling in the air. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>The day starts <b class=\"gs\">with</b> a short show. Students sing songs, dance, and perform short plays <b class=\"gs\">on the</b> school stage. <b class=\"gs\">Last</b> year my class did a traditional Chinese dance. We practiced for weeks before the big day. When we finished, the <b>crowd</b> clapped loudly. I felt so proud. After the show, the principal gives a speech and wishes all the students a happy Children's Day. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>Then the fun really begins. The school sets up game booths <b class=\"gs\">all over</b> the playground. There are <b>ring</b> toss games, guessing games, and relay races. Students can win small prizes like pencils, erasers, and candies. I tried al<b class=\"gs\">most</b> every game and <b>won</b> a <b>cute</b> little notebook. We ran from booth to booth, laughing and cheering. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>In the afternoon, I <b class=\"gs\">go home</b> and my parents usually have a small <b class=\"gs\">surprise</b> for me. Sometimes it is a new book, sometimes a toy, and sometimes we <b class=\"gs\">go out</b> for ice cream. Children's Day makes me feel special and <b class=\"gs\">love</b>d. I am already looking forward to the next one. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p>"}},{"name":"学校艺术节","entries":[{"cn":"最大的（big的最高级）","en":"biggest","type":"word"},{"cn":"照耀；发光；发亮","en":"shine","type":"word"}],"passage":{"title":"The School Art Festival","html":"<p>Every spring our school holds an art festival. It <b class=\"gs\">last</b>s for three days and is one of the <b>biggest</b> events of the year. Students from all grades take part. There are singing competitions, painting shows, handwriting displays, and drama performances. The campus becomes a colorful and lively place. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>My favorite part is the painting and calligraphy show. The school hallway is turned into a gallery. Paintings by students are hung <b class=\"gs\">on the</b> walls. Some are watercolors, some are oil paintings, and some are simple pencil sketches. I like to walk slowly and <b class=\"gs\">look at</b> each piece. <b class=\"gs\">Last</b> year my painting of a sunset river won third prize. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>The singing competition is also very popular. Students sing alone or in groups <b class=\"gs\">on the</b> big stage in the school hall. The lights <b>shine</b> brightly and the music fills the room. I am too shy to sing <b class=\"gs\">in front of</b> so many people, but I <b class=\"gs\">love</b> to sit in the audience and listen. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>The art festival brings the whole school together. It lets us show our talents and appreciate the talents of others. It also gives us a break from our usual studies. I think every school should have an art festival. It helps us grow in ways that books alone cannot. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p>"}},{"name":"道歉","entries":[{"cn":"对不起的；抱歉的","en":"sorry","type":"word"},{"cn":"道歉","en":"apologize","type":"word"},{"cn":"发生（happen的过去式，过去分词）","en":"happened","type":"word"},{"cn":"可装配为木箱的各个部件；一捆；（英）禾束堆 v. 摇动（shake的过去式） adj. 受到严重打击的；心绪不宁的 n. (Shook)人名；(英)舒克","en":"shook","type":"word"}],"passage":{"title":"Saying Sorry","html":"<p>Everyone makes mistakes. I have made my share, and one of them taught me how important it is to say <b>sorry</b>. It <b>happened</b> <b class=\"gs\">last</b> year <b class=\"gs\">with</b> my best friend, Zhang Wei. We had been friends since primary school and did al<b class=\"gs\">most</b> everything together. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>One day we had a big argument over something small. We were working on a group project, and I thought he was not doing his part. I got angry and said some unkind words. He got angry too. We did not speak to <b class=\"gs\">each other</b> for three days after that. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>Those three days were very hard. I missed talking and laughing <b class=\"gs\">with</b> him. I knew I should <b>apologize</b>, but I was too proud <b class=\"gs\">at first</b>. My mother noticed I was quiet and asked what was wrong. When I told her, she said, \"A true friend knows how to say <b>sorry</b>. It takes more courage to <b>apologize</b> than to stay angry.\" <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p><b class=\"gs\">On the</b> fourth day, I walked up to Zhang Wei after class. I said, \"I am <b>sorry</b> for what I said. It was wrong. Can we be friends <b class=\"gs\">again</b>?\" He looked at me and smiled. \"I am <b>sorry</b> too,\" he said. We <b>shook</b> hands and everything was okay <b class=\"gs\">again</b>. I learned that saying <b>sorry</b> does not make you weak. It makes you a better person and a better friend. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p>"}},{"name":"收到礼物","entries":[{"cn":"失踪的；缺少的 v. 错过（miss的ing形式）；想念；漏掉 n. (Missing)人名；(德)米辛","en":"missing","type":"word"},{"cn":"信；字母","en":"letter","type":"word"}],"passage":{"title":"Receiving a Gift","html":"<p>A gift does not <b class=\"gs\">have to</b> be big or expensive to be special. The best gift I ever received was small and simple, but it meant the world to me. It was a handmade bookmark from my little cousin, Xiaomei. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>It was my birthday, and my family had a small party <b class=\"gs\">at home</b>. There was a cake, some snacks, and a few balloons. Many relatives came, and everyone brought gifts. I got books, clothes, and a new pair of shoes. I was happy <b class=\"gs\">with</b> all of them. Then Xiaomei came up to me <b class=\"gs\">with</b> something in her small hands. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>She handed me a rectangle of thick paper. On it, she had drawn a sun, some flowers, and a rainbow <b class=\"gs\">with</b> colored pencils. The drawing was not perfect. Across the top, she had written \"Happy Brithday\" <b class=\"gs\">with</b> a <b>missing</b> <b>letter</b>. She had added a ribbon at the top to make it a bookmark. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>I al<b class=\"gs\">most</b> cried when I saw it. She had spent a long time making it, giving me her time and her <b class=\"gs\">love</b>. No store could sell something like that. Even now, I still use that bookmark. Every time I see it, I remember her sweet face and the <b class=\"gs\"><b class=\"gs\">less</b>on</b> she taught me: the best gifts <b class=\"gs\">come from</b> the heart. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p>"}},{"name":"帮助他人","entries":[{"cn":"奶奶;外婆","en":"grandma","type":"word"},{"cn":"苹果","en":"apple","type":"word"}],"passage":{"title":"Helping Others","html":"<p>One Saturday morning, I was walking home from the market <b class=\"gs\">with</b> a shopping bag. I was looking forward to getting home and having a cold drink. As I turned a corner, I saw something that made me stop. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>An elderly woman was struggling <b class=\"gs\">with</b> a heavy shopping cart. The wheel had gotten stuck in a crack <b class=\"gs\">on the</b> sidewalk. She was trying hard to pull it free, but she was not strong enough. She looked tired. Other people walked by, but no one stopped to help. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>I did not think twice. I put down my bag and went over to her. \"Let me help you, <b>grandma</b>,\" I said. I lifted the cart just enough to free the stuck wheel. Then I asked her where she was going. She lived about two blocks away, so I pushed the cart for her. She smiled and thanked me many times. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>When we reached her home, she wanted to give me some fruit. I said no, but she insisted, so I took a small <b>apple</b>. Walking back, I felt a warm glow in my heart. Helping her took only ten minutes, but it made my whole day meaningful. A small act of kindness can make a big difference. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p>"}},{"name":"感到紧张","entries":[{"cn":"/ ***everyone** /ˈevriwʌn/ 每人,人人","en":"everybody","type":"word"},{"cn":"票；入场券","en":"ticket","type":"word"},{"cn":"文件；证件；论文数 n. (Papers)人名；(希)帕佩尔斯","en":"papers","type":"word"}],"passage":{"title":"Feeling Nervous","html":"<p><b>Everybody</b> feels nervous sometimes. For me, the <b class=\"gs\">most</b> nervous I have ever been was <b class=\"gs\">on the</b> day of my middle school entrance exam. I had studied for months and done many practice questions. When the day came, my heart beat so fast I could feel it in my ears. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>That morning I woke up very early. I checked my bag three times to <b class=\"gs\">make sure</b> I had my admission <b>ticket</b>, pens, and pencils. <b class=\"gs\">At breakfast</b> I could hardly eat. My mother told me to take deep breaths. \"You have prepared well,\" she said. \"Just go and do your best.\" Her words helped a little. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>The exam room was very quiet. All the students sat at their desks <b class=\"gs\">with</b> serious faces. When the teacher handed out the <b>papers</b>, my mind went blank for a few seconds. I closed my eyes, took a deep breath, and told myself to <b class=\"gs\">calm down</b>. Slowly the words came back to me. I started writing, and the nervous feeling began to fade. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>When the exam was over, I walked out feeling light and free. My parents were waiting for me outside. They did not ask me how I did. They just gave me a hug. I learned that feeling nervous is normal. What matters is not letting it stop you from doing what you need to do. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p>"}},{"name":"感恩的心","entries":[],"passage":{"title":"A Grateful Heart","html":"<p>When I look back on my life, I see many things to be grateful for. First, I <b class=\"gs\">think of</b> my family. My parents work very hard every day to give my sister and me a good life. They may not say \"I <b class=\"gs\">love</b> you\" often, but their <b class=\"gs\">love</b> shows in everything they do. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>My father wakes up before the sun to go to work. Even when he is tired, he always asks about my day. My mother takes care of the house and still finds time to help me <b class=\"gs\">with</b> my homework. My grandparents teach me old stories and values not found in any schoolbook. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>I am also grateful for my teachers. They give their time and energy to help me learn and grow. When I struggle <b class=\"gs\">with</b> a subject, they stay after class to explain it <b class=\"gs\">again</b>. My friends, too, are a big part of my life. We share joys and sadness together. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p><p>Having a grateful heart does not mean my life is perfect. I have problems like anyone else. But when I <b class=\"gs\">focus on</b> the good things I have <b class=\"gs\">instead of</b> the things I do not have, I feel peaceful and strong. I want to remember this feeling and one day give back the same <b class=\"gs\">love</b> and care to the people around me. <span class=\"passage-play\" onclick=\"speakParagraph(this)\" title=\"朗读本段\">🔊</span></p>"}}]};